<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoxOffice     03-21 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Police Academy' Blocks For `Good Morning, Vietnam' from Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Police Academy 5: Assignment Miami Beach,''
grabbed first place in weekend box office receipts, dislodging
``Good Morning, Vietnam'' after nine weeks at the top and
preventing it from setting a record.
   ``Police Academy 5'' from Warner Bros. earned $6.1 million in
its debut weekend, while Disney-Touchstone's ``Good Morning,
Vietnam,'' earned more than $4 million, falling to second. The
Robin Williams comedy's nine-straight weekends as the most nation's
popular movie equaled the longest consecutive hold on No. 1 set in
1986 by the comedy ``Crocodile Dundee.''
   The latest ``Police Academy'' sequel features the whole wacky
crew in Miami for a police convention.
   Another debut movie, ``D.O.A.'' was third with $3.7 million in
ticket sales. The Disney-Touchstone film stars Dennis Quaid and Meg
Ryan in a remake of the 1949 thriller of the same name. Quaid plays
a poisoned college professor who has 24 hours to find his killer
before he dies.
   Disney-Touchstone has four of the 10-top, while MGM-UA and
Warner Bros. each have two.
   In fourth place was the father-son role switch movie ``Vice
Versa,'' which sold $3 million in tickets, while ``Masquerade,''
about the romance between an heiress and a scheming yachtsman
earned $2.7 million, good for fifth place.
   Cher's ``Moonstruck'' earned $2.3 million for sixth place. Its
writer, John Patrick Shanley, won the Writers Guild of America's
honor for best original screenplay last week. The movie has been
nominated for six Academy Awards.
   ``Three Men and A Baby'' was in seventh place with $2.1 million,
and reached a $150.6 million cumulative gross.
   ``Off Limits,'' a story about two military undercover officers
trying to solve a series of prostitute murders in Saigon during the
Vietnam War, earned $1.58 million for eighth place.
   In ninth was Roman Polanski's ``Frantic'' with $1.50 million,
followed by ``Shoot To Kill,'' with $1.4 million.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release, and estimated production costs when available.
   1. ``Police Academy 5: Assignment Miami Beach,'' Warner Bros.,
$6.1 million, 1,700 screens, $3,592 per screen, $6.1 million, one
week, n-a.
   2. ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' Disney-Touchstone, $4 million,
1,523 screens, $2,647 per screen, $96.6 million, 12 weeks, $21
million.
   3. ``D.O.A.,'' Disney-Touchstone, $3.7 million, 875 screens,
$4,287 per screen, $3.7 million, one week, n-a.
   4. ``Vice Versa,'' Columbia, $3 million, 1,225 theaters, $2,503
per screen, $7.9 million, two weeks, n-a.
   5. ``Masquerade,'' MGM-UA, $2.7 million, 1,031 theaters, $2,663
per screen, $7.6 million, two weeks, n-a.
   6. ``Moonstruck,'' MGM-UA, $2.3 million, 1,124 theaters, $2,068
per screen, $52.6 million, 13 weeks, $17 million.
   7. ``Three Men And A Baby,'' Disney-Touchstone, $2.1 million,
1,162 theaters, $1,866 per screen, $150.6 million, 16 weeks, $18
million.
   8. ``Off Limits,'' 20th Century Fox, $1.58 million, 1,371
theaters, $1,155 per screen, $5.4 million, two weeks, n-a.
   9. ``Frantic,'' Warner Bros., $1.5 million, 842 theaters, $1,788
per screen, $15.4 million, three weeks, n-a.
   10. ``Shoot To Kill,'' Disney-Touchstone, $1.4 million, 893
theaters, $1,610 per screen, $26.3 million, five weeks, $18 million.
</TEXT>
