<2ND_LINE>AM-Box Office, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0813,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Police Academy' Arrests No. 1 Spot In Box Office Parade</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT that `Good Morning, Vietnam' in
first place for nine sted 11 weeks; SUBS 6-7th grafs, bgng `In
fourth..', to CORRECT that `Moonstruck' in sixth, sted fifth place,
add that `Masquerade' in fifth place. Picks up 8th graf, `The
Tom...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Police Academy 5: Assignment Miami Beach,''
signaled the first success of the spring break movies by kicking
``Good Morning, Vietnam'' out of its long-held No. 1 position in
the weekend national box office.
   ``Police Academy 5'' from Warner Bros. earned $6.1 million at
1,700 screens over the weekend, while Disney-Touchstone's ``Good
Morning, Vietnam,'' earned more than $4 million and fell to second.
It held first place for nine weeks.
   The latest ``Police Academy'' movie features the whole wacky
crew in Miami for a police convention.
   Another debut movie, ``D.O.A.,'' earned third place with $3.7
million in ticket sales. The debut Disney-Touchstone film stars
Dennis Quaid and Meg Ryan in a remake of the 1949 thriller of the
same name. Quaid plays a fatally poisoned college professor who has
24 hours to find his killer before he dies.
   The arrival of ``D.O.A.'' in the Top 10 list gives
Disney-Touchstone four of the films on the list, while MGM-UA and
Warner Bros. each have two.
   In fourth place was the father-son role switch movie ``Vice
Versa,'' which sold $3 million in tickets, while ``Masquerade,''
about the romance between an heiress and a scheming yachtsman,
earned $2.7 million for fifth place.
   Cher's romantic comedy ``Moonstruck'' earned $2.7 million for
sixth place. Its writer, John Patrick Shanley, won the Writers
Guild of America's honor for best original screenplay last week.
The movie has been nominated for six Academy Awards.
   The Tom Selleck-Ted Danson comedy ``Three Men and A Baby'' was
in seventh place with $2.1 million, and reached a $150.6 million
cumulative gross that outdistanced the Michael Douglas-Glenn Close
thriller ``Fatal Attraction,'' which has earned more than $149
million in six months of release. ``Three Men'' earned its gross in
just 16 weeks.
   ``Off Limits,'' a story about two military undercover officers
trying to solve a series of prostitute murders in Saigon during the
Vietnam War, earned $1.58 million.
   In ninth place was director Roman Polanski's missing-person
thriller ``Frantic'' with $1.50 million, followed by Sidney
Poitier's crime story ``Shoot To Kill,'' with $1.4 million.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release and estimated production costs.
   1. ``Police Academy 5: Assignment Miami Beach,'' Warner Bros.,
$6.1 million, 1,700 screens, $3,592 per screen, $6.1 million, one
week, not available.
   2. ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' Disney-Touchstone, $4 million,
1,523 screens, $2,647 per screen, $96.6 million, 12 weeks, $21
million.
   3. ``D.O.A.,'' Disney-Touchstone, $3.7 million, 875 screens,
$4,287 per screen, $3.7 million, one week, n-a.
   4. ``Vice Versa,'' Columbia, $3 million, 1,225 theaters, $2,503
per screen, $7.9 million, two weeks, n-a.
   5. ``Masquerade,'' MGM-UA, $2.7 million, 1,031 theaters, $2,663
per screen, $7.6 million, two weeks, n-a.
   6. ``Moonstruck,'' MGM-UA, $2.3 million, 1,124 theaters, $2,068
per screen, $52.6 million, 13 weeks, $17 million.
   7. ``Three Men And A Baby,'' Disney-Touchstone, $2.1 million,
1,162 theaters, $1,866 per screen, $150.6 million, 16 weeks, $18
million.
   8. ``Off Limits,'' 20th Century Fox, $1.58 million, 1,371
theaters, $1,155 per screen, $5.4 million, two weeks, n-a.
   9. ``Frantic,'' Warner Bros., $1.50 million, 842 theaters,
$1,788 per screen, $15.4 million, three weeks, n-a.
   10. ``Shoot To Kill,'' Disney-Touchstone, $1.4 million, 893
theaters, $1,610 per screen, $26.3 million, five weeks, $18 million.
</TEXT>
