<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru a0700 03-21 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0700,0852</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 400 People Arrested or Charged in Rioting in Caucasus
City</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with two Armenians named, march
figure. PICKS up 4th pvs, `On Feb. 28 ...' SUBS grafs 17-20 pvs,
`It was ...' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with names of Armenians
chastised, other detail.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 400 people have been arrested or charged
in murders, rapes, looting and acts of rioting in a southern Soviet
city divided by ethnic tensions, the prosecutor's office reported
Monday.
   The Communist Party daily Pravda said the territorial dispute
between the Soviet republics of Armenia and Azerbaijan that sparked
the unrest in Sumgait was caused by the ``clear anti-socialist
spirit'' of a campaign waged by militant Armenian leaders.
   In signs of continuing tension in the region, 7,000 people
reportedly staged a protest march in the Armenian capital, Yerevan,
and the official Tass news agency and Soviet television condemned
two of the Armenians by name.
   The Armenians are demanding the union of the predominantly
Armenian region of Nagorno-Karabakh, part of Azerbaijan since 1923,
with Armenia.
   On Feb. 28, after repeated demonstrations calling for union with
Armenia in Nagorno-Karabakh and Yerevan, rioting broke out in
Sumgait, an industrial city in Azerbaijan.
   Official Soviet accounts have said the victims were of various
nationalities, but Armenian sources said Armenians living in
Sumgait were sought out and killed by Azeris, members of the
predominantly ethnic group in Azerbaijan.
   Moscow-based journalists have been barred from traveling to the
Caucasus since unrest there began, and have been unable to verify
reports.
   The Soviet Prosecutor's Office, in a report distributed by Tass
Monday night, said 32 people ``of various nationalities'' were
killed in Sumgait, and 197, including about 100 policemen, were
injured.
   In addition, there were reports of 12 cases of rape, thefts at
more than 100 apartments, and damage to 26 stores and more than 20
motor vehicles, the prosecutor's office said.
   The report, which Tass said was complied by investigators from
the prosecutor's office, was the most complete official account of
the unrest to date.
   ``Most of those who took part in the murders, rape, assaults and
theft have been identified by now,'' the report said. ``Some of the
42 people who have been arrested have a criminal record.''
   In addition, 400 people have been brought to administrative
account for violations of public order, the report said. Soviet
police have the right to mete out fines and short jail terms for
minor offensives without recourse to the courts.
   The prosecutors' office made no mention of ethnic hatred as a
reason for the violence, blaming it on ``a group of hooligans.''
   In February, clashes took place in Nagorno-Karabakh in which two
people were killed and about 50 injured, the prosecutor's report
said.
   It said investigations were continuing to find the instigators.
   Pravda, in a report on the dispute over Nagorno-Karabakh, used
tough language to criticize Armenian militants who have formed the
``Karabakh Commission'' to demand reunification.
   ``They claim they fight for socio-economic development of the
region, but they consciously or unconsciously use methods which
Western Sovietologists recommend for fighting against socialism.
Thus we see that a noble idea of a reunion has a clear
anti-socialist spirit,'' Pravda said.
   Tass, in a commentary read on state-run TV's evening news,
criticized commission members I. Muradyan and K. Nagepetyan, saying
they refused to listen to people calling for reason and calm at a
March 19 meeting of the group.
   It said commission organizers ``cynically and perfidiously'' are
willing to exploit difficulties experienced by Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform program.
   The disputed area, smaller than the state of Delaware, has been
part of mostly Moslem Azerbaijan for 50 years, even though
three-fourths of its 157,000 residents are Armenians, most of whom
are Christian.
   Gorbachev has promised that another meeting of the policy-making
Central Committee will be held to consider the Nagorno-Karabakh
question and relations among the country's more than 100 ethnic
groups. In February, the committee refused an earlier request for
restitution of the area.
   Pravda did not say outright that the region should remain in
Azerbaijan, but denounced using demonstrations, strikes and mass
meetings to pressure officials for a decision in favor of reunion.
   Paruyr Ayrikyan, an Armenian nationalist now in Moscow, said he
was told by telephone from Yerevan that 7,000 people marched Monday
to the Press House, headquarters of Armenia's official media, to
protest the Pravda story.
   The article was signed by a Pravda correspondent in Armenia, Y.
Arakelyan, and two other correspondents. However, an Armenian
official said Monday night Arakelyan denied seeing or signing the
article.
   ``They forged his name because they needed an Armenian name on
the article,'' Gamlet Kocharyan, an industrial worker and member of
the governing council of the Armenian city of Kafar, said in a
telephone interview.
   In recent weeks, some officials blamed for the problems linked
to Nagorno-Karabakh and Sumgait have been ousted.
</TEXT>
