<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 5thLd-Writethru a0885 03-21 1036</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0885,1,000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Stays On Top In Delegate Count; Bush Wins Puerto Rico</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOPS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Jackson winning, UPDATE
Republican and Democratic figures; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs bgng, `The
51-member;' Stands for AMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush and Democratic presidential contender
Jesse Jackson each snared another victory Sunday, winning their
parties' primaries in Puerto Rico.
   But Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis remained the leader of
the Democratic presidential pack because Jackson picked up no
delegates in the non-binding ``beauty contest'' in the U.S.
commonwealth.
   Bush swept the winner-take-all GOP contest in Puerto Rico, with
14 delegates at stake. Puerto Rico GOP Chairman Luis Ferre declared
that ``Bush has the 14 delegates,'' even though the counting was
proceeding slowly. With results from almost one-third of the
precincts, Bush had picked up 97 percent of the vote, while Dole
had gotten only 3 percent.
   On the Democratic side, Jesse Jackson won the non-binding
primary that hinged more on local issues than the candidates. With
31 percent of the precincts reporting, Jackson had 35 percent of
the votes. The nearest contender was Dukakis with 23 percent,
followed by Illinois Sen. Paul Simon with 20 percent.
   The 51-member Democratic delegation from Puerto Rico was
expected to go to the convention uncommitted and vote as a bloc.
The commonwealth will send an additional five party leaders,
including the governor, to the convention as delegates.
   Bob Dole, fighting for the survival of his Republican
presidential bid, was in Wisconsin campaigning for the state's
April 5 primary. The Kansas senator, who has suffered a series of
crushing losses to Bush, has pledged to keep his faltering campaign
alive at least until that contest.
   Dole, who was gravely wounded in World War II, was making a
visit to a veterans hospital in Milwaukee on Sunday. Such
appearances have become a campaign staple for Dole, who likes to
use them to suggest he can surmount the greatest odds, as he did
when he was recovering from his crippling injuries.
   Those odds appeared to lengthen Sunday, as a poll published in
the Milwaukee Journal suggested Bush held a commanding lead in
Wisconsin. The survey of likely Republican voters, with a 6-point
margin of error, said 69 percent backed Bush while 25 percent
supported Dole. Pat Robertson trailed with 6 percent.
   ``I've got a lot of hill to climb before April 5,'' Dole
acknowledged, but added: ``Bob Dole is a fighter.''
   On the Democratic side, Dukakis led in Wisconsin with 38
percent, with Jackson at 30 percent, the Journal survey indicated.
The other three Democrats were closely clustered: Rep. Richard
Gephardt, 11 percent; Simon, 11 percent and Tennessee Sen. Albert
Gore Jr., 10 percent. The Democratic survey had a margin of error
of 5 percentage points.
   Dukakis, at a Boston breakfast on Sunday, was upbeat after his
victory a day earlier in the Kansas Democratic caucuses, joking
that he was ``just a simple farm boy _ from Brookline,'' a Boston
suburb.
   Although he was edged out by Gephardt in delegates counted
Saturday in South Dakota and by Jackson in Texas delegates counted
the same day, Dukakis remained ahead in national delegates.
   The South Dakota totals were in line with last month's primary,
which Gephardt won. Texas had already allocated the bulk of its
delegates on Super Tuesday, with the Saturday figures from county
conventions and caucuses.
   The latest AP delegate count gave Dukakis 526.5 delegates to
508.55 for Jackson and 362.8 for Gore. Simon had 171.5, Gephardt
had 154 and 292.65 were uncommitted. To nominate, 2,082 delegates
are needed.
   Gore told about 200 members of the Harriman Society, a social
club of the Westchester Democratic Party, that the country's first
priority should be arms control so it can change its underlying
political relationship with the Soviet Union.
   ``The next great negotiating effort beyond the strategic arms
agreement will have to come in conventional arms control,'' Gore
said, adding, ``There is a deep and understandable fear that the
balance of forces could be less stable after reductions than
before.''
   Before his speech at a fund-raising cocktail party, Gore said
the April 19 New York primary ``may well turn out to be the
critical contest.''
   Jackson got an enthusiastic reception when he addressed
California Democrats, meeting in Palm Springs. All the candidates
were invited to address the annual gathering, but only Jackson
accepted.
   ``There's room for you in the Jackson campaign,'' he said to
cheers and applause.
   All the Democrats planned to spend at least three days in
Michigan this week in advance of Saturday's Democratic caucuses,
with 138 delegates at stake.
   Simon, who jump-started his stalled campaign with a win in his
home state of Illinois last week, was campaigning Sunday in
Michigan, where he has said he hopes for a respectable showing but
is not expecting a victory.
   ``I'd be fooling you if I said we expected to win in Michigan,''
he said.
   Gephardt was taking a day off on Sunday at home in suburban
Washington. The Missouri congressman, who was the big Democratic
loser on Super Tuesday and did not mount a real effort in Illinois,
has staked his hopes on a strong showing in Michigan, and planned
to spend almost every day of this week in the state.
   Bush, too, was in Washington Sunday, where he has spent most of
his time since his Illinois victory last Tuesday. He planned to
resume campaigning on Monday.
   The vice president was meeting Monday in Trenton with New Jersey
Gov. Thomas H. Kean, and some leading state Republicans said the
session could mean Kean planned to endorse the vice president. A
Kean spokesman, Carl Golden, would not comment on whether an
endorsement was forthcoming.
   Bush planned appearances in Connecticut this week with Sen.
Lowell Weicker Jr., who has stopped short of formally endorsing the
vice president. But Weicker, like Bush the scion of a powerful
Connecticut family, has been going out of his way lately to praise
him.
   Connecticut holds its primary March 29, with 35 GOP delegates at
stake. Dole planned to venture into the state toward the end of the
week, but Robertson had no Connecticut appearances scheduled this
week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
