<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FugitiveCaptured 1stLd-Writethru a0886 03-21 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fugitive Captured, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0886,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Captures `Ten Most-Wanted' Fugitive</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 10th graf pvs, `Earlier this...', to
UPDATE with reaction from latest kidnap victim, Louisiana sheriff.
Picks up 11th graf pvs, `Weeks and...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted killer who escaped from a Louisiana
prison 1{ years ago and has been implicated in two interstate
kidnappings since then was arrested Sunday with a companion is also
accused in one of the abductions.
   Danny Michael Weeks, 34, was serving a life sentence for murder
and another sentence for armed robbery at the time of his escape
from the Louisiana State Penitentiary at Angola in August 1986. He
was later placed on the FBI's 10-most-wanted list.
   Weeks was captured by a special 10-member FBI team, along with
Jorene H. Florea, 56, said chief Seattle FBI agent Don S. Tokunaga.
   Weeks and Ms. Florea apparently were just passing through the
Seattle area, Tokunaga said. Agents received an anonymous tip from
someone who had recognized Weeks as a most-wanted criminal, the
agent said.
   Agents converged on Weeks and Ms. Florea about a half-hour after
receiving the tip as the two were looking into the trunk of a car
in a residential neighborhood, Tokunaga said. ``We were fortunate
there were no incidents,'' he said.
   The two were not armed, but agents had not completed a search of
the vehicle, he said.
   Authorities said that after Weeks and a companion escaped from
the prison Aug. 24, 1986, the two men abducted a woman at
knifepoint in the parking lot of an Alexandria, La., hospital and
forced her to drive them to Houston, where she was released
unharmed about eight hours later.
   The pair then forced a second woman, who was a lieutenant in the
U.S. Army, to drive them hundreds of miles during a 50-hour ordeal
that took her to El Paso, Texas, where she was left in a shopping
center parking lot.
   Weeks' companion, James Lee Colvin, 33, of Shreveport, La., was
arrested not long after that incident. Last August, he was
convicted on fedeal charges of kidnapping, using firearms during a
violent crime, illegally possessing revolvers and transporting
stolen vehicles across state lines.
   Earlier this month, Weeks and Ms. Florea were charged with the
Feb. 23 abduction of Susan Kathleen Vincent, a Guilford, N.C.,
sheriff's deputy, from a shopping center in Greensboro, N.C. She
was released unharmed in Chicago three days later.
   ``I'm ecstatic,'' Ms. Vincent said Sunday night about the
capture. ``I'm real relieved.''
   Ms. Vincent said that during her abduction, her captors robbed a
bank in Davenport, Iowa. She said she also was forced to use a bank
card to withdraw money, and ended up giving her kidnappers $208.
   ``I'm real glad they caught them so soon, before they got out of
the country,'' Ms. Vincent said. ``The worst is over now. All
that's left is the court action.''
   Sheriff Layman Godwin of Ouachita Parish, La., where Weeks twice
escaped from deputies' custody in 1982 and 1983, said Seattle
authorities had better take no chances with the captured fugitive.
   ``I just hope they learn from our mistakes that he's a sharp son
of a gun,'' said Godwin. In those two earlier escapes, charges were
dropped as part of a plea bargain.
   Weeks and Ms. Florea are to appear before a U.S. magistrate in
Seattle on Monday, Tokunaga said.
   Weeks, originally from Roswell, N.M., had been serving a
99-year-sentence for armed robbery and a life sentence for a 1981
contract slaying.
   He pleaded guilty to a lesser charge of second-degree murder in
that slaying, avoiding a possible death penalty for conviction on
the original charge of first-degree murder.
</TEXT>
