<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0830,0360</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Lewyt. No separates moved for AMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Alexander M. Lewyt</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANDS POINT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander M. Lewyt, an inventor who
developed a vacuum cleaner designed to operate without interfering
with TV or radio reception, died Friday at age 79.
   Lewyt, who was born in New York, the son of an Austrian
immigrant who ran a gadget shop, held patents on scores of
inventions.
   When he learned of undertakers' difficulty in fastening neckties
on corpses, the teen-age Lewyt devised a new kind of bow tie that
clipped on. He sold 50,000 of them. It was unclear whether he ever
patented the concept.
   He was best known for the compact Lewyt vacuum cleaner, which
had no dust bag and was designed not to cause interference.
   In the first eight years after his vacuum cleaner was introduced
after World War II, Lewyt Corp. sold 2 million of them. During the
war, Lewyt Corp. did a multi-million dollar business making such
things as radar antennas and popcorn poppers.
   Lewyt sold his interest in the company to the Budd Corp. in the
1950s.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Sidney Johnson Harkreader</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sidney Johnson ``Fiddlin' Sid''
Harkreader, one of the first featured fiddlers on the Grand Ole
Opry, died Saturday at age 90.
   Born near Gladeville, Harkreader bought his first fiddle from a
catalog for $3.95 when he was about 10 with money earned from
selling rabbit skins.
   He played on the Opry, a live country music show, off and on
from the 1920s until the 1950s. He performed well into his 80s.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Robert Goralski</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Goralski, a former NBC News
correspondent, died of cancer Friday at age 60.
   Goralski covered the Vietnam War and the Mideast War of 1967 and
reported from the White House, Pentagon and State Department at
various stages of his career.
   Goralski left NBC in 1975 to join Gulf Oil Corp. as public
relations director. In recent years, he was a senior adviser to the
American Petroleum Institute, a trade association for the oil
industry.
</TEXT>
