<1ST_LINE>r p PM-BeforetheBrokers Bjt   03-21 0784</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Before the Brokers, Bjt,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Has Until May 3 To Settle Dem Nomination</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN WOLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republicans have a runaway winner and now
the Democrats are in a quandary: They'd like to keep up with the
Bushes and have one of their own, but the prospects for wheeling
and dealing are so delicious that many party leaders can barely
contain themselves.
   ``It keeps the excitement going,'' says Colorado Gov. Roy
Roemer. ``I'd like to have a voice.''
   ``There will be brokering,'' says New York's Mario Cuomo. ``The
question is where and how.''
   If it happens at the convention, Cuomo says, ``the whole United
States will see you in the grubby business of cutting deals. I say
that's no way to do it. I say let's do it when they're not
watching.''
   Tip O'Neill, the retired House speaker, harkens back to 1952,
when the Democrats nominated Adlai Stevenson in the most recent
roll-call convention. ``It makes it more fun,'' he says.
   Of course Stevenson lost to Eisenhower and the Democrats were
out in the cold for eight years. Former President Carter says the
boisterous 1980 convention made him ``weaker than when I went in''
and he is urging that the Democrats find a ``winning ticket'' and
unite behind it in Atlanta.
   That's the cool, calculated Democratic Party talking. The one
whose chairman, Paul Kirk, wants to have a June summit to work
things out before the July roll call in Atlanta.
   The problem is that Democratic voters haven't made it clear whom
they want and party leaders fear that no one will emerge from the
primaries.
   Despite the predicament, the Democrats can be sure that George
Bush is not taking his presidency for granted. So far, the struggle
for the Democratic nomination probably says more about the party's
strength (breadth of support, with multiple candidates tapping
different veins of support) than its weakness (no obvious leader to
rebuild the party's old majority coalition).
   ``The process is going to work its will,'' predicts Sen. John
Kerry. ``Nobody said the process had to end by March.''
   For Kerry's candidate, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the
process is likely to end in May, one way or the other. Alone among
the candidates, Dukakis has the money, the organization and the
wintertime success to nail down the nomination during the second
round of primaries and caucuses.
   Democrats wouldn't even bother thinking about brokered
conventions except that Dukakis' third-place disappointment in
Illinois raised questions about his dominance in the string of
urban states to come. He has from Michigan on Saturday to Ohio on
May 3 to eliminate the doubts _ with these key states in between:
Wisconsin, April 5, New York on April 19 and Pennsylvania on April
26.
   The Gary Hart law of politics says that opportunity knocks just
once every four years. If Dukakis stumbles in the next five weeks,
there will be little hope of redemption in California in June (let
alone Atlanta in July).
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr., after an incredible two-week anguish over
where to go next, is now plotting an April 5 ambush in Wisconsin to
start the ball rolling his way. He wouldn't seem to stand much
chance, except that Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois is crossing the
state line to make another last stand. Simon could drain enough
Dukakis support to deny him the victory.
   Like Dukakis, Gore will either win at the ballot box or he won't
win at all. His hope is to block Dukakis in April and May and then
sweep California and New Jersey on Final Tuesday, June 6.
   If the two of them slug it out without a winner, then who?
   Jesse Jackson? He followed up his Southern victories with second
place in Kansas last Saturday and he maintains a slight lead over
Dukakis in the competition for Texas delegates _ but many voters
tell pollsters they would never consider voting for him. This
``high negative'' rating probably disqualifies him from the ticket.
   Richard Gephardt? He was the Democratic golden boy for a while,
but all the congressional endorsements in the world can't help if
his trade and family-farm message doesn't win him Michigan this
weekend.
   That leaves the usual suspects: Cuomo, Sam Nunn and Bill
Bradley, with Lee Iacocca on the list to add spice. Nunn has thrown
in with Gore, but not very vigorously. Bradley is saying nice
things about Dukakis and Cuomo is reconsidering his well-honed
neutrality. In any event, it hardly seems worth exploring the
alternatives until the coming ``Dukakis primaries'' have run their
course.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jonathan Wolman is The Associated Press'
assistant bureau chief in Washington.
</TEXT>
