<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DestroyerSlaying Bjt   03-21 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Destroyer Slaying, Bjt,0722</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slaying Of Disbursement Officer Remains A Mystery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like the fog that rolls in
from the Atlantic, enshrouding this base most mornings, mystery
surrounds the payday robbery and killing of the USS John Hancock's
disbursement officer.
   Sometime early Tuesday after Lt. j.g. Ratish Prasad finished his
watch at midnight, someone shot him in the head at close range,
choked him and shoved his body into a storage area on the destroyer.
   The killer vanished with $94,629 in Navy payroll and blank
checks.
   This base, stunned 10 months ago when 37 sailors were killed in
an attack on one of its ships _ the USS Stark _ in the Persian
Gulf, is reeling from what veterans say is a crime like none in
memory here.
   The Naval Investigative Service, which is probing the
24-year-old Prasad's killing in conjunction with the Duval County
Sheriff's Office, has been mum about the investigation, saying it
will remain so until there is a break in the case. The sheriff's
office also hasn't commented on the case.
   Some have speculated, however, that because visits to such a
ship are tightly restricted, the killer could be one of the 320
officers and sailors aboard the destroyer. Even Navy personnel
without specific business have difficulty going aboard, said Chief
Petty Officer Art Riccio, a Navy spokesman.
   ``That feeling is there. People are looking about, asking
questions, trying to find out what is going on,'' Command Master
Chief Curtis T. Cook said in an interview with The Florida
Times-Union.
   Or, the killer could be someone who slipped through the security
gate at the base and a checkpoint at the pier, got on the ship,
committed the crime and escaped.
   The Navy is refusing to say if there are any leads, whether it
has any suspects or whether the probe is focusing on crew members.
However, Navy and civilian investigators have been interviewing
members of the ship's crew.
   Mayport has 35 ships, including two aircraft carriers, and
18,500 active-duty personnel and 3,000 civilian employees.
   Prasad, the only son of Indian-born parents, Rameshwar and
Mithilesh, was a strict vegetarian, unusual in the
meat-and-potatoes Navy. Fellow officers aboard the ship called him
``Radish'' because of his penchant for vegetables.
   As the man responsible for handing out pay, Prasad probably got
to know more people than many others during nearly three years in
the Navy.
   ``He smiled a lot. He was friendly and he always said hello to
the rest of the crew. He probably could tell you by sight the name,
and probably the pay record, of everyone on board,'' Cook said.
   Prasad's mother, in a telephone interview from her home in Park
Forest, Ill., told The Florida Times-Union his death was the
realization of the family's worst nightmare.
   ``We didn't want him to join. It was scary for us because you
never know what is going to happen,'' she said.
   Her son had a degree in business administration from the
University of Illinois and had planned to go to graduate school
after the Navy, relatives said.
   Officials said that at every muster since the body was found, no
one has been reported missing from the ship.
   ``We know exactly where everyone is at,'' Riccio said, adding
that at least a fourth of the ship's personnel is on duty at any
one time and others must check in daily unless they are on leave.
   The ship's disbursement office is a secure area ``like a bank''
and the combination of the safe was issued only to those with a
need to know, Riccio said.
   When the disbursing office door was discovered open Tuesday, an
immediate search for Prasad was called, said Lt. Cmdr. Tim Taylor.
Prasad had gotten off duty at midnight, then spent the night on
board in a stateroom, Taylor said.
   Investigators initially thought Prasad had absconded with the
money, but they quickly found his car still parked on the pier.
Shortly afterward, his body was found in an isolated storage area
one deck below his office.
   Navy officials said the time of death, an important element of
the investigation, hadn't been determined as far as they knew.
</TEXT>
