<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CruiseFire     03-21 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cruise Fire,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire-Damaged Ship Under Tow To Miami</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fire-damaged Scandinavian Star was being towed
into port here so federal investigators can look for the cause of
an engine-room blaze that cut short a Mexican cruise.
   The ship could arrive as early as today at the home base of its
operators, SeaEscape Ltd., the National Transportation Safety Board
said.
   A preliminary inspection showed that the fire ``cooked'' wiring
in the ship's engine room, said William P. Fannon, leader of the
four-member investigative team.
   Once the ship is in Miami, NTSB investigators hope to rig bright
lights and ventilating fans in the engine room, which is currently
lit by dim lights from an auxiliary power unit.
   ``We want to develop a scenario of what happened,'' Fannon said.
``We're going to examine everything because the probable cause can
come from any one of a number of indicators.''
   The fire broke out Wednesday morning when the Star was about 35
miles northeast of the Yucatan peninsula. The ship was returning to
St. Petersburg from a three-day cruise to Cozumel, Mexico.
   The ship was towed to Cancun, and its 447 passengers were flown
back to Florida late Thursday.
   Fannon said the investigation will include interviews with crew
members and passengers.
   As the ship was being towed, more than 260 crew members relaxed
on deck chairs, Fannon said.
   But he said the crew were hardly enjoying a vacation. Because of
electrical damage, the Star had no water for showers.
   ``There is also no air conditioning,'' Fannon said. ``It's quite
uncomfortable.''
</TEXT>
