<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RocketScare     03-21 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rocket Scare,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Discovers Son Playing With Live LAW Rocket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Grigg was miffed when his
11-year-old son pointed what he thought was a toy bazooka at him _
then was stunned to find out it really was a live anti-tank rocket
launcher.
   Grigg said he was working on a car Sunday afternoon when he saw
his son, Dennis, pointing the weapon at him.
   ``I walked over to tell him not to point toy guns at people,''
Grigg said. ``Then I found out it was a real one.''
   Grigg, who once served with an artillery unit in the army, said
he looked down the barrel of the weapon and saw something inside.
   ``I decided not to take any chances and called the sheriff's
department,'' he said.
   The Sangamon County Sheriff's Department called for a bomb
disposal unit, which identified the weapon as a LAW anti-tank
rocket launcher, said Gary Mack, spokesman for the bomb unit.
   The bomb squad X-rayed the weapon, and determined it to be a
live weapon with the firing pin intact, Mack said. Police then
transported it to a gun club, where it was detonated.
   Grigg said his son had been playing with the live weapon in the
house for 1{ days before he noticed it.
   ``He thought it was a toy,'' Grigg said.
   Authorities were trying to find out where the weapon came from.
   Grigg said his son got it from a friend who found it in his
father's pickup truck.
   Grigg said that boy's father is a trash collector who had gotten
the weapon from another man who had been storing it in an old
refrigerator and wanted it taken to a trash dump.
</TEXT>
