<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HoneyWar     03-21 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honey War,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conte, Honey Producers Battle Over Federal Support Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's a honey of a fight on Capitol Hill,
and Rep. Silvio O. Conte is in the middle of the stirred up beehive.
   The Massachusetts Republican is waging a one-man battle against
beekeepers over the government's 38-year-old honey support program.
   ``I found these entitlements to be a classic example of wasteful
federal spending,'' Conte said in an interview. ``We now have a
federal program that encourages producers to have every single drop
of honey subsidized.''
   The Agriculture Department's honey support program was created
in 1950. Sugar rationing and the need for beeswax for waterproofing
ammunitions and equipment during World War II had bolstered the
honey business, and the end of the war hurt the once-prosperous
producers.
   The post-war program was used sparingly for the first 30 years.
Companies would give the government honey in exchange for a loan,
then redeem the loan and put the stored honey on the market when
demand went up.
   But during the 1980s, world honey supplies outpaced demand,
causing prices to drop. At about the same time, China began
flooding U.S. markets with less expensive honey, along with Mexico,
Canada and Argentina.
   ``We became a dumping ground,'' said Richard Adee, president of
the American Honey Producers Association Inc. and owner of a Bruce,
S.D., honey farm that he says is the largest in the world.
   Domestic producers began relying more and more heavily on the
federal supports. Some producers now regularly obtain federal loans
only to default on them later, leaving the government with tons of
honey as collateral.
   Adee defends the program as necessary to keep domestic producers
afloat.
   ``Everybody thinks this is a gravy train, but we've lost 20
percent of our industry in the past five years,'' he said.
   To Conte, the program ``has ballooned out of control.''
   ``We have to attack the program for what it is and not what it
was. It's a free ride now,'' he said.
   In 1986, Conte successfully capped the amount of money that
could be put under loan and forfeited by each company at $250,000.
   But honey-industry supporters in Congress, led by Sen. John
Melcher, D-Mont., removed the cap in the waning hours of Congress
last year.
   Without the cap, an estimated 200 million pounds of honey will
be subsidized at about 25 cents a pound this year _ approximately
double the annual amount that was subsidized under the limitation,
Conte said.
   The Agriculture Department, which supported the cap and decried
its removal, estimates the unlimited loans and forfeitures will
cost the government an extra $6.1 million over the next four years.
But Adee said a 2-cent a pound reduction in the buy-back price will
keep costs down.
   Conte, a 15-term congressman and the top Republican on the House
Appropriations Committee, has vowed to unleash another attack on
the honey industry this year.
   The American Beekeeping Federation, a lobbying group, is ready
to fight back. Last month, the federation sent out a fund-raising
letter warning of Conte's wrath.
   ``The changes in the honey support program at the last moment
during the preparation of the reconcillation budget for 1988 has
Rep. Silvio Conte mad, no _ furious,'' the group's executive
committee warned in a Feb. 10 letter. ``Rep. Conte is out for
revenge and he will try to kill the support program for 1989 and
forever.''
   In a frank assessment of its 1987 success and fear in 1988, the
federation said: ``There were some big bucks and time spent in
Washington to change the program, but those are insignificant
compared to what we will need in 1988 to save the program.''
   Conte said he will be satisfied with reinstituting the loan cap.
   ``I don't think I can get rid of the whole program. I'd love to,
but I've been around here a long time. I'm realistic,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
