<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CommercialStrike 1stLd-Writethru a0817 03-21 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commercial Strike, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0817,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio-TV Commercial Actors Ordered To Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with union ordering strike;
picks up 4th graf pvs, `The advertising ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commercial actors and announcers nationwide
were ordered late Sunday to strike.
   ``Unfortunately, no new negotiations have been scheduled at this
time,'' a hot-line message to union members in Los Angeles said
late Sunday.
   Representatives of the Screen Actors Guild and the American
Federation of Television and Radio Artists and advertisers could
not be reached for comment late Sunday.
   ``The strike will begin as planned at 12:01 a.m. this Monday,
March 21st,'' the union hot-line recording said, adding that
members shouldn't renew or reinstate any old commercials.
   ``Beginning at that time, no member of SAG or AFTRA may audition
for or perform in any television or radio commercial,'' it said.
``Our fellow actors will also place picket lines in New York,
Chicago, Miami, Honolulu and other cities to follow next week.''
   The advertising firm of Ogilvy and Mather was targeted by
pickets in Los Angeles and Honolulu. In New York City, strikers
were told to set up picket lines at General Motors Plaza during a
GM board meeting.
   In Chicago, the agencies of Leo Burnett, J. Walter Thompson, DDB
Needham Worldwide and Tatham-Laird and Kudner were targeted for
union picketing.
   Talks on a new three-year pact between the commercial performers
and the Joint Policy Committee of the American Association of
Advertising Agencies and the Association of National Advertisers
began Jan. 11 in New York City and broke off March 7.
   Union negotiators received a 93 percent strike authorization
from members just before contract talks broke off.
   The contract dispute centers on performers' demands for a share
of money made from commercials broadcast on cable television
stations and advertisers' attempts to reduce union cost-of-living
adjustments.
   The unions recently sent telegrams to all presidential
candidates warning them of the strike and offering production
waivers if they agree to interim contracts conceding the demands
turned down by advertising negotiators.
   The interim contract offer was given to regular advertisers as
well, and as many as 40 have said they will seek them, according to
the union.
   The advertisers' negotiator, John McGuinn, had urged agncies to
resist signing interim contracts, although he said a strike could
last as long as six months.
   The joint SAG-AFTRA membership is more than 100,000. The unions
negotiate together on the commercial contract. Union actors will be
barred from auditioning or appearing in commercials, but can work
in films and on television shows.
</TEXT>
