<DOCNO> AP880321-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 0203EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Market Bjt   03-21 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Market, Bjt,0854</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Underground Economy Surfaces at Riga Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet underground economy has poked through
the surface at Riga Market, a weekend jungle of moonlighters,
fast-ruble artists and curious consumers brought out by Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's economic reforms.
   ``You can get anything you want here; the price is the only
thing,'' said Lyonya. The curly-haired 17-year-old surveyed the
open-air sales of imitation Western clothes, wool and fur hats,
coats and other goods at the market in northern Moscow near the
Riga train station.
   A cigarette dangling from his mouth, Lyonya moments before had
approached a Westerner and offered to illegally exchange money.
   Thousands of shoppers jostle and slide through snow and ice to
trade their rubles for goods of uncertain origin. A knee-length red
winter coat devoid of any labeling was priced at 250 rubles, $400
at the official exchange rate.
   One hundred rubles ($160) could buy a jean skirt with the
``SFINKS'' brand on a triangular metal tab displaying the ancient
Egyptian monument. The average worker earns about 200 rubles a
month.
   The market illustrates the opportunities and abuses of
Gorbachev's drive to loosen some of the controls on the state-run
economy, as well as the pent-up demand for anything Western.
   Black-market money traders and speculators who sell prized
Western goods and Soviet imitations long have flourished
underground at tourist hotels, among taxi drivers and elsewhere.
   But the reforms started by Gorbachev, the Communist Party
leader, have given traders a new place to operate, mingled with
legal moonlighters who produce a few items by hand to earn extra
rubles.
   Gorbachev said in January that 300,000 Soviets drive taxis,
repair apartments, run restaurants and pump gas outside the
official economy under new laws allowing citizens more freedom to
work for themselves or form a cooperative.
   But many Soviets complain cooperative goods and services are too
expensive and those who work in them are out to make a quick
profit. Meeting with factory workers several weeks ago, Gorbachev
praised honest initiative but said authorities would not permit
``outright money-grabbing.''
   A draft of a new law published recently indicates the government
is planning to tax both the profits of cooperatives and the incomes
of their members.
   On weekdays, Riga Market differs little from other farmers'
markets scattered around Moscow. But on Saturdays and Sundays it
blossoms with the booths of several thousand merchants.
   The merchants say they work for themselves or are members of
cooperatives formed under the new law. But they are reluctant to
discuss their affairs, apparently either because they are operating
illegally or because public disapproval makes them nervous.
   The newspaper Moskovsky Komsomolets, aimed at young readers,
said in a recent article that Riga Market draws young people like a
magnet and that ``crimes are committed here every day, and in no
small quantity.''
   Although Moscow needs such places, Riga Market should be limited
to 300-400 sellers and officials must control the activity, the
newspaper said.
   Lyonya said Western jeans like those he was wearing are
available from speculators for about 100 rubles, and Western-made
boots cost 150 rubles to 200 rubles ($240 to $320).
   A few minutes later, another young man approached the same
Western correspondent and asked if he had a jacket, boots, or pants
to sell. Told no, he followed behind and asked, ``Do you have any
friends?''
   Lyonya said a friend of his buys sweatshirts at the official
price of three rubles, puts an English-language emblem saying
``Manufactured Exclusively for SMASH'' on them and sells them for
35 rubles.
   The seller, who had a half-dozen shirts hanging from a line, was
asked how many such shirts he could sell in a weekend. He refused
to answer and said the query was ``a provocative question.''
   Valery, a Muscovite with several days' growth of beard and a
wide-brim black hat, said he can buy the labeling and everything he
needs for the ``SFINKS'' denim line from associates at the market.
He also had for sale two children's sweatsuits, one with Walt
Disney's Bambi emblazoned on it, for 20 rubles (about $32).
   He said he sells in Moscow occasionally but prefers the Soviet
Far East or Siberia. ``It's too crowded here. People have more
money there because they earn higher salaries,'' he said.
   He said his store job offers him three days off for every one he
works, giving him plenty of time to sew the garments. He declined
to go into more detail about his business and refused to be
photographed.
   Moskovsky Komsomolets said one morning's police records showed a
young Russian was arrested after selling an imported jeans jacket
for 120 rubles ($190). Another was selling packs of Marlboro
cigarettes for 8 rubles (about $12.80).
   A 12-year-old boy was found selling things he stole from his
parents, the newspaper said.
   ``The main heroes of these stories are basically young guys and
girls, young Communists,'' the newspaper said. ``Do they need these
lessons?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
