<DOCNO> AP880321-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 0222EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArabAmericans     03-21 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arab Americans,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Americans Parlay Palestinian Uprising Into Political Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab Americans are parlaying the Palestinian
revolt against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip
into a surge of charitable contributions and domestic political
gains.
   Last month, the United Palestine Appeal and other charitable
organizations raised $300,000 to help Palestinians continue a
three-month resistance campaign that has captured the world's
attention, according to David Sadd, executive director of the
National Association of Arab Americans.
   This compares with some $1 million these groups raised in all of
1987, and does not include the checks sent by American Palestinians
to their relatives in the occupied territories, said Sadd, whose
group is a major lobbyist for an estimated 2.3 million Arab
Americans.
   ``There's real pride about the courageous Palestinians. We want
to help them go on,'' said Sadd. ``If they can't work, we want to
make sure they have enough resources to continue the resistance.''
   A civil disobedience campaign combined with intimidation by
extremists have kept many of the 1.5 million Palestinians under
occupation away from their jobs in Israel.
   Sadd said leaders of major Arab American organizations are
discussing establishing a central resource to identify areas of
need in the West Bank and Gaza and to coordinate distribution of
medicine, blankets and other items.
   The organizations also are trying to link up with such
established charitable groups as Catholic Relief to help channel
their aid in order to prevent Israel from blocking the funds, Sadd
said.
   The revolt in which 100 Palestinian Arabs have been killed has
provided a renewed national consciousness in the mostly U.S.-born
community whose parents or grandparents came from Lebanon, Syria,
Egypt and Palestine.
   Unlike the 6 million American Jews, many of whom link their
religious and national identity to Israel, most American Arabs have
tended to identify less with their country of origin than with
village and family groups.
   ``Unlike the Jews, we don't have Zionism. We have always felt
that this is our home,'' said James Zogby, executive director of
the Arab American Institute.
   But in recent years, Zogby's organization and others have
modeled themselves on long-established Jewish lobbying and
charitable groups in an effort to unite the community and organize
grassroots support to influence the political scene.
   Last year, the Arab American Institute launched a project to
elect Arab American candidates locally and nationally and to
pressure other candidates to confront the sensitive issue of
statehood for the Palestinians.
   The West Bank and Gaza uprising and the harsh methods Israel is
using to quell it have given Arab Americans more confidence, he
said.
   But other Arab Americans acknowledge that the inroads are
slight, and may not be lasting. A wave of Arab American indignation
over the 1982 massacre of hundreds of Palestinians by
Israeli-allied militiamen in the Sabra and Chatillah refugee camps
fizzled out.
   Community leaders note that Arab Americans are better organized
now than they were then. The longer the revolt draws on, the more
entrenched and sustained will be the support for it, they maintain.
   Rep. Nick Rahall, a West Virginia Democrat of Lebanese descent,
warned that ``while Arab Americans are making gains from the
uprising, the question is whether they can translate it into
meaningful support in Congress or in the presidential race.''
   Congress traditionally has been strongly supportive of Israel
and has not spoken out against the Israeli killings and beatings.
Most presidential candidates have been vague when asked their views.
   The exception is Jesse Jackson, who has drawn broad support from
Arab Americans for his condemnation of the Israeli methods and for
his longtime support of a role for the Palestine Liberation
Organization in Mideast peace talks.
   Arab Americans have contributed $175,000 to his campaign, Zogby
said.
   Since the Palestinian unrest began Dec. 8, Arab Americans have
conducted demonstrations and vigils around the country, also
sending thousands of letters to congressmen and presidential
hopefuls.
   Abdeen Jabara, head of the Arab-American Anti-Discrimination
Committee, said he was pleasantly surprised when he was invited by
two groups of congressmen to brief them on his recent trip to the
West Bank. His previous attempts to get congressional attention for
the Palestinian cause failed, he said.
   ``But the changes are still very slight,'' he said. ``Public
opinion is with us, but congressional attitudes don't reflect
this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
