<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Porn, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0454,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sex-Film Stars Deny AIDS Is Rampant In Their Industry</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to restore dropped word `wife.' Contents may be
offensive to readers. Barbii is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the AIDS-related death of pornographic
film star John Holmes, industry officials insist the adult film
business is AIDS-free and that precautions such as AIDS testing are
widespread.
   Concerned about the adverse publicity surrounding Holmes' death,
sex film producers and performers said last week that AIDS and
venereal disease are virtually non-existent among sex-film stars.
   Industry concerns were heightened by a statement by Holmes'
24-year-old wife, Laurie.
   ``It's my belief that AIDS is running rapidly through the adult
entertainment business,'' said Mrs. Holmes, who once acted in porn
films under the name Misty Dawn and whose husband died March 13 of
a form of pneumonia brought on by acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
   Ron Sullivan, a sex-film producer and president of the
industry's 350-member Adult Video Association, said Mrs. Holmes
``is completely wrong.''
   Industry figures argued they have avoided AIDS by testing actors
for infection and making sure the men use condoms and anti-viral
spermicides. They said the small inner circle of pornographic
performers insist on the safety measures.
   Sullivan knew of no sex-film star who has contracted AIDS. It
was not known how Holmes got the disease, but in addition to his
14,000 claimed sexual encounters over the years, he used
intravenous drugs, which also can spread AIDS.
   Nina Hartley, who starred in such adult fare as ``Feminist Porno
Actress'' and ``Intellectual Tinker Bell,'' gave the porn industry
a clean bill of health.
   ``There is absolutely no evidence AIDS is rampant,'' said the
27-year-old San Francisco actress, who has appeared in adult films
for four years. ``AIDS testing is pretty common, but it's not
mandatory.''
   Ms. Hartley suggested actors would jeopardize chances for key
roles if they insisted on testing for their co-stars. She said she
knows of only a few sex stars who demand AIDS testing.
   ``Most of the veterans and people who have worked for quite a
while really keep health conscious,'' porno star Angel Kelly said.
``In the last six months we've even begun printing up a newsletter
to all the actors and actresses with health tips.''
   Sullivan and Ms. Hartley said there are only about 100 active
sex-film stars, and they are cautious.
   ``We are capable of taking care of ourselves and we want the
public to know that,'' said Sullivan, who organized a voluntary
testing program for adult film actors. His Los Angeles-based
association is paying the $75 test costs.
   ``We're doing it because of the adverse publicity (after Holmes'
death) saying that the industry is inundated with AIDS,'' he said.
   Movie sex star Barbii said she gets tested regularly and insists
that her partners be tested.
   ``Most girls don't take (AIDS) seriously,'' Barbii said.
``People don't talk about it _ it's kind of hush.''
   But Ms. Hartley counters that fear of AIDS and venereal diseases
permeates the industry, and that prevention, detection and
discretion have gained industry acceptance.
   ``Safe sex scenes are more prevalent now,'' she said. ``Not
every scene uses a condom and you won't see it (condom use) take
over the industry, but more actors are using them.
   The AIDS virus damages the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to death from infections and cancer.
   It can be spread through sexual contact, needles or syringes
shared by drug abusers, or transfusions of infected blood or blood
products.
</TEXT>
