<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PLOMission     03-21 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO Mission,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Plans Suit To Close PLO's UN Mission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department will seek an
``immediately enforceable'' court order to force the Palestine
Liberation Organization to vacate its New York office, a department
spokesman says.
   Spokesman Patrick Korten said Sunday that the department is
planning to file suit in U.S. District Court in New York to force
the closing of the PLO observer mission at the United Nations.
   ``We're ready to go ahead and file the papers if they don't
close the mission voluntarily,'' Korten said.
   The United States has declared the PLO a terrorist organization,
but the United Nations recognizes it as the only legitimate
representative of the Palestinian people.
   The PLO served notice last week that it planned to defy any U.S.
effort to shut the mission, which is in a New York City townhouse.
   Korten said the department probably will file the suit by
Wednesday, depending on how long the paperwork takes.
   ``The chances are it would be within a day or two if they are
not out,'' Korten said. ``We are hoping those who walk into the
office to look for them would find them gone. If that's not the
case, then we would proceed with legal action.''
   The Justice Department announced March 11 that it planned to
enforce the Anti-Terrorism Act passed by Congress last year by
going to court to close the mission. That act takes effect Monday.
   Korten said the suit would seek an ``immediately enforceable''
court order directing the PLO to vacate its offices in New York.
   In a failed effort to stop the legislation ordering the U.N.
mission closed, the State Department last year closed down the only
other PLO office in the United States, an information office in
Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880321-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 0438EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     03-21 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Lite Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Balancing 360 eggs on their ends may not be a
scientifically approved way of demonstrating the supposed powers of
the first day of spring. But don't tell that to performance artist
Donna Henes.
   About 200 people helped Henes balance the eggs at 4:39 a.m.
Sunday, the precise moment of the vernal equinox, one of two points
in the year when the sun crosses the equator and day and night are
equal.
   ``Considering the hour, more people showed up than I expected,''
she said. The egg balancing took place on a long table-like
platform at the South Street Seaport shopping area.
   According to Henes, balancing an egg on its end is an ancient
Chinese custom that brings good luck.
   Scientists are dubious whether eggs really do balance during the
equinox due to changes in the gravitational pull, but Henes is
convinced.
   ``It's funny, because I've asked a lot of scientists about it
and they say its impossible,'' Henes said. ``However, when I ask
them to join in the ritual and they see it happen, they become
instant believers.''
   Henes, who has been observing the egg-balancing ritual for the
past 13 years, said eggs are ancient symbols of fertility and
spring around the world. ``Easter is only one of many spring
holidays where the egg is used as a symbol of rebirth,'' she said.
   After balancing the eggs, the participants enjoyed them at a
breakfast prepared by one of the tourist attraction's restaurants.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SHEBOYGAN, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bratwurst makers here say they've
been inundated with long-distance orders since their business was
featured last week by a New York newspaper.
   However, Scott Poth and Scott Luchterhand of Poth's Meats say
their sudden popularity won't change things much _ at least not the
secret recipe.
   ``That came down from my grandmother on my mother's side of the
family,'' said Poth, 29.
   Poth operates the store his father, Henry, started some 40 years
ago, with the assistance of Luchterhand, his brother-in-law.
   Their store was one of 11 Sheboygan shops featured in a March 13
article in The New York Times, which called Sheboygan the ``wurst
city in the world.''
   ``The impact could really be significant,'' said Heather Clyde,
director of the city's Convention and Vistors Bureau. ``It could
really up attendance at our local bratwurst festivals.''
   Poth said he had more than a dozen orders from East Coast
residents last Monday, a day after the article appeared.
   But while mail-order sales are always welcomed, Poth said he
knows his most reliable market will always be in Sheboygan.
   ``Brat fries are just a primary part of life here,'' he said.
``All the fund-raisers? Brat fries. All the family picnics? Brat
fries.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
