<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BaptistAlliance     03-21 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baptist Alliance,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moderate Baptist Group Concerned About Its Fate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of moderate Baptists gathers tonight
for its second annual meeting, wondering if it will retain a place
in the fundamentalist-dominated Southern Baptist Convention that
sparked its formation.
   ``We are Southern Baptists, but we intend to hold up that flag
of religious liberty and we're going to yell ouch every time they
step on that principle and we're going to keep on yelling,'' said
the Rev. Jim Strickland, a Cartersville pastor who is a leader of
the Southern Baptist Alliance.
   Strickland said victories by moderates at some state Baptist
conventions last year indicate the Southern Baptist Convention's
annual meeting in San Antonio, Texas, this summer may be ``a
high-water mark ... a shootout at the O.K. Corral.''
   Nevertheless, Strickland said, this week's alliance meeting at
Mercer University is not a strategy session for moderates.
   ``The Southern Baptist Alliance is not a political organization.
... We are not going to do that footwork out there,'' although the
alliance supports those political efforts, he said.
   The alliance was formed in February 1987 in reaction to
fundamentalist actions as they gained control of the Southern
Baptist Convention, the nation's largest Protestant denominaton
with about 14.5 million members.
   Fundamentalists maintain that the Bible is without error in
historical and scientific as well as religious areas; moderates
hold there is room for interpretation.
   Fundamentalists have removed moderates from leadership
positions, including the presidency of Southeastern Baptist
Seminary in Wake Forest, N.C. In another instance, an employee of
one of the denomination's agencies says he was fired because he
said he believed Jews could go to heaven without accepting Jesus.
   The alliance has grown to include 34 churches with more than
20,000 members, plus about 2,500 other member whose churches do not
belong to the alliance. Strickland said the alliance is not
intended to be the nucleus of a new denomination.
   ``Our hope as members of the Southern Baptist Alliance is that
we can articulate Baptist philosophy _ not necessarily current
Southern Baptist philosophy _ about religious liberty. We want to
call Baptists who think religious freedom is important back to that
heritage,'' Strickland said.
   Strickland is pastor of Heritage Baptist Church, formed less
than a year ago, partly because of fundamentalist control of the
First Baptist Church of Cartersville, he said.
   Mercer University, supported by the Georgia Baptist Convention,
was itself the center of controversy last year when fundamentalists
mounted a campaign to gain control of the school, citing its
listing as a ``party school'' by Playboy magazine and the moderate
views of President R. Kirby Godsey.
   But the Georgia Baptist Convention last November defeated
efforts to remove Godsey. The action was seen at the time as one of
a series of victories by moderates in various state Baptist
conventions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
