<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalBriefs     03-21 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Conservatives Endorse Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush won the
presidential endorsement of the conservative California Republican
Assembly even through Pat Robertson personally sought the nod of
the volunteer group.
   Robertson called the CRA _ the largest and most conservative of
California's grassroots Republican organizations _ the most
important GOP endorsing body in the nation in an enthusiastically
received appearance before it Saturday.
   But Bush's supporters stressed the inevitability of his
nomination and the need for conservatives to unify behind him. In
the Sunday vote, Bush picked up nearly all the supporters of Sen.
Bob Dole and Rep. Jack Kemp after their names were dropped from the
endorsement ballot.
   Bush led Robertson by 178-70 on the first CRA ballot, but failed
to win the required two-thirds for an endorsement because Dole had
34 votes and Kemp 33. Bush easily defeated Robertson to win the CRA
endorsement on a 231-81 second ballot.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Oregon Democrats Defeat Marijuana Plank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EUGENE, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oregon Democrats have rejected a plank in
their state party platform that would have called for reduced
criminal penalties for growing and possessing marijuana.
   In the past, state Democrats have approved platform planks
advocating both outright legalization of marijuana and lessening
criminal penalties, arguing that the money would be better spent
fighting ``hard'' drugs.
   ``We're cleaning up our act,'' James Klonoski, a past state
Democratic party chair, said after the marijuana plank was rejected
Sunday. ``In the old days, we used to embarrass our elected
officials. We don't do that anymore.''
   Tom Alexander, a Benton County state convention delegate who
wanted the marijuana plank in platform, said the main opposition
was from Gov. Neil Goldschmidt and other elected Democrats worried
about the party's image and the upcoming elections.
   ``The problem is that the Democratic party leaders, because the
Republicans have shifted so far to the right, think we have to play
to the Republican moderates for votes,'' Alexander said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Gore Opposes Reagan Plan for Mideast Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr., after meeting with Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, says he prefers ``direct
negotiations'' between Israel and its Arab neighbors rather than
the Reagan administration's plan for an international Middle East
peace conference.
   ``I think there are questions that have been given short shrift
that deserve a more careful study,'' the Tennessee Democrat told
reporters after meeting with Shamir here Sunday. ``What would the
role of the Soviet Union be in the conference?''
   Shamir maintained his opposition to an international peace
conference in meetings with President Reagan last week, saying a
Soviet presence in the talks would bring more pressure on Israel to
give up land captured from the Arabs during the 1967 Middle East
War.
   Gore spent Sunday here campaigning for support in New York's
April 19 presidential primary. He addressed about 1,200 people at
the annual dinner of the Council of Jewish Organizations of Borough
Park, an umbrella organization for 190 groups in a neighborhood
that is home to 100,000 Hasidic Jews.
</TEXT>
