<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Israel     03-21 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Israel,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack 6 Outposts Of Israeli-Backed Militia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas attacked six positions manned by
an Israeli-backed militia before dawn today in one of their biggest
assaults this year, security sources reported.
   There was no immediate report of casualties and it could not be
determined which guerrilla faction launched the assault on the
South Lebanon Army outposts, the second reported clash in three
days.
   After today's attack, Israeli and South Lebanon Army gunners
shelled the Shiite Moslem market town of Nabatiyeh with mortars and
tank cannon in an apparent retaliation for the pre-dawn raid,
police said.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
guerrillas fired machine guns and rocket-propelled grenades into
the South Lebanon Army positions in the central sector of Israel's
self-proclaimed ``security zone'' on the Lebanon-Israel border.
   The mainly Christian South Lebanon Army retaliated with heavy
machine guns and mortars, the sources reported.
   Israeli troops rushed to reinforce the army positions and opened
up on the raiders with tank fire, the sources said. The fighting
lasted for two hours until the attackers withdrew, the sources said.
   Several positions manned by Irish and Finnish troops of the
United Nations peacekeeping force were caught in the crossfire, but
no U.N. soldiers were hurt, the sources added.
   The zone policed by the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon overlaps
the Israeli-occupied buffer zone carved out in June 1985 when
Israel withdrew the bulk of its army three years after its invaded
Lebanon.
   In the attack by Israeli and South Lebanon Army on the Moslem
town, two women were wounded when five shells exploded in the Sarai
quarter, crowded with villagers in town for the weekly market day,
police said.
   The 30-minute barrage brought the town of 150,000 inhabitants to
a standstill. Shopkeepers lowered their shutters, businesses closed
and schools sent pupils home.
   Today's hostilities came two days after tank-led Israeli troops
and South Lebanon Army militiamen raided suspected guerrilla bases
four miles northeast of the security zone.
   Shiite Moslem guerrillas earlier fought a seven-hour shelling
duel with the Israelis and their militia allies in which two
elderly Lebanese civilians were wounded.
   Israeli fighter-bombers raided a Palestinian guerrilla camp in
the Chouf Mountains southeast of Beirut last Thursday, killing one
guerrilla in their deepest penetration into Lebanon this year.
</TEXT>
