<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 0605EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Politics     03-21 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Politics,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Effort To Unite Opposition Fails</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiations to reunite South Korea's
bitterly divided opposition collapsed again today with both sides
refusing to compromise over sharing power and party posts.
   The Reunification Democratic Party announced it had pulled out
of talks with the smaller Party for Peace and Democracy and said
there was no hope of uniting the two parties. It denounced Party
for Peace and Democracy supporters for staging a violent protest
that broke up talks.
   ``The party concluded it would be meaningless and impossbile to
continue merger talks because the positions between the parties are
so wide apart,'' said a Reunification Democratic Party spokesman,
Kim Pae-ryong.
   Party for Peace and Democracy leaders said they wanted to
continue unification talks, but they recognized negotiations had
stalled. They charged the Reunification Democratic Party wanted to
destroy rival opposition groups.
   The two parties said there was no chance of reuniting before
National Assembly elections next month. Both groups said they would
mount separate election campaigns even though it would boost the
government's chances of a major victory.
   The acting Party for Peace and Democracy president, Park
Young-sook, said the party hoped that unification talks could be
revived after the election if not sooner. ``We need a strong
leadership and a strong opposition,'' she said.
   About a dozen students staged protests at the two party
headquarters today to demand the talks resume and wrote protests
with blood after cutting their fingers.
   Some opposition leaders and lawmakers had been pushing for
reunification of the two parties to avoid a major defeat in the
National Assembly elections expected to be held April 26.
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung and his supporters split away
from the Reunification Democratic Party to form the Party for Peace
and Democracy late last year after he and the larger party's
president, Kim Young-sam, failed to agree on which one of them
should run for president.
   Both Kims ran in the Dec. 16 election and were defeated by
government candidate President Roh Tae-woo after splitting the
opposition vote.
   Roh took office Feb. 25.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
