<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GunmenStandoffs     03-21 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gunmen Standoffs,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Gunmen Hold Police At Bay In Separate Incidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A standoff between Nashville police and a man who said he
accidentally killed his girlfriend ended early today when the
gunman fatally shot himself, while an Alabama gunman critically
wounded himself after killing a man and holding police at bay,
authorities say.
   George E. Powell, 45, of Nashville died at 1:35 a.m. of a
shotgun wound to the head at Vanderbilt University Medical Center,
officials said.
   Powell called police at 6:45 p.m. Sunday and told them he had
accidentally shot his girlfriend, Caroline Campbell of Nashville,
during a scuffle, said Buddy Mitchell, a hostage negotiator for the
police.
   ``He says they both had been drinking and had a sawed-off
shotgun,'' Mitchell said. ``He says they got into an argument over
the gun and it went off and shot her. He dragged her into the
bedroom and covered her up with a blanket and set the telephone on
top.''
   Powell, a sheet metal worker, told police he planned to kill
himself, Mitchell said. Police said they talked on the phone with
Powell throughout the ordeal.
   At least 10 patrol cars and the SWAT team communications van
were dispatched to the scene, and police sealed off the area.
   At 12:45 a.m., Powell said goodbye to the negotiators on the
phone, hung up and shot himself in the head, police said.
   In Huntsville, Ala., a 40-year-old man was listed in critical
condition after an eight-hour standoff that began with the gunshot
slaying of an acquaintance of the man's ex-wife and ended when the
man apparently shot himself, authorities said.
   Madison County Sheriff Joe Patterson said Jerry Staggs
apparently attempted suicide about 7 p.m. Sunday after he released
his ex-wife, Sherry, 29, and the couple's two boys, whom he had
taken hostage before noon.
   Staggs was taken by helicopter to Huntsville Hospital, where he
was being treated for a gunshot wound to the head, said spokeswoman
June Hackworth.
   The apparent suicide attempt ended a tense standoff that began
when Staggs shot the acquaintance of his ex-wife as the man sat in
his car outside Staggs' trailer, police said. About 25 police
officers surrounded the trailer and evacuated residents of the
dozen other mobile homes in the trailer park north of Huntsville.
   The Huntsville News reported today the victim was identified as
Don Pressnell, a former Athens police officer.
   Patterson said Staggs had been arrested two weeks ago on a
kidnapping charge and there had been an attempt to obtain
psychiatric treatment for him.
   The standoff ended when a shot rang out and Mrs. Staggs ran out
the door of the trailer. She told police her ex-husband had shot
himself in the head, said Capt. Robert Moder of the Huntsville
Police Department.
   Butler said Staggs was employed by the city maintenance
department.
</TEXT>
