<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Most-WantedCapture 1stLd-Writethru a0465 03-21 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Most-Wanted Capture, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0465,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`10 Most-Wanted' Fugitive Captured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to recast lead to clarify and to tighten.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI agents acting on an anonymous tip peacefully
captured one of the agency's 10 most wanted fugitives, a killer
sought in three kidnappings since his escape from a Louisiana
prison 19 months ago, authorities said.
   Danny Michael Weeks, 34, and a companion, Jorene H. Florea, 56,
were arrested Sunday by a 10-member FBI team, said Don S. Tokunaga,
who heads the agency's Seattle office.
   The two apparently were just passing through when agents
received an anonymous tip from someone who had recognized Weeks as
on the most-wanted list, Tokunaga said.
   ``It was one of those spur-of-the-moment things,'' he said. ``We
were fortunate there were no incidents.''
   The two were scheduled to appear before a U.S. magistrate today.
   Weeks was wanted for escape, interstate flight, and on warrants
alleging kidnapping in Houston and kidnapping and robbery in
Greensboro, N.C. He also has been implicated in a kidnapping in
Alexandria, La., the day after his Aug. 24, 1986, escape from the
Louisiana State Penitentiary.
   Ms. Florea was wanted by officials in Greensboro on a warrant
charging her with kidnapping.
   When arrested, the pair were unarmed and were looking into the
trunk of a car.
   Weeks, originally of Roswell, N.M., was serving a life sentence
for armed robbery and murder when he and James Lee Colvin, 33, of
Shreveport, La., escaped from the prison.
   The next day, authorities said, Colvin and Weeks kidnapped a
woman at knifepoint in Alexandria and forced her to drive to
Houston, where she was freed unharmed.
   Later that day, authorities said, the two forced another woman
at gunpoint into her car in Houston. She was forced to drive them
to El Paso, Texas, but was unharmed.
   Colvin, who was captured in 1986 in Los Angeles, was convicted
in August in Houston of federal kidnapping charges.
   Tokunaga said the Greensboro warrants stemmed from the Feb. 23,
1988, kidnapping at gunpoint of Guilford County, N.C., sheriff's
Deputy Susan Kathleen Vincent, 27. She was released unharmed in
Chicago on Feb. 26.
   Ms. Vincent said that during her abduction, her captors robbed a
bank in Davenport, Iowa.
   Greensboro police said they were seeking the extradition of
Weeks and Ms. Florea in Ms. Vincent's abduction.
   Weeks was serving a 99-year sentence for armed robbery when he
was sentenced in 1985 to life in prison for the Christmas 1981
contract slaying of Army Sgt. Major Hubert Ester. Weeks pleaded
guilty to second-degree murder.
   Ester's wife, Patricia, was convicted of first-degree murder in
1983 for hiring Weeks and is serving a life sentence.
   Weeks escaped twice from authorities in Ouachita Parish, La. He
committed the armed robbery in Shreveport after his first escape.
</TEXT>
