<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Fashion     03-21 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Fashion,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sequins, Cowboy Hats and Military Insignia Accent Some Winter
Styles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Models in glen plaid cutaways or sequined jackets
over black pants looked like emcees from the Folies Bergeres as
Italian Enrico Coveri threw a winter wear floor show to celebrate
his 10th year as a Paris designer.
   As for the skinny sequin dresses with hearts or fringes on
bosoms and the crinoline short puffy dresses, they more often
looked like Toulouse-Lautrec's dancers.
   His longer dance-hall dresses with striped taffeta skirts, moire
jackets and bodices laced up with velvet were more wearable.
   Coveri's show Sunday featured day looks with military details.
Reversible short capes in all colors, plaids and houndstooth checks
flew open over well-cut suits, either with short, full skirts or
pants with gold-buttoned military jackets _ sergeant's stripe
details stitched into the sleeves.
   Long pants or minis had the zebra touch, sometimes paired with
leather.
   Angelo Tarlazzi had a ``spaghetti Western'' show with some
strong ideas for day clothes.
   Boots and cowboy hats were worn with almost everything,
including the full-skirted belted coats _ black for daytime,
taffeta for evening.
   Some of the long and swirly-skirted coats in dusty pinks came
out with brown beaver collars and full beaver sleeves. Some of his
greatcoats were worn with gray or navy battle jackets and flounced
grey flannel skirts underneath.
   Another suit had a tailored jacket front and puffy sleeves over
slim velvet or tweed pants. Tarlazzi often topped pants with long
split or wrapped pleated skirts.
   Minis appeared in low-waisted royal blue and black or red
jersey, sometimes topped with wrapped shawls _ long a Tarlazzi
trademark.
   His new soft sweaters either had yoked fronts and black ribbons
wound through their hems or ``passementerie'' or tasseled
curtain-edging in bi-colored outfits.
   For evening, it was Western saloon garb, with puffy taffeta
skirts hitched up over boots, fitted fake fur tops with pointed
hems, tiered and ruffled skirts with short tuxedo tops _ over pants.
   Issey Miyake, the artistic Japanese with a flair for fabrics,
has loosened up his complicated looks to smoother styles for easy
wear.
   His triple-layered flowing jersey tent dresses in soft sky or
royal or grape blues, plum, gray and black left the body totally
unconstricted.
   Menswear styles looked pleasingly shaped or baggy. But feminine
notes abounded as well, especially in a short sheer crepe caramel
dress pleated all over.
   Miyake finished up with some trouser suits splattered with color.
   At Balenciaga, designer Michel Goma showed simple sophistication
in belted coats with pilgrims' or caped collars, suits with cropped
weskit jackets and full-skirted tweed suits with full lacy
petticoats showing underneath.
   At Dorothee Bis, the unpretentious styles were easy, young and
offhand, always colorful, with fuchsias, blues and bright greens.
   Her all-knit starters were slim polo-necked and short, coming
out in 14 colors with matching tights. To pep up some of the
dresses, she plastered them with triangles flapping from one point.
   Shorts suits and babydoll dresses with yokes put in a cheery
appearance. And evenings had glitter dusted on black or cocktail
suits with guipure or heavy lace backs and sleeves on blazers over
guipure skirts.
</TEXT>
