<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Minister-Crack     03-21 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minister-Crack,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Baptist General Convention's Top Adminstrator Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Florida Baptist
General Convention are in an ``uproar'' over the drug arrest of
their executive director.
   The Rev. John Taylor, 25, was one of 139 people arrested last
week in Operation Crackdown III by the Broward Sheriff's
Department, deputies said. He was charged with trying to buy crack
from an undercover officer, police said.
   Dr. Henry J. Lyons, a minister and president of the St.
Petersburg-based group, said Taylor has been suspended without pay.
That leaves vacant the convention's top administrative post two
weeks before the 500,000-member organization convenes its annual
meeting.
   Taylor's future will be discussed at that gathering, Lyons said.
   ``Everyone is in an uproar and an outrage. They don't know what
to think,'' Lyons said. ``We will offer him some sort of
rehabilitative help if he wants it or deems it necessary.''
   ``If proven guilty, we will have no alternative but to terminate
him from his office,'' Lyons said. The convention is an association
of 728 Baptist churches that considers itself the single largest
black organization in the state.
   Lyons said Taylor, who lives in St. Petersburg, was in Fort
Lauderdale on official convention business. He was arrested
northwest of Fort Lauderdale several hours after he attended a
service Thursday at Mount Olive Baptist Church.
   Lyons said he sent two ministers to Fort Lauderdale on Friday to
learn the facts of the case.
   The convention hired Taylor 16 months ago, recruiting him from
Bishop College in Dallas, where he was doing graduate work.
   ``He handles the nuts and bolts. He carries the program of the
convention across the state,'' Lyons said. ``He does his job
extremely well. We were quite satisfied with his job performance. I
have no reason to think he was using cocaine. It never dawned on
me.''
   A Broward County Jail employee said Taylor was no longer in
custody Saturday.
</TEXT>
