<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Celeste-Carlucci     03-21 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Celeste-Carlucci,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ohio Governor Asks Carlucci to Reconsider Guard Exercises in
Honduras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Richard Celeste wants Defense
Secretary Frank Carlucci to reconsider holding National Guard
training exercises in Honduras because of recent reports of
hostilities with neighboring Nicaragua.
   In a letter to Carlucci on Saturday, Celeste said he was
concerned for the safety of Ohio guardsmen after President Reagan
ordered ``combat ready'' members of the 82nd Airborne into the
Central American nation.
   Reagan sent the troops last week after Nicaraguan troops
reportedly crossed into Honduras in pursuit of Contra rebel forces
battling Nicaragua's Sandinista government.
   ``I urge you to defer this and all National Guard training
missions at least until the current highly charged situation is
behind us,'' Celeste said in the letter. ``If not, what assurance
can you provide that this is a neccessary and prudent training
mission for our Guard members at this time?''
   The governor also wrote that he believed the presence of U.S.
National Guard units in Honduras could undermine progress on
Central American peace negotiatons.
   Celeste wrote that he continued to oppose sending Ohio
engineering units into Honduras for exercises scheduled for 1989,
but pledged to abide by instructions of the Defense Department and
the National Guard Bureau.
   Ohio and several other states joined Minnesota in a lawsuit
challenging the Guard Bureau's authority to commit state guardsmen
to training exercises outside the country over a governor's
objection. A federal court in Minnesota last summer ruled in favor
of the Guard Bureau, but the decision is being appealed.
   The governor's press secretary, Debra Phillips, said the letter
was sent Saturday by an overnight delivery service to Carlucci ``so
it will be on his desk when he gets in Monday morning.''
   Copies of the letter also were sent to Ohio's U.S. Senators _
John Glenn and Howard Metzenbaum _ and to U.S. Rep. Edward Feighan,
all Democrats.
</TEXT>
