<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PoltergeistIII     03-21 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poltergeist III,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Studio Unsure How To Market Film Starring Late Child Actress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The recent death of child star
Heather O'Rourke has left MGM studio executives in a quandary over
how to market her film ``Poltergeist III'' without appearing to
exploit the 12-year-old actress.
   ``Normal adults and obviously fathers like myself might be very
offended,'' said Barry Lorie, MGM's senior vice president for
marketing.
   Miss O'Rourke died Feb. 1 of septic shock caused by a bowel
obstruction. She had completed the film, scheduled for release June
10, last spring.
   She was best known for her lines ``They're heeeeere'' and
``They're baaaaack,'' which helped sell the first two
``Poltergeist'' films.
   In ``Poltergeist III'' Miss O'Rourke's character, Carol Anne,
still haunted by ghostly beings, is sent to live with relatives in
Chicago.
   Although Lorie said the films generally appeal to teen-age
audiences whose members likely wouldn't be disturbed by Miss
O'Rourke's death, he added he could imagine angry letters from
adults denouncing an ad campaign that appears to trade on her death.
   The studio plans to test audience reactions to various ad
campaigns shown at screenings before releasing the film June 10.
   Lorie said MGM has also asked the movie's other main stars, Tom
Skerritt and Nancy Allen, to avoid interviews that would lead to
questions about Miss O'Rourke.
   Lorie said the studio is worried about tabloid exploitation,
particularly because one actor on each of the previous movies died
shortly after shooting was completed.
   Actress Dominique Dunne, who appeared in the original 1982 film,
was strangled by an ex-boyfriend in 1982. Julian Beck, of
``Poltergeist II'' died of cancer in 1985.
</TEXT>
