<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BuffaloAccidents     03-21 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Buffalo Accidents,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Injured, Seven Beefalo Die After Herd Ambles Onto Highway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Horse thieves cut a hole in a fence and allowed at
least 75 beefalo to wander onto the Florida Turnpike, leading to
five minor accidents, an injury to a woman and the deaths of seven
animals, police said.
   Five of the beefalo died in the accidents and two other injured
animals had to be killed by Humane Society workers, the Florida
Highway Patrol reported.
   The beefalo, part of a 400-head herd owned by Dr. Arnie Oper,
roamed through a hole cut by thieves and ambled onto the turnpike
extension north of Miami Sunday morning, said FHP Sgt. Alvis Chinn.
   ``What they're doing apparently is stealing the horses in the
early morning hours and they're leaving without fixing the fence,''
Chinn said.
   The accidents caused an estimated $18,000 to $20,000 in damage
to the vehicles involved, Chinn said. An unidentified woman who was
treated for minor injuries and released from Palmetto General
Hospital, he said.
   Motorist Shelley D'Errico said she slowed down when she spotted
part of the herd. When one started toward her car, she took off.
   ``My husband told me to gun it,'' she said, adding that her car
was unscathed. ``I don't know if my insurance company would believe
that a buffalo put a dent in my car.''
   The herd was rounded up by animal-control officers, passersby
and ranch workers, Chinn said. The beefalo, a hybrid of buffalo and
cattle, were valued at $1,500 to $1,800 each.
</TEXT>
