<2ND_LINE>PM-Cocaine Fire,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Set Afire Because Of Drug Debt, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who owed a $50 cocaine debt was
beaten and locked in a car trunk, then doused with gasoline and set
afire by angry drug dealers, police said.
   The 36-year-old woman, who officers refused to identify, was
taken to Alta Bates Hospital in Berkeley with second- and
third-degree burns on 15 percent of her upper body, police said. A
nursing supervisor who asked not to be identified said the woman
was in stable condition.
   ``This is my first time to find something like this in a coke
deal,'' said police Sgt. Roy Williams.
   Authorities said witnesses told investigators a group of men
confronted the woman Friday seeking payment of the drug debt.
   They said that when she said she couldn't pay, she was beaten,
thrown into the trunk of their car and driven away, then was
returned and set afire.
   Residents of one North Oakland neighborhood held a rally
Saturday to urge a battle against drug dealers.
   ``After years of slavery, job discrimination, the Depression,
Northern intimidation, lynchings and beatings, none of which broke
the spirit of the black race, a little white powder has come along
that has done more damage to the black community than any span of
history,'' the Rev. Ray Williams told listeners.
   Many homes in the area had boarded up windows and barred doors.
   ``What's happened to the neighborhood?'' asked Estelle Harmon, a
resident for 28 years. ``Name it. Everything. It used to be nice
and neat and clean, and now all of these dope people have gotten in
here, and I mean we are surrounded.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
