<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingBooks     03-21 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Books,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Want To Question Oscar-Nominated Writer About Huge Book
Find</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN LUIS OBISPO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police looking for overdue books
with fines totaling about $3,000 found more than 10,000 books from
libraries worldwide in lockers rented by the Oscar-nominated author
whose book became the movie ``Full Metal Jacket.''
   Police want to question Jerry Gustav Hasford, author of ``The
Short-Timers,'' said campus police detective Ray Berrett of
California Polytechnic State University, San Luis Obispo.
   A search warrant served by police from the school sought 87
overdue books that had been checked out from the campus library in
Hasford's name. Fines totaled about $3,000.
   ``We found a lot more than we bargained for,'' said Wayne
Carmack, another investigator.
   Officers found only seven campus library books, but seized
thousands of books marked as belonging to libraries as far away as
England and Australia, Carmack said.
   University police have been unable to find Hasford and question
him about the books, but have not sought an arrest warrant from the
district attorney's office, Berrett said Saturday.
   Officers took a weekend break from the mammoth job of cataloging
the pile of books, which measures 27 feet long, 5 feet wide and 5
feet tall, police dispatcher Suzi Goodwin said Sunday.
   Hasford, who recently lived in nearby Morro Bay, doesn't attend
the university but got a library card under a program open to state
residents, Carmack said. But the card was obtained with a false
address and Social Security number, Carmack said.
   There was no comment from Hasford; he does not have a listed
telephone number in San Luis Obispo.
   Hasford shares a 1988 Academy Award nomination for best
screenplay adaptation with ``Full Metal Jacket'' director Stanley
Kubrick and Michael Herr.
   He didn't appear Friday night at the Writers Guild of America
Awards ceremony, where he was considered for a similar award but
didn't win.
</TEXT>
