<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PoliceShooting     03-21 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Shooting,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Misunderstood Order Led to Police Break-in, DA Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A misunderstanding by officers resulted
in police breaking into the house of an elderly couple, where an
84-year-old man was killed in an exchange of gunfire, a prosecutor
says.
   The officers were supposed to knock on the door but thought
incorrectly that they were being ordered inside to capture a rape
suspect, District Attorney Andy Fuller said in an interview
published Sunday in The Times of Gainesville.
   Dillard Free was killed in the Christmas Eve shooting. Fuller
said Free apparently was awakened by the sound of his front door
being kicked down and fired two shots at officers.
   A grand jury on March 10 declined to indict the officer who shot
Free, but it expressed outrage about the shooting and called for a
review of police procedures.
   A Georgia Bureau of Investigation report on the shooting remains
sealed because of indictments against the two people who told
police the rape suspect was in the house. They are accused of
making false statements.
   Fuller said he decided to discuss the GBI's findings because
``the people of Hall County need to know this information.''
   Fuller said six law officers told the GBI they remembered police
Detective Robert Gable directing that they use normal procedure for
serving an arrest warrant _ that is, knocking and announcing
``warrant'' _ at the Free home.
   But the officers who took up positions in front of the house,
Lee West, Gary Lenderman and Kirk Williamson, were not present to
hear that order, Fuller said.
   He said that when Detective Russell Elrod told the officers by
radio to ``Go on in,'' Lenderman seemed surprised and asked, ``You
want us to go?''
   ``The evidence indicates the detectives did not mean for (West
and Williamson) to break the door down, but the evidence also
indicates that the uniformed officers felt they had been given a
directive to go into the house,'' Fuller said.
   West kicked down Free's front door and he and Williamson entered
the darkened living room while Sgt. Benny Patrick rushed onto the
front porch, Fuller said.
   He said Patrick saw a silhouette moving inside and shouted
``Police,'' but a shot was fired that narrowly missed his head. He
said West then also shouted ``Police'' and saw the figure fire
again, striking a door frame.
   West then fired two shots, fatally wounding Free in the thigh
and neck.
   Free's wife, Agnes, 73, was hospitalized for shock and died
March 5, three days after suffering a heart attack.
   The rape suspect the officers were seeking was arrested
Christmas Day in Texas.
</TEXT>
