<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Attack     03-21 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Attack,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Bombs Explode In Downtown Tokyo</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands as writethru to PM-BRF-Japan-Attack. UPDATES thruout
with details of second explosion.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A motorcycle, apparently rigged with explosives,
blew up today near the Saudi Arabian Airlines office and a car bomb
exploded near the Israeli Embassy about 15 minutes later, police
said.
   There were no reports of injuries in the attacks. Police said
radicals may have been responsible.
   A police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
motorcycle, with apparent explosives on its back seat, burst into
flames at about 7:17 p.m. near Hibiya Park and shattered windows of
the Saudi Arabian Airlines Tokyo office. The park is about a
half-mile yards southeast of the Imperial Palace.
   The police official said the second attack occurred near the
Israel Embassy about 15 minutes later when explosives in a parked
car's trunk exploded, damaging windows of nearby houses.
   He said there were no reports of damage at the embassy, about 3{
miles from Hibiya Park.
   The official said Japanese radicals, who sometimes fire homemade
missiles from cars parked in streets, may have been responsible for
the explosions. Further details were not immediately available.
   Last month, four shuttle buses used to transport passengers to
and from airports were burned in Tokyo in apparent arson attacks by
radicals opposed to the expansion of the New Tokyo International
Airport in Narita.
   Local farmers and their supporters, including anti-government
radical groups, have been resisting government plans to expropriate
farmland to construct a second runway at Narita.
   In May 1986, Japanese radicals fired homemade missiles at the
state guest house, the U.S. Embassy, the Imperial Palace, the Crown
Prince's residence and police headquarters in Osaka before a
seven-nation summit meeeting in Tokyo.
   One attack came during Japan's welcoming ceremonies for the
heads of government of the United States, Canada, Britain, France,
West Germany and Italy.
</TEXT>
