<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GarbageCrush 1stLd-Writethru a0514 03-21 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Garbage Crush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0514,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Garbage Truck Driver Shocked To Find Man In Compactor Chamber</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to delete extra `nearly'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PORT RICHEY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A garbage truck driver who thought a
cat had climbed into his compactor was stunned to find a man nearly
buried under loads of trash.
   Driver Michael Penton said he had taken on two loads of garbage
when he got out of the truck to adjust the next garbage bin and
heard a noise.
   ``At first I thought it was kids playing,'' Penton said. ``But
then I realized there are no kids there; it's all retirees or
professional people.''
   Then he thought a cat was stuck inside.
   ``I just climbed up the ladder on the side of the truck, and
there was this guy buried in the trash,'' Penton said. ``All I saw
was this arm and head.''
   Pasco County emergency workers disentangled Dale Berube, who
suffered a broken pelvis and other injuries in the Thursday
accident.
   Berube said he had been trying to retrieve an old rug from the
garbage bin for a friend who wanted it to line a doghouse. He never
heard the garbage truck coming.
   Nor did he realize what was happening until he felt the truck
pick up the metal box, he said in a strained voice Saturday from
his bed at Bayfront Medical Center in St. Petersburg. He was tossed
into the truck and the compactor was started.
   ``I was very lucky,'' said Berube, who has been having
nightmares about his brush with death.
   ``I thought I was going to die for sure,'' he said. ``It was
like squishing my body apart. I saw it coming back the third time
and I thought, `Please, God, please.'''
</TEXT>
