<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 0912EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SAfrica-Newspaper     03-21 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Newspaper,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Says Government Can Shut Black Paper During Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the country's most
militant anti-apartheid newspapers today lost a court appeal
seeking protection from government action, clearing the way for
authorities to shut it down for three months.
   Home Affairs Minister Stoffel Botha had intended to close the
New Nation in January, but the paper's court challenge delayed the
move. His office would not comment today on how soon he would act.
   The paper was launched in January 1986 by the Southern African
Catholic Bishops Conference as an alternative newspaper to reflect
``the daily struggles, desires and aspirations of the masses.''
   Published weekly with a circulation of 50,000 to 60,000, it has
a small staff, and gets many of its reports from members of
community organizations, trade unions and youth groups in the rural
areas where the majority of black South Africans live.
   Its editor, Zwelakhe Sisulu, has been detained without charge
for 16 of the 26 months of publication. The government has said he
is being held because of his journalistic activities.
   Authorities have banned four of the paper's editions and seized
two. Police have raided the New Nation offices, and it was the
first of six publications to be warned by Botha that they could be
closed or censored for publishing material he found objectionable.
   The paper does not claim to be objective. It's philosophy was
explained in the last issue: ``Journalists should not only report
on what happens in society, but should also help find solutions to
the problems of our country.''
   But the paper challenged the government to prove in court that
any of its reports were illegal under the law or the emergency
regulations.
   The Johannesburg Supreme Court ruled last week that Botha has
nearly unlimited powers to deal as he pleases with papers he feels
might contribute to unrest. The court specifically ruled that Botha
did not have to give reasons for his decisions or actions.
   The court said the paper could appeal. But today, the court
turned down the paper's request to keep Botha from closing it
during the nine months the appeal will take to be heard.
   The decision left the way open for Botha to immediately issue a
decree closing the paper.
   Acting Editor Gabu Tugwana said after the court decision, ``We
are pretending we don't face any suspension. If the deadline (for
the Thursday) edition comes and we are printed, good luck to us.''
   He noted that government gazettes, in which emergency decrees
are published, usually come out on Friday ``except in special
circumstances. We don't know if we are that special to the
government. They don't contact us. They don't have to.''
   Botha's power allows him to close a paper for up to three
months, or establish an in-house censor, but Tugwana said that if
the paper is closed it would only be allowed to reopen under even
more stringent restrictions.
   ``I just think the world at large, internally and externally,
haven't yet seen this seriously. It is an action against the whole
media,'' he said.
   ``There are many more axes hanging in the air that will fall on
many others,'' he said in reference to warnings issued against
several other papers. ``We are the first on the line because we
have lesser protection. As far as the government is concerned, we
are just a pamphlet.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880321-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 0922EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CommercialStrike     03-21 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Commercial Strike,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actors And Announcers For Commercials Go On Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actors and announcers who make commercial
went on strike nationwide today after contract talks were
deadlocked over cable television residuals and cost-of-living
adjustments.
   ``The Screen Actors Guild and AFTRA did begin a strike at 12:01
this morning against advertising agencies and producers of
commercials,'' said Dick Moore, a spokesman for the American
Federation of Television and Radio Artists.
   He said no new negotiations had been scheduled.
   The joint SAG-AFTRA membership numbers more than 100,000. The
unions negotiate together on the commercial contract.
   Talks on a new three-year pact between the performers and the
Joint Policy Committee of the American Association of Advertising
Agencies and the Association of National Advertisers began Jan. 11
in New York City and hit an impasse March 7.
   Union negotiators received a 93 percent strike authorization
vote from members just before contract talks broke off.
   Meanwhile, no new talks were scheduled between the 9,000-member
Writers Guild of America and producers to end that union's
2-week-old strike. They have been at a stalemate over residuals
from foreign distribution, creative control and a management
proposal to restructure residuals for one-hour television shows
sold into syndication.
   The commercial contract dispute centers on performers' demands
for a share of money made from commercials broadcast on cable
television and advertisers' attempts to reduce union cost-of-living
adjustments.
   Actors currently receive no residuals from cable television
broadcasts of their commercials after they have earned their first
$1,000 in payments from regular, prime-time television. Virtually
all ads shown on cable meet the $1,000 requirement, said guild
official Ken Orsatti.
   The unions recently sent telegrams to all U.S. presidential
candidates offering to grant them production waivers if they agree
to interim contracts conceding to the demands.
   The interim contract offer was given to regular advertisers as
well, and as many as 40 have said they will seek them, according to
the union.
</TEXT>
