<HEAD>Teenage Girls Arrested For Threatening, Robbing Two Elderly Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three teen-age girls have been arrested and
accused of terrorizing two elderly woman by pushing their way into
the women's apartment and demanding money while they tore the place
apart, police said.
   Tanya Williams, 16, and two 13-year-old females whose names were
withheld because of their age were arrested Sunday and charged with
first-degree robbery and first-degree burglary, said police Sgt.
Diane Kubler.
   The three teen-agers allegedly pushed their way into an
apartment occupied by 90-year-old Emma Otto and her 83-year-old
sister, Margaret Tellesen, on March 16, Kubler said.
   Tellesen said she let the girls in Wednesday when they asked to
use the bathroom. One of the 13-year-olds knew one of the women
through her mother, police said.
   The three scattered papers around the apartment, cut the
telephone line and threatened to kill the women if they did not
give them money, Kubler said. The three left after the women gave
them $50, she said.
   The three returned to the apartment Saturday, pushing their way
in and again threatening the women, the sergeant said.
   The three left after taking $300 in cash and two bank books,
Kubler said.
   Building owner Zack Kaimakliotis took the women to police after
the second robbery and detectives staked out the apartment.
   The three girls were arrested after they returned a third time
early Sunday. The girls told police they spent the money on
clothes, the newspaper reported.
