<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 0943EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-SuperfundWoes 2ndLd-Writethru a0483 03-21 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Superfund Woes, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0483,660</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 15th graf pvs, ``This is,'' with 1 graf to clarify that
assessment is not Locero's, but his paraphrase of company
statements.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's ``Superfund'' program
cleaning up toxic waste dumps should go back to its old policy of
seeking up-front payment commitments from polluters before
beginning work, an Environmental Protection Agency official says.
   Gene A. Locero says the program faces inevitable shortfalls as
it begins new cleanup projects before the polluting companies agree
to pay for the work.
   Locero is head of the waste programs enforcement office at EPA,
but plans to leave. On April 15, he will become a special assistant
to Administrator Lee M. Thomas.
   His gloomy analysis of Superfund's prospects appears in the
March-April issue of ``Environmental Forum,'' a publication of the
Environmental Law Institute.
   Locero's boss, Winston Porter, the assistant administrator whose
programs include Superfund, had not yet seen the article, his
office reported.
   For the first two years of the program, officials negotiated
with companies responsible for pollution at dump sites, trying to
win agreements to pay before substantial work was begun.
   But accusations of political influence on decision-making that
rocked the agency in 1983 and led to many resignations also led to
a new strategy _ if cleanup agreements aren't reached quickly, the
agency will start site investigations and cleanup work anyway and
seek reimbursement later.
   Amendments passed in 1986 that authorized an $8.5 billion
program over the next five years oblige the agency to start 175
cleanups by October 1989, and another 200 by 1991.
   Locero presented this worst-case analysis:
   ``If it is assumed that the agency will fund all the starts
itself, and that the average cost is $30 million for each action,
then by October 1989 the agency would need $5.25 billion for these
actions alone,'' and $6 billion more for the 200 actions to follow
by 1991.
   EPA now assumes each site will cost $21 million for cleanup
alone, not counting overhead _ an estimate that has more than
tripled in six years.
   Companies will obviously pay for some, but ``the agency's top
management officials do not dispute whether there will be a
shortfall, but only how much,'' Locero wrote.
   EPA now tends to seek ``all or nothing'' agreements from the
companies responsible for a site. The agency has little incentive
to craft the far more difficult agreements where some companies pay
for only some of the cleanup followed by court action against
recalcitrants.
   Locero says the court action is ``unlikely to be a priority''
and thus not much of a threat.
   To many companies that might settle with EPA, ``this is
equivalent to `shooting the volunteers,''' Locero wrote. ``This
dynamic, if not changed, reduces the likelihood that the agency can
look to (companies) for a greater share of the cleanup outputs it
is committed to.''
   Meeting the commitment means ``confronting the possibility once
again that outside observers, especially Congress, may criticize
the agency by slowing down cleanup by looking to more (company)
cleanups, or for entering into partial settlements that are too
favorable'' to the companies.
   The 1986 amendments recognized that remedial action may not be
able to achieve full restoration of every site, but ``some in the
agency fear that making remedy decisions that are less than full
restoration will provoke harsh and damaging criticism of the
program,'' Locero said.
   ``Unfortunately this has diverted attention to collecting more
and more data to justify decisions, which threatens to add more
time to the ever-increasing length'' of site investigations, he
added.
   Locero said the the agency must consider beginning cleanup
before the investigations are finished, and stop trying to make
cleanups that will be final.
   On sites that involve polluted groundwater, he said EPA should
consider installing pump-and-treat systems early in the first
months of a site investigation to capture the contaminant plume and
keep the groundwater resource from being polluted further and save
both time and money.
   ``In some cases, it might be just as appropriate ... to restrict
access as long as the result was adequate protection of human
health and the environment,'' Locero said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
