<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Defense     03-21 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Defense,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takeshita Says Japan To Maintain Defense Growth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita told graduating
military cadets today that Japan's military power should match its
economic strength.
   ``We cannot cope with a military threat or maintain ties with
our allies and gain their trust without defense capabilities
commensurate with our national power,'' Takeshita told the 410
graduates of the National Defense Academy in Kanagawa prefecture,
west of Tokyo.
   Takeshita's speech was his first at the nation's only defense
college since he became prime minister last November.
   Takeshita said Japan would use its military only for defensive
purposes and would never threaten other nations.
   He said Japan's defense buildup would be attained within the
framework of the Japan-U.S. security treaty, while adhering to
Japan's three non-nuclear policies. Japan bans the manufacture,
possession and introduction of nuclear arms into Japan.
   The United States has been pressuring Japan to increase defense
spending and take more responsibility for its defense. But some
Asian nations, which suffered from Japanese aggression during World
War II, have expressed concern about a Japanese military build-up.
   Takeshita said Japan's security ``will not be guaranteed by its
military power alone'' and called for a comprehensive approach to
security, including diplomatic efforts and efforts to maintain a
continuous supply of natural resources from abroad, academy
spokesman Nobuo Tsuchida quoted Takeshita as saying.
   Last year, Japan formally scrapped a decade-old ceiling which
limited defense spending to 1 percent of its gross national
product. During the current 1986-90 defense buildup plan, the
government says Japan's defense spending will total $119.87 billion.
</TEXT>
