<2ND_LINE>PM-Islamic Conference,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>King Hussein Calls For Moslem Nations To Back Palestinian
Protesters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein of Jordan today called on
Moslem nations to back protesters in the Israeli-occupied
territories and repeated that the the PLO must join any peace talks.
   ``The Palestinian people have a rightful claim on us to support
their uprising both on the national and international level so that
the uprising may bear fruit,'' Hussein said in opening a conference
of foreign ministers from the Organization of Islamic Conference.
The group includes 45 Moslem nations and the Palestinian Liberation
Organization.
   Hussein, a key player in any Middle East peace negotiations,
said: ``The uprising of the Palestinian people is not an end in
itself nor is it a transient coincidental event that will soon
wither away.
   ``It is rather an expression of the will of an entire nation to
fight for its freedom and right of self-determination in its own
land.''
   Hussein, in his remarks prepared for delivery to the conference,
gave no specifics of what kind of help he wants for the Palestinian
protesters.
   The protesters have been fighting Israeli occupation forces in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip in an outbreak of violence that began
nearly four months ago. The United Nations reports more than 100
Palestinians have died in that time from gunfire, beatings, and
tear gas inhalation. The first Israeli soldier was killed Sunday.
   Israel seized the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip from
Egypt in the 1967 Middle East War.
   In demanding that the PLO be included in peace talks, Hussein
parted ways with the United States, which subscribes to the Israeli
view of the group as an illegal, terrorist organization.
   Hussein also called on Iran to accept U.N. calls for a
cease-fire in its 7{-year-old war with Iraq. In the latest
escalation, the two nations have been hurling missiles into each
other's cities for the past three weeks.
   Hussein told those attending today's conference that the war was
a ``wound ... still bleeding and draining our resources and
energies.''
   Iraq has said it will stop shooting if Iran does. But Tehran has
said it will only comply with the U.N. appeal when Iraq is branded
the aggressor.
