<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0541,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Nicosia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fire Aboard Two Ships, 54 Crewmen Presumed Dead From Iraqi Attack</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with fire aboard two ships in
gulf. PICKS up 4th graf, `Iraq, meanwhile ...' EDITS to tighten.
CHANGES byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian gunboats today attacked a
Liberian tanker and a Spanish refrigerator ship in the Persian
Gulf, setting them afire, and Norwegian officials said as many as
54 crewmen were believed killed in a weekend Iraqi raid.
   Maritime salvage experts, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the blaze today aboard the 10,168-ton refrigerator ship
Iberian Reefer was ``fierce.''
   Salvage tugboats were racing to aid the vessel, but there were
no immediate word on casualties, the officials said.
   Gulf-based shipping executives said earlier at least one Iranian
gunboat fired up to 10 rocket-propelled grenades at the 61,762-ton
Liberian-registered Fumi, setting its engine room ablaze and
blasting holes in one of its tanks.
   The Japanese-managed tanker, laden with Saudi Arabian oil, was
on its way out of the gulf. The executives said salvage tugboats
helped the Fumi's crew put out the fire.
   The Iranian attacks today were in apparent retaliation for an
Iraqi attack on Kharg Island oil terminal Saturday.
   The Norwegian Foreign Ministry in Oslo said as many as 54
crewmen were presumed dead in that attack.
   Most of the crew were Iranians or Asians, although a Swedish
officer was among the missing.
   If the Norwegian report is correct, it would be the highest
death toll from an Iraqi raid on Iranian vessels since the
so-called ``tanker war'' began in 1984, an offshoot of the
7{-year-old Iran-Iraq war.
   About 480 ships have been attacked by one side or the other
since the war broke out. Until the weekend attacks, more than 200
seamen had been killed.
   Christen Puntervold of the Norwegian Shipping Association said
four of the 29-man crew of the tanker 253,837-ton Sanandaj had been
found alive after the attack Saturday.
   ``The others are missing. About the other ship, we don't know
for sure, but we are afraid it could be the same for them,'' he
said, referring to the 316,379-ton Avaj which also carried a crew
of 29.
   Both ships were owned by the National Iranian Tanker Co., but
Sanandaj's crew was enlisted by Viking Engineering, which is
Norwegian owned.
   Bahrain's Information Minister, Tariq al-Moayyed, called for
foreign naval forces in the region to guarantee the safety of
shipping lanes in the gulf, through which 20 percent of the
non-communist world's oil supplies pass.
   The minister, in an interview with NBC-TV urged the foreign
forces to ``reach a declaration ... that they will not allow
interference with freedom of shipping in the gulf.''
   Iraq, meanwhile, said it fired a long-range missile into Tehran
today, the 105th in three weeks, and that Iranian gunners pounded
its southern port city of Basra in an 18-hour artillery and rocket
barrage.
   There was no immediate report from Tehran of a missile strike.
   But the official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia,
Cyprus, reported that the missile was fired at 3:40 p.m. in
retaliation for the bombardment of Basra.
   It said there were ``heavy casualties'' in Basra, which the
Iranians were hammering in apparent retaliation for rocket and air
attacks on Tehran and other cities Sunday.
   Iran's official media said at least 33 civilians were killed and
65 wounded in those strikes.
   Both sides have fired nearly 250 missiles into each other's main
cities and border towns since Feb. 29, reportedly killing hundreds
of civilians.
   The Iranian news agency today reported scores of Kurdish
children, aged between 2 and 10 years old, were being treated in
hospitals for injuries suffered in Iraqi chemical bomb attacks
Thursday.
   The children were among 4,000 Iraqi Kurds Tehran claims were
injured in the Iraqi raids on towns captured by Iranian forces in a
new offensive.
   The Iranians have charged that 5,000 Kurds in the northeastern
towns of Khomal, Halabja and Dojaila were killed in the chemical
bombing raids.
   Iran claims it has punched 9{ miles into northeast Iraq in an
offensive launched a week ago.
   The Iraqis have admitted the loss of several towns in
Sulaimaniyeh province as Iran reported fighting still raging
between its Revolutionary Guards and Iraq's 5th Corps.
</TEXT>
