<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-CableRates     03-21 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Cable Rates,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Let Governments Regulate Cable Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to let states
and local governments regulate the prices most of the nation's
cable television operators charge for basic service.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that the
deregulation effected in 1986 by Congress and the Federal
Communications Commission left subscribers vulnerable to illegal
monopoly pricing.
   Most of the nation's 7,800 cable operators provide both basic
and ``premium'' services. For an extra monthly fee, subscribers
receive channels offering exclusive sports and movie programming.
   Basic service includes local broadcast stations and a few cable
networks such as CNN, ESPN and C-SPAN.
   Prior to 1984, the FCC allowed local communities to regulate the
rates charged for basic cable service but not for premium service
rates.
   Congress in 1984 enacted the Cable Communications Policy Act,
which lets local authorities regulate basic cable rates only in the
absence of ``effective competition.''
   Defining ``effective competition'' was left up to the FCC, and
the commission's definition paved the way for the deregulation of
basic-service rates charged by more than 90 percent of all cable
operators.
   The commission's rule says any cable system faces effective
competition _ and avoids local regulation of basic-service rates _
if television viewers in the area can watch at least three
different channels without a cable hookup.
   The deregulation took effect Dec. 29, 1986.
   The prices cable operators charged for basic service rose an
average of 10.6 percent during the first six months of
deregulation, according to a survey released by the National Cable
Television Association.
   The survey indicated that premium-channel rates dropped 2.3
percent during the same period.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here upheld the commission
rule and basic-service rate deregulation last July 17.
   The appeal acted on today was filed by lawyers for Connecticut,
New York City, the National League of Cities and the American Civil
Liberties Union.
   ``The FCC committed procedural and substantive errors that will
... pre-empt state and local governments of traditional cable rate
regulation powers and will expose cable subscribers to monopoly
pricing,'' the appeal contended.
   Lawyers for the commission and the cable operators association
urged the justices to reject the appeal.
   The case is Connecticut vs. FCC, 87-671.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880321-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1033EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Union     03-21 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Union,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Excamine Unions' Power in California Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to examine the
power of labor unions to fire elected officials for disagreeing
with union policies.
   The court said it will consider killing a lawsuit by a Los
Angeles area union business representative who said he was fired
illegally by the Sheet Metal Workers' International Association.
   Edward Lynn was elected to his position with Local 75 of the
Sheet Metal Workers union in 1981.
   He and other members of the local became increasingly critical
of how the union was spending its money, and organized a dissident
group that successfully defeated proposals to raise the local's
dues.
   The international association in 1982 placed Local 75 in
trusteeship and under the leadership of a regional official,
Richard Hawkins.
   Hawkins proposed a new dues increase that again was defeated,
with Lynn speaking out against the hike.
   Hawkins then filed charges against Lynn, and the international
union removed Lynn from office. He also was fined $2,500.
   Lynn sued in federal court in 1983, accusing union leaders of
firing him illegally and violating his free-speech rights.
   A federal judge threw out the suit but the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals reinstated it.
   The appeals court said that because Lynn was elected to his
position as business representative he could not be fired for
taking a stand against policies proposed by other union leaders.
   ``Lynn's removal was precipitated by his outspoken opposition to
the proposed dues increase, a position which also reflected the
view of the majority of the union membership,'' the appeals court
said.
   Its decision drew a distinction between an elected union
official and one who is appointed.
   The Supreme Court in 1982 ruled that appointed union
administrators are not protected from dismissal when there is a
change in union leadership. The high court ruled then that business
agents of a Teamsters union local could be fired for supporting a
rival of the man elected president of the local.
   The 9th Circuit court said Lynn's firing was a different matter
because he was elected, and that he cannot be dismissed by the
parent union to suppress dissent.
   ``Just as the international may not impose a trusteeship for
illegitimate purposes such as suppressing dissent, so it may not
use the powers inherent in a legitimate trusteeship for similarly
illegitimate purposes,'' the appeals court said.
   The case is Sheet Metal Workers vs. Lynn, 86-1940.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880321-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1047EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama 3rdLd-Writethru a0534 03-21 0804</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0534,0824</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Patrol Streets On First Day Of Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with details of strike. PICKS up
5th graf, `Aurelio Barria ...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shops and stores remained shuttered
today and thousands of soldiers toting M-16 rifles and tear gas
canisters patrolled the capital at the outset of a general strike
aimed at ousting strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Buses and taxis were operating normally, but many were empty or
were carrying fewer passengers than normal. Traffic was light.
   Many government offices appeared to be operating with limited
personnel, despite a government warning that public employees would
be suspended if they joined in the work stoppage.
   In the city's central business district, where six previous
strikes in the past nine months have had little effect, most stores
didn't open.
   Businessmen there have never before joined larger, wealthier
merchants and industrialists in a strike.
   ``We're sending Noriega a message,'' said the owner of one small
shoe store, who asked not to be identified. ``We hope he's
listening.''
   Helmeted soldiers in battle garb patrolled nearby. No violence
was reported early in the day.
   The government said the troops were deployed to assure transit
of buses and taxis and to provide security for businesses and store
owners that wanted to open despite the strike call by the National
Civic Crusade.
   Many of the transportation companies are owned by the Panamanian
Defense Forces and those that aren't require government licenses to
operate.
   Aurelio Barria, head of the opposition National Civic Crusade,
said Sunday the government may try to use an emergency decree to
forcibly open industries and businesses that close during the
strike.
   The indefinite work stoppage was called after Noriega, commandr
of the Defense Forces and the force behind the civilian government,
rejected a U.S. plan for his removal as ``unacceptable, illogical
and anti-Panamanian.''
   Noriega, who has been indicted in the United States on drug
trafficking charges, reportedly told William Walker, a U.S. deputy
assistant secretary of state, he wanted to remain in Panama and
help from a transitional government.
   Walker and Michael Kozak, a State Department legal officer, were
said to have offered Noriega freedom from U.S. extradition if he
sought asylum in a third country. They met with the general and his
high command on Friday.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, appearing Sunday on NBC's
``Meet the Press,'' said Noriega ``can't expect to have any say in
the transition.''
   The Panamanian government has responded to recent unrest with a
state of emergency allowing it to suspend civil rights and take
over private businesses.
   ``The next few days are the determinant time,'' said Barria. He
predicted the strike ``will be very, very successful.'' The Civic
Crusade is an umbrella coalition of groups seeking Noriega's
downfall.
   Barria also said Sunday he heard meetings had been held within
Panama's Defense Forces to discuss what to do about Noriega, and
Barria said he expected some action by the military this week.
   But Maj. Augusto Villalaz, who had been one of Noriega's
personal pilots before defecting last week, said Noriega had
loyalists and Cuban arms to keep him in power.
   Villalaz told ABC's ``This Week With David Brinkley'' on Sunday
that he had flown three shipments of arms to Panama from Cuba and
that Noriega planned to import 500,000 pounds of weapons.
   On Sunday, many Panamanians flocked to supermarkets to stock up
on food, flashlights and other essentials to last through the
coming strike.
   Barria confirmed Sunday he had met with the papal nuncio, Msgr.
Jose Laboa, but denied persistent reports that the church official
was mediating a solution between Noriega and the opposition.
   Barria previously said Noriega approached opposition leaders
with an idea for a ``Panamanian solution'' to the crisis that would
allow the general a future role in the military. But the crusade
rejected the idea, Barria said.
   ``We don't have anything to negotiate with him except his
departure,'' Barria said, ``the day and the flight number.''
   In Panama City's Pacific port area of Balboa, dock workers
striking because they have not been paid their full salaries vowed
to keep the docks shut down today. The union has run out of
emergency food bags and its 800 members have not received wages for
two weeks.
   Panama's already ailing economy was sent into a tailspin last
month after Noriega's indictment and the effort of then-President
Eric Arturo Delvalle to fire the general, who heads Panama's
15,000-member Defense Forces. Noriega allies in Parliament on Feb.
26 ousted Delvalle, who has since been in hiding.
   The Reagan administration retaliated by backing the freezing of
Panamanian government bank deposits in the United States, creating
a critical cash shortage in Panama, which uses the dollar as its
currency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
