<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-PhoneRates     03-21 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Phone Rates,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Asks Administration Comment on Case from Hawaii</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today sought the Reagan
administration's views of an appeal by Hawaii officials seeking to
roll back an annual $10.5 million increase in intrastate telephone
rates.
   The court asked Justice Department lawyers to comment on a lower
court ruling that the state lacks authority to block the higher
rates.
   The high court is not expected to decide whether to grant full
review to the case until hearing from the government lawyers, which
could take months.
   The Hawaii Public Utilities Commission in 1984 granted a $20
million rate increase to Hawaii Telephone Co., $10.5 million less
than the company requested.
   The company then filed a federal lawsuit, charging that the
reduction violated an order of the Federal Communications
Commission.
   Generally, the FCC regulates interstate phone rates while state
public utility officials regulate intrastate rates.
   But the commission in 1981 adopted a plan to reduce interstate
rates for phone users in Hawaii, bringing the charges into line
with interstate rates for people in the 48 contiguous states.
   The lower rates were to be phased in over four years in an
effort to avoid a dramatic impact on rates for in-state calls.
   The Hawaii Telephone Co. said the commission plan bars state
officials from imposing the $10.5 million reduction.
   A federal judge agreed with the company, and that ruling was
upheld last September by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   The appeals court said the commission properly pre-empted the
state's authority in this case.
   ``No one disputes the authority of a state ... to establish a
reasonable rate of return for utilities within its jurisdiction,''
the appeals court said. ``But ... (Hawaii's) adjustment here was a
fairly transparent and improper attempt to circumvent the FCC
mandate.''
   The appeals court said the commission has priority in
apportioning the cost of equipment and other expenses between
in-state and out-of-state service.
   The case is PUC vs. Hawaiian Telephone Co., 87-1152.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
