<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Access     03-21 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Access,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Turns Away Legal Dispute Involving Health of Former Sen.
Hawkins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today turned away a legal
dispute sparked by controversy over the health of former Sen. Paula
Hawkins, R-Fla.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the public
has no right of access to pretrial statements and other materials
generated by civil lawsuits.
   Lawyers for The Miami Herald had argued that denying public
access to all unfiled pretrial materials in civil cases violates
the Constitution's First Amendment.
   In a related case, the justices last November let stand a
Florida Supreme Court ruling that the public has no right to hear
or see pretrial statements, called depositions, given during
criminal prosecutions.
   In the case acted on today, the Florida court extended its
ruling on pretrial materials in criminal cases to depositions and
other pretrial materials in civil cases.
   Hawkins, who lost her Senate seat in the 1986 election to
Democrat Bob Graham, a former Florida governor, injured her back in
a 1982 accident at television station WESH in Orlando.
   She sued in early 1986, charging that the accident _ a studio
set wall fell on Hawkins while she was taping a talk show _ was
caused by the station's negligence.
   The lawsuit alleged that Hawkins' injury became a physical
handicap that impaired her ability to work.
   While pretrial proceedings were underway, Hawkins continued her
work in the Senate and actively sought re-election. But as a result
of the lawsuit's allegations, her health became a major issue in
the campaign coverage.
   In October 1986, about two weeks before the election, the
Orlando Sentinel sought to intervene in the lawsuit between Hawkins
and WESH and compel access to pretrial documents, including
hospital and medical records.
   Two other newspapers, The Miami Herald and the Florida Times
Union in Jacksonville, filed similar requests.
   Hawkins settled her lawsuit out of court in June 1987 but the
Herald continued its effort to obtain the pretrial documents.
   Under Florida law, those documents are not routinely placed in
public court files.
   The Supreme Court last July 2 ruled against granting access. It
relied on its earlier decision denying public access to pretrial
depositions in criminal cases.
   The Herald then filed the appeal acted on today.
   The case is Miami Herald Publishing Co. vs. Gridley, 87-1193.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
