<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1103EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Desegregation     03-21 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Desegregation,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justices Tell Appeals Court to Reexamine School Quota Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today sent back to a lower
court a dispute over a racial-quota integration plan for a public
elementary school in Chicago.
   The justices told the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to study
whether a challenge by a group of whites, Cubans and American
Indians to quotas at the Walt Disney ``magnet'' elementary school
has become moot.
   The court did not explain why it believes the case may have lost
its legal relevancy but the Chicago Board of Education contended
that the children on whose behalf the original lawsuit was filed
now are too old to attend the school.
   The Disney school was opened in 1968 on Chicago's north side to
promote integration. Students were selected by lottery to reflect
the racial, ethnic and economic composition of the area.
   The school is considered a ``magnet'' because it offers special
educational opportunities designed to attract a cross-section of
the community.
   Many cities in the nation have adopted the magnet concept as a
key element in integrating public schools.
   Chicago officials incorporated racial quotas at the Disney
school as part of the school system's overall integration plan
adopted in response to a complaint by the federal government
charging segregation. The city signed an agreement in 1980 with
federal officials, promising to implement a citywide integration
plan.
   The quotas at Disney were challenged in 1981 by parents of
Cuban, American Indian and white children. Those children were told
they would be admitted to the school but two months later were
informed they could not attend because the quotas had been adjusted
in the interim.
   The quotas require that white students comprise 15 to 35 percent
of the school's population, and that minorities comprise from 65 to
85 percent.
   The Disney plan was upheld by a three-judge panel of the 7th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. The panel said that Chicago's
citywide desegregation plan already had been upheld in previous
federal court rulings, precluding any attack on the quotas at the
Disney school.
   The students excluded from Disney ``are indeed necessarily
attacking the desegregation plan as a whole by challenging its
effect upon them,'' the panel said.
   The students' parents then asked for a review of their appeal by
all 10 members of the 7th Circuit court. By a vote of 6-4, the
judges refused to hear the case.
   Judge Frank H. Easterbrook of the 7th Circuit, in voting to hear
the case, said, ``Chicago has not been found to have engaged in
racial discrimination in operating its schools. Some such finding
... is essential before children may be shuffled from one school to
another on account of their race.''
   He added that the children who were barred from attending the
Disney school were being deprived of educational opportunities they
may be unable to receive at any other public school in the city.
   The case is Samayoa vs. Chicago Board of Education, 86-1503.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
