<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-King     03-21 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-King,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Revive Allegations Raised in Massachusetts
Governor's Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to revive some
allegations previously raised in former Massachusetts Gov. Edward
J. King's $3.6 million libel lawsuit against the Boston Globe.
   The justices, without comment, let stand rulings that three
editorial cartoons, one editorial and two columns King sued over,
did not libel him.
   The high court earlier this month cleared the way for a jury
trial on King's claim he was libeled by a Nov. 8, 1981, column
written by David Farrell, who since has left the newspaper.
   State courts threw out most of the ex-governor's claims in
pretrial proceedings, ruling that the sued-over comments and
cartoons amounted to constitutionally protected expressions of
opinion.
   King, who served as the state's governor from 1979 through 1983,
contended that he was libeled in various cartoons and articles,
most of which were published in 1981.
   ``Cartoons are seldom designed to disclose facts but rather are
ordinarily understood by reasonable viewers to be rhetorical,
exaggerated means of expressing opinions,'' the Massachusetts
Supreme Judicial Court said in ruling on King's suit last Aug. 17.
   The state court said the other articles ordered dropped from the
suit also fell ``within the ambit of protected opinion.''
   The case is King vs. Globe Newspaper Co., 87-1259.
</TEXT>
