<HEAD>Chambers Jury Returns for Fifth Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury today began its fifth day of deliberation
in the murder trial of a young man accused of strangling a teen-age
woman in Central Park, where they walked from a popular watering
hole.
   The jury returned to the courtroom this morning and listened to
a reading of testimony from Dr. Robert C. Shaler regarding body
fluid stains on the victim's jacket.
   During deliberations Sunday, jurors asked Justice Howard E. Bell
to restate the charges against Robert Chambers and asked if they
could take notes.
   Bell allowed that, but admonished the jurors to also listen
carefully. It is highly unusual for New York juries to be allowed
to take notes.
   Chambers, 21, is charged with second-degree murder in the Aug.
26, 1986, strangulation of Jennifer Levin, an 18-year-old woman he
had met in an Upper East Side bar frequented by affluent young
people.
   The jury could convict Chambers of the lesser crimes of first-or
second-degree manslaughter or criminally negligent homicide.
   The prosecution has charged that Chambers used Miss Levin's
blouse to strangle her, while his lawyers maintain he accidentally
killed her when she hurt him by squeezing his genitals during rough
sex.
