<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Salvador-Elections 2ndLd-Writetheu a0463 03-21 0779</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Elections, 2nd Ld - Writetheu, a0463,0800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rightists Win San Salvador: Early Returns Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with early returns showing
rightists trouncing Christian Democrats. PICKS up 5th graf, ``I
want ...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A resurgent right battered the
governing Christian Democrats in municipal and legislative
elections, according to early returns today.
   The result of Sunday's balloting, in which hundreds of thousands
participated despite threats of guerrilla violence, sets the stage
for a rough final year in office for President Jose Napoleon
Duarte, a Christian Democrat.
   The leftist guerrillas had called for a boycott of the voting,
and the sizeable turnout was hailed by politicians as a triumph for
democracy and a demonstration of civic spirit.
   The rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, won the
mayor's post in San Salvador from the Christian Democrats, who had
held the position for the past 24 years. They also appeared assured
of a majority in the 60-seat National Assembly, according to
projections made by local television stations.
   The Christian Democrats currently hold 33 seats. Arena has 13.
   The ``Areneros'' apparently benefited from a wave of popular
discontent with the Christian Democrats.
   Duarte was elected in 1984 on a platform of ending the war and
improving the economic situation. But four years later, the war
that has taken 65,000 lives grinds on, an estimated 40 percent of
Salvadorans are unemployed and inflation is running at an annual
rate of about 40 percent.
   Arena's campaign slogan was ``Change for the better,'' which
apparently struck a chord in the electorate.
   Prior to the election, the Chistian Democrats themselves had
conceded they would be set back by the vote, citing the natural
erosion of support experienced by a party governing in troubled
times.
   Arena national chairman Alfredo Cristiani told a news conference
Sunday night his party, if it gained control of the legislature,
would work with the Christian Democrats to resolve the country's
pressing problems.
   ``We will not present a systematic and capricious opposition. We
must look for unity regarding certain crucial points,'' he said.
   In the San Salvador mayor's race, Armando Calderon Sol, the
candidate of the rightist alliance, beat Alejandro Duarte, the
Christian Democratic candidate and son of President Jose Napoleon
Duarte.
   ``I want to publicly recognize that Mr. Calderon Sol has won,''
Duarte said at a news conference Sunday night. He congratulated the
Salvadoran people for voting despite threats of violence from
leftist guerrillas.
   ``This day was a glorious gesture of the Salvadoran people,'' he
said. ``We have defeated the terror and violence of the left.''
   The third party presenting candidates nationwide was the
National Conciliation Party, another rightist group. Leftist
parties declined to present candidates, saying the war made fair
elections impossible.
   State-run Channel 10 television, citing unofficial preliminary
counts, estimated 66 percent of the 1.6 million registered voters
had cast ballots. It said that, according to its projections, Arena
would win an outright majority in the assembly.
   Mario Samayoa, president of the electoral council, also hailed
the electorate for turning out to vote.
   He also said there had been no allegations of fraud by any party
from any polling station in the country.
   In a bid to disrupt the election, leftist guerrillas blew up
electrical lines, cutting energy to much of the country Saturday
night. However, little violence was reported during the election
Sunday, apart from rural skirmishes in the central part of the
country. No casualties were immediately reported.
   Power was returning gradually to some regions by today.
   Today was the first day since Friday that Salvadorans could
expect normal transport. The Marxist-led Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front, an alliance of five guerrilla armies, lifted its
3-day-old road travel ban as of midnight Sunday.
   The rebels had termed the election ``a farce'' and called for a
boycott.
   ``To vote is a duty, the way we demonstrate we are Salvadoran
citizens,'' said Pablo Castellano, a 38-year-old peasant farmer in
Nejapa, 10 miles north of San Salvador. He had walked 10 miles in
the blazing sun to cast his ballot.
   The guerrillas had warned polling places would be considered
``military objectives'' because of the wide deployment of soldiers
to provide election security.
   They had stepped up urban violence in the 10 days prior to the
voting. Three car bombs exploded in San Salvador, wounding three
people.
   Voters were electing all 60 members of the National Assembly,
the unicameral legislature, and mayors and town councils for 262
municipalities nationwide.
   The guerrillas, who have been fighting since 1979, demand a
share of power in exchange for laying down their arms. The
government rejects the demand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
