<DOCNO> AP880321-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1130EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-Obit-Reynolds     03-21 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Reynolds,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Senator From NebraskA Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sam W. Reynolds, a businessman who was
appointed a U.S. senator and served for seven months, has died. He
was 97.
   He died at home Sunday of pneumonia, a family spokesman said.
   Reynolds owned and operated Reynolds-Updike Coal Co. for 76
years until retiring in 1984. He also was a partner in Updike
Lumber and Coal.
   Gov. Bob Crosby appointed Reynolds, a Republican, to the Senate
in 1954 after the death of Sen. Hugh Butler. Reynolds did not seek
election to a full term.
   Reynolds was a city councilman in 1956 and 1957 and had been
city civil defense coordinator. He won the Nebraska amateur golf
championship seven times.
   Reynolds' wife, Louise, died in 1981. Survivors include a
brother, three daughters, six grandchildren and three
great-grandchildren.
   A funeral was scheduled Wednesday.
</TEXT>
