<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-WoundedKnee     03-21 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Wounded Knee,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justices Refuse to Kill Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, with four of nine justices
on the sidelines, today refused to kill a 13-year-old lawsuit
stemming from an armed confrontation between Indians and federal
agents at Wounded Knee, S.D.
   The remaining five justices, citing the lack of a quorum,
automatically upheld a federal appeals court ruling that clears the
way for a trial on allegations that the government's use of Army
troops in the 1973 incident violated constitutional rights.
   The suit names former presidential aide Alexander Haig,
ex-attorney general Richard Kleindienst and 10 other federal or
military officials as defendants.
   On Feb. 27, 1973, an armed group of Indians with grievances
about the federal government's handling of Indian affairs occupied
the village of Wounded Knee on the Pine Ridge Reservation.
   The FBI, U.S. Marshals Service and Bureau of Indian Affairs
police sealed off the village by setting up roadblocks. Before the
71-day standoff ended, two Indians were killed and a deputy marshal
was wounded.
   Fourteen people, most of them residents of the Pine Ridge
Reservation, sued in 1975. Their suit contends they were confined
unconstitutionally because Army troops helped maintain the
roadblocks and an armed perimeter around Wounded Knee.
   The suit relies heavily on a federal law, the Posse Comitatus
Act, that bans use of the Army or Air Force as a civil police force.
   Because the use of Army troops violated federal law, it also
violated the individuals' constitutional protection against
unreasonable government seizures, the lawsuit says.
   People who allege they were subjected to a constitutionally
impermissible search or seizure may sue the offending officials for
damages.
   U.S. District Judge Donald J. Porter in South Dakota threw out
the suit but the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated it in
1986.
   The Supreme Court last year agreed to review the 8th Circuit
court's ruling, and today's brief, unsigned opinion upheld that
ruling.
   The 8th Circuit court said the involvement of Army troops was
``affirmatively forbidden by a criminal law of long standing,
itself expressive of an authentically American tradition of even
longer standing.''
   While acknowledging that a seizure that violates federal law
does not necesarily violate the Constitution, the appeals court
said violations of the Posse Comitatus Act represent ``a special
case.''
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day
O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy disqualified
themselves from the case without explanation.
   The case is Haig vs. Bissonette, 86-987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
