<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-PLOMission 1stLd-Writethru a0494 03-21 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-PLO Mission, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0494,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Mission Defies Eviction Notice</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout with PLO defying eviction deadline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO defied an eviction deadline today
to vacate its U.N. observer mission under a U.S. anti-terrorist law
as the General Assembly met in emergency session to consider ways
to keep the mission open. A court battle appeared likely.
   The PLO observer, Labib Zehdi Terzi, made no move to shut the
13-year-old mission in a townhouse near Park Avenue and said he was
awaiting U.S. legal action against the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   ``Once we see what they do, then we will respond,'' he said in
the U.N. Delegates Lounge. He said last week that U.S. authorities
would have to drag him away.
   But no confrontation or physical move to shut the mission was
expected. The U.S. government said that if the PLO does not leave
the United States voluntarily, then it would initiate legal action
this week to make it move. But U.S. officials say they will allow
litigation to run its course.
   The United States has declared the PLO a terrorist organization,
but the United Nations recognizes it as the only legitimate
representative of the Palestinian people. It was invited to New
York by the United Nations.
   The PLO's counsel, former Attorney General Ramsey Clark, said
that if the United States files suit against the PLO, he will seek
to dismiss the complaint.
   Envoy Terzi said it is up to the United Nations to go to court
on behalf of the PLO.
   In the emergency session which started Friday, all speakers
denounced the U.S. move to close the PLO Mission and 50 more
speakers were scheduled this week.
   Today and Tuesday the assembly is scheduled to consider calls by
some delegates to take legal action on behalf of the PLO and to
house the mission on U.N. international territory _ off limits to
U.S. police.
   The PLO participates in all debates on the Middle East but has
no voting rights.
   Some delegates also want to move the next 159-member General
Assembly to Geneva in September or to shift the special session on
disarmament in May and June to Geneva, but such moves are unlikely.
   This week the assembly is expected to adopt a resolution calling
on Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar to take all necessary
action, including legal steps, in defense of the Headquarters
Agreement.
   The Justice Department was expected to initiate legal action in
Manhattan Federal Court probably by Wednesday to close the mission,
department spokesman Patrick Korten said in Washington on Sunday.
   ``We're ready to go ahead and file the papers if they don't
close the mission voluntarily,'' he said.
   Clark has said the closure order is illegal because it violates
the 1947 U.S.-U.N. Headquarters treaty under which the United
States allows U.N. missions to operate.
   Clark said the anti-terrorism law of 1987 and legal efforts to
oust the PLO are unconstitutional because they conflict with
international law. He said the U.N. Headquarters Agreement takes
precedence over U.S. domestic law.
   The anti-terrorism law was attached to a State Department
spending bill and requires closing the PLO Mission by today.
   The State Department and United Nations opposed the legislation
on grounds it violates U.S.-U.N. treaty obligations. Secretary of
State George P. Shultz called it ``a very bad piece of
legislation'' which unnecessarily glorifies the PLO.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
