<1ST_LINE>u w PM-NorthRetires     03-21 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-North Retires,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Approves Requests to Retire, Use Up Leave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Col. Oliver North's request to retire from
the Marine Corps later this spring has received final approval from
the Navy, Pentagon officials said today.
   North, the fired national security aide who was indicted last
week in connection with the Iran-Contra affair, also has received
permission to start using up his accumulated leave and will no
longer have to report for work at Marine Corps headquarters.
   ``Lt. Col. North began his terminal leave today,'' said Lt. Col.
John Shotwell, a Marine Corps spokesman. ``He had sufficient leave
on the books to cover the period from now until his retirement on
May 1.''
   North announced Friday that he had decided to retire from active
duty, saying the step was necessary because he would likely have to
subpoena ``the highest ranking officials in our government'' to
defend himself against the Iran-Contra charges.
   ``That strikes me as a course of action incompatible with my
continued service as a Marine officer,'' North said at the time.
   ``Accordingly, with great sadness, I have tendered my request to
retire from the Marine Corps.''
   North becomes eligible to retire with a military pension on May
1 _ the point at which he will have spent 20 years on active duty.
He automatically had the right to request retirement on that date,
but needed a waiver of a requirement that he provide at least four
months' advance notice of his plans.
   That waiver was approved by Chase Untermeyer, the assistant Navy
secretary for manpower and reserve affairs.
   North was reassigned to Marine Corps headquarters on the
planning staff in November 1986 after President Reagan fired him as
an aide to the National Security Council.
   North, former national security advisor Rear Adm. John
Poindexter and two others were indicted by a federal grand jury
March 16 on charges they conspired to divert Iranian arms sales
profits to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   The 23-count indictment, which also named retired Air Force Maj.
Gen. Richard V. Secord and his business partner, Albert Hakim, said
the defendants organized, directed and concealed ``a program to
continue funding of and logistical and other support for military
and paramilitary operations in Nicaragua by the Contras'' at a time
U.S. law barred such action.
</TEXT>
