<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-McCullough     03-21 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-McCullough,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Communist Fighter Hester R. McCullough Dies at 71</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRYN MAWR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hester R. McCullough, once a heroine of
the political right for her 1940s stand against entertainers
associated with communist causes, is dead at 71.
   Mrs. McCullough died at home Sunday.
   In the late 1940s, Mrs. McCullough, then living in Greenwich,
Conn., returned a $6 subscription ticket to a performance by dancer
Paul Draper and harmonica player Larry Adler, whom she accused of
being members of communist-front organizations.
   In a letter to the Greenwich Community Concert Association that
was published in a local newspaper, Mrs. McCullough wrote that the
entertainers, ``while fine artists, have been openly denounced in
the press as being pro-communist and, as such, I do not believe
should appear in any community project in Greenwich.''
   Draper and Adler sued Mrs. McCullough for libel, but they
decided not to pursue the case when it ended in a hung jury in
1950. By then it had become a cause celebre taken up by
conservative columnists such as Westbrook Pegler.
   In later years, Mrs. McCullough said she had no regrets.
   ``What I thought then, I still do,'' she told The Philadelphia
Inquirer Magazine in a 1987 interview. ``The communists themselves
wanted to destroy this country and its government.''
   Mrs. McCullough was born in Philadelphia, graduated from London
University when she was 19 and became a secretary at the former
Pennsylvania Military College, now Widener University.
   She married John T. McCullough, a Harvard graduate, who worked
for Time magazine.
   Mrs. McCullough is survived by a son, Bruce, of Hollywood, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
