<DOCNO> AP880321-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1221EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Ireland 3rdLd-Writethru a0539 03-21 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ireland, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0539,0771</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Policeman Slain By IRA</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 10-11, bgng, `In London ...,' with 3 grafs to
UPDATE with King announcing that policy about IRA funerals will be
reviewed. PICKS up 12th graf, `Concerning the ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish Republican Army shot
dead a policeman today, two days after a mob at an IRA funeral
killed two British soldiers.
   Police said the policeman was shot in the head in a jeep in the
Roman Catholic Creggan district of Londonderry, and died at a
hospital.
   The IRA claimed responsibility in a clandestine message to
Belfast media.
   The officer, whose name was not made public immediately, was the
23rd person and the second policeman to die in the British province
this year.
   Police sources said today about 30 suspects were being sought in
connection with the mob attack Saturday on two British soldiers.
The outlawed IRA also claimed responsiblity for the killings of the
soldiers.
   Irish and British newspapers said a police roundup of suspects
in Catholic strongholds in Belfast was imminent.
   Police made no formal statement, but the sources, requesting
anonymity, said suspects were identified by studying videotape of
Saturday's rampage, in which the two soldiers were beatend and
stripped naked by the crowd and shot by IRA gunmen.
   Three suspects were arrested immediately after the killings.
   In the Catholic Markets district of West Belfast, police seized
600 pounds of ``explosive material'' early today and said they
arrested a woman.
   In London, Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King announced today
an immediate review of its new policy of not policing Irish
Republican Army funerals following the killings Saturday.
   In all, five people died during burials or funeral corteges in a
four-day period last week.
   King said a ``massive murder investigation is under way'' in the
soldiers deaths.
   Concerning the search for the killers of the soldiers, a
statement by the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the Northern Ireland
police force, said only that, ``Inquiries are being actively
pursued.''
   But police sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
about 30 suspects were identified after officers scrutinized film
of the slayings.
   The British army said Sunday the two soldiers had ignored
general orders to stay away from the Irish Republican Army funeral
procession.
   The men's commanding officer in Belfast, Lt. Col. Martin
Roberts, said in a radio interview today that the men must have
driven into the area by mistake.
   ``Obviously, the soldiers drove into the funeral cortege by
mistake and tried to escape and in the process they were hemmed in
by the black taxis,'' said Roberts, who is commander of the army's
communications in Northern Ireland.
   An army helicopter assigned to film the funeral in Catholic west
Belfast hovered overhead as corporals Derek Wood, 24, and David
Howes, 23, were killed. King flew to Belfast on Sunday for
briefings from army and police chiefs and was shown the
helicopter's film of the attack.
   Ulster Unionist leader James Molyneaux claimed the two soldiers
were ``sacrificed'' to the new policy of not policing IRA funerals
while 500 members of the security forces were on standby in the
city.
   The Rev. Ian Paisley, leader of the Democratic Unionist Party,
also blamed the soldiers' slayings on the new policy. He called on
King and the police chief, Sir John Hermon, to resign.
   But Conservative lawmaker Michael Mates said scrapping the new
policy could mean more violence. ``A return to heavy-handed
policing could provoke riots, which is what the IRA want so they
can say to the world: they won't even let us bury our dead in
peace,'' he said.
   The mainly Catholic IRA wants to drive the British from Northern
Ireland and unite the predominantly Protestant province with the
overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic.
   On Wednesday, as security forces stayed away from Belfast's
Milltown Cemetery for the funerals of three IRA members slain by
British forces in Gibraltar, a Protestant gunman killed three
mourners and wounded 68 with grenades and bullets.
   The two soldiers slain Saturday interrupted the funeral of Kevin
Brady, 20, one of the three killed in Milltown Cemetery.
   A statement from the IRA, which said its members shot the
soldiers after identifying them, said the mourners thought they
were being attacked when the soldiers' car sped toward them.
   Sinn Fein, the IRA's legal political wing, blamed the British
government for the violence and praised those who beat the soldiers
for their ``bravery in protecting the cortege from attack.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
