<DOCNO> AP880321-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1247EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-AgeSuit     03-21 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Age Suit,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Take Up Age-Bias Suit from Pennsylvania</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, agreeing to decide an
important issue for all lawsuits alleging age bias in employment,
said today it will study the case of a laid-off Pennsylvania man.
   The justices agreed to decide whether Eugene F. Brieck's lawsuit
against his former employer, Harbison-Walker Refractories, should
proceed to a jury trial.
   Harbison-Walker, a division of Dresser Industries, sells
specialized ceramic brick products primarily to steel producers.
Brieck worked as an installation specialist for Harbison-Walker
from 1965 to 1982.
   In July 1982, several employees of Harbison-Walker's Iron and
Steel Marketing Support Group were laid off, including Brieck. He
then was 55.
   Brieck sued Harbison-Walker in Pittsburgh in 1984, contending
that he was laid off and not recalled to work because of his age.
His lawsuit pointed to a 39-year-old installation specialist with
less seniority who was not laid off until November 1982 and then
recalled eight months later.
   Lawyers for Harbison-Walker contended that the other employee,
Hugh Faust, was retained because of his more diverse work
experience.
   But Brieck alleged that such diverse capabilities played a very
small role in the job Faust performed.
   U.S. District Judge Gerald J. Weber threw out Brieck's suit,
ruling that Harbison-Walker had articulated legitimate,
non-discriminatory business reasons for laying off Brieck while
retaining a younger man with less seniority.
   But the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated Brieck's
suit last June 19.
   The appeals court ruled that an employer charged with violating
the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act cannot avoid trial
by articulating legitimate business reasons if the suing employee
presents ``a reasonable inference that the employer' proffered
explanation ... is unworthy of credence.''
   The appeals court added: ``The question is not whether the
employer's asserted reason is plausible, but whether there is also
evidence of record which, if credited, could render the reason
implausible.''
   In seeking Supreme Court review, lawyers for Harbison-Walker
argued that the appeals court ruling ``virtually eliminates summary
(pretrial) judgment in employment discrimination cases.''
   The case is Harbison-Walker vs. Brieck, 87-271.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880321-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1245EST</FILEID>
