<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Obit-Evans     03-21 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Evans,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jazz Great Dies In Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gil Evans, a composer, pianist and band leader
who made his mark with innovative arrangements with jazz great
Miles Davis, has died in Cuernavaca, Mexico, at the age of 75.
   Evans died Sunday of peritonitis while recuperating from
prostate surgery, his widow, Anita, said today in New York.
   Evans had been active until recently, playing at a New York club
in December and January. He went to Cuernavaca to recuperate from
his operation, taking his synthesizer to work on new compositions.
   An upcoming tour will proceed as planned, with Evans' son Miles
leading the Gil Evans Orchestra, Mrs. Evans said.
   ``Gil left tones of music to be carried forth,'' Mrs. Evans said.
   Jazz historian and writer Leonard Feather said Evans made his
mark with innovative arranging, particularly in three records by
trumpeter Miles Davis. The albums, ``Miles Ahead,'' ``Porgy and
Bess'' and ``Sketches of Spain,'' showcased Davis' cool style.
   ``They were really among the most brilliant orchestral jazz
records made by anybody,'' Feather said. ``He made brilliant use of
tone colors.''
   Evans was born Ian Ernest Gilmore Green in Toronto, Ontario, on
May 13, 1912. His parents were Australian and he grew up in
Stockton, Calif., starting his first jazz band while in high school.
   He led a band in Stockton from 1933 to 1938, and from 1941 to
1948, except for three years of Army service, he arranged for the
Claude Thornhill Orchestra.
   He experimented with bebop with Davis, Gerry Mulligan and John
Lewis, worked as a free-lance arranger in New York and gained
recognition for a reunion with Davis in 1957 that resulted in
``Miles Ahead.''
   In 1958 he started recording with his own band. His arrangements
always had a fuller, more orchestral sound than most jazz and swing
bands. In recent years, Evans had added electronically amplified
instruments for a more commercially acceptable sound.
   Evans had recently had worked on a record album with Helen
Merrill, and Davis told Mrs. Evans last week that he had written a
new tune, titled ``Gil Evans.''
   The upcoming tour included appearances at the JVC Jazz Festival
here and appearances in London and at the Umbria Jazz Festival in
Italy, Mrs. Evans said.
   A memorial service will be held in New York, probably on Easter
Sunday, Mrs. Evans said. Evans' sons, Noah and Miles, were with him
in Cuernavaca when he died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
