<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-DefenseCosts     03-21 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Defense Costs,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stevens Wants Japan To Pick Up Full Cost of Its Defense</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress should order American troops and
military installations pulled out of Japan unless the Japanese do
much more to pay for western defense, Sen. Ted Stevens said Monday.
   Stevens said that because of the strength of the Japanese
economy and its favorable trade balance with the Unite States,
Tokyo should be able to foot the bill for its own defense.
   ``The yen has conquered a great portion of American,'' the
Alaska Republican told a group of Pentagon officials during a
hearing of the Senate Appropriations military construction
subcommittee. ``Now that the Japanese economy is going full tilt,''
Japan should pay the full cost of keeping U.S. troops and
facilities in that nation, Stevens said.
   Stevens said he was ``putting the Pentagon on notice'' that he
plans to offer a bill next year that would require U.S. military
withdrawals from Japan.
   Stevens said his proposal would be similar to legislation which
was routinely sponsored _ and just as routinely defeated _ by
former Sen. Mike Mansfield, D-Mont., calling for U.S. troops to be
withdrawn from Europe. Mansfield is now U.S. ambassador to Japan.
   ``Mansfield was right,'' Stevens said.
   The United States has been pressuring Japan to increase defense
spending and take more responsibility for its defense. Those calls
have been particularly loud on Capitol Hill, where Japan has come
under increasing criticism for its trade policies.
   In Tokyo, Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita said Monday that
Japan's military power should match its economic strength.
   Japan last year formally scrapped a decade-old ceiling which
limited defense spending to 1 percent of its gross national
product. During the current 1986-90 defense buildup plan, the
government says Japan's defense spending will total $119.87 billion.
   Japan pays about 40 percent of the $5.9 billion cost of
maintaining U.S. facilities in the country.
   Richard Armitage, assistant secretary of defense for
international security affairs, told Stevens that Congress
shouldn't engage in ``Japan-bashing.''
   Japan is increasing its defense budget, Armitage said, and the
spending total ``is on the verge'' of passing the British, French
and West German defense budgets.
   ``We should look beyond the popular ally-bashing rhetoric of a
campaign year,'' Armitage said.
   Stevens responded that he would have offered his proposal this
year, but ``it shouldn't be an election-year issue.''
   Japan is now meeting all its mutually agreed defense goals,
Armitage said, and is building up its naval fleet.
   Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn., chairman of the subcommittee, told
Armitage that ``this burden-sharing issue is not going to go
away.'' The congressional criticism ``is the reflection of a deeply
felt concern among the American people'' that U.S. allies should do
more.
   On other matters, Sasser said ``there are good signs'' that NATO
will come up with a new home, probably Italy, for the 401st
Tactical Fighter Wing in Spain. The Spanish government earlier this
year formally asked that the wing's 72 F-16s be removed from
Torrejon air base outside Madrid.
   Congress has banned the spending of any U.S. money to relocate
the wing. Instead, the cost will be picked up by NATO.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
