<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PershingLaunch     03-21 0134</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pershing Launch,0137</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pershing II Missile Launches Successful</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Army Pershing II missiles were
flight-tested today at the Air Force space and missile test center
range.
   The missiles were successfully fired by NATO troops from West
Germany under battlefield conditions, said Dave Harris, a spokesman
for the Army's Redstone Arsenal in Huntsville, Ala.
   The Pershings have been banned from use under an arms treaty
signed by President Reagan and Soviet Leader Mikhail Gorbachev, but
the treaty has not yet been ratified by the Senate.
   The Pershing is a field missile launched by its own erector and
can be carried anywhere, towed by a truck. Each of the missiles
cost $4 million.
   The missiles were launched separately during the morning from
8:01 a.m until 11:53 a.m., Army officials said.
</TEXT>
