<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru a0525 03-21 0737</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0525,730</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 14 grafs new with Fitzwater comments; picks up 6th graf
pvs, Boren said. Deletes final 7 grafs pvs to shorten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
today the Reagan administration is ``very encouraged'' by a new
congressional plan to send aid to the Contra rebels, but said other
suggestions were also welcome.
   ``We anticipate signing on to a bill, in the sense that we want
a Contra aid package, and we are working to get the best one that
we can get,'' Fitzwater told reporters. ``I think something will be
very forthcoming very soon.''
   The $48 million plan, which would permit the delivery of as much
as $2.5 million worth of previously authorized arms and ammunition,
was proposed Friday by Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., and a
bipartisan group of senators. It came in the wake of President
Reagan's decision to airlift more than 3,100 U.S. troops to
Honduras.
   Reagan dispatched the troops Wednesday after Nicaragua's leftist
government mounted an offensive against Contra rebels along the
Honduran border. In his Saturday radio address, Reagan blamed
Congress' recent rejection of new aid for the Contras for the
Sandinista push against the rebels.
   Asked if the administration objected to anything in the new
proposal, Fitzwater said, ``I would say overall that we are very
encouraged by the Kassebaum proposal ... but we want to be open to
other suggestions as well.''
   He said the administration would hold talks with House Speaker
Jim Wright, D-Texas, ``when the time is right.'' Discussions with
other members would continue today, he said, but he refused to name
the individuals.
   Asked if the administration believed there was a chance that
military aid for the rebels would be approved, the spokesman
declined to comment.
   The spokesman said the Sandinista push against the Contras had
``improved chances'' for such a package because it had changed
minds on Capitol Hill.
   ``Events of the last week have left little to the imagination in
terms of what President (Daniel) Ortega and the Sandinistas are
really up to,'' Fitzwater said.
   Secretary of State George Shultz, offering the administration's
first comment on the Contra aid proposal said Sunday that it
``should go forward.''
   Commenting on NBC-TV's ``Meet the Press,'' he said the package
was ``a little low on money'' but under study by the administration.
   Representatives from Capitol Hill differed today on whether the
situation had improved chances for renewed Contra aid.
   Senate Intelligence Committee Chairman David Boren, D-Okla.,
said on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America'' that the U.S. show of
strength had ``helped the situation.''
   Boren said he was ``amazed that there hasn't already been more
action'' in advancing the plan.
   However, Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., a senior member of the House
Foreign Affairs Committee and an opponent of further military aid
to the Contras, said today that a favorable vote in the House is
much more problematic.
   ``The events of last week probably enhanced the possibility of
some kind of aid package moving forward,'' Hamilton said on the
same ABC-TV show. ``But there are a lot of obstacles to overcome.
It's very had to predict at this point.''
   But some in Congress say the administration, if it chooses to
back a new Contra aid request, must confront doubts about the
seriousness of the border clash and perhaps even a backlash in
Congress prompted by the sudden airlift of troops.
   ``There is ... a very serious lack of full trust here, which
goes back many years,'' said House Majority Leader Thomas Foley,
appearing on CNN's ``Newsmaker Sunday.''
   Reagan's national security adviser, Lt. Gen. Colin Powell,
denied Sunday that he had misled Congress when he briefed lawmakers
Wednesday. He acknowledged, however, that he had failed to mention
Reagan's decision in principle to send troops to Honduras if
President Jose Azcona requested them.
   ``We did not go into the specific options because we did not
want it all over the newspapers,'' Powell said during an appearance
on ABC-TV's ``This Week with David Brinkley.''
   The national security adviser said the fighting on the
Nicaraguan-Honduran border was ``pretty much over'' and offered
assurances that it was unlikely U.S. troops would become involved.
   ``The combat zone is rapidly disappearing as the Sandinistas
appear to withdraw, and I don't think there is any reasonable
likelihood that they would be anywhere near the combat zone,''
Powell said of the U.S. troops.
</TEXT>
