<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ModularMansions Bjt   03-21 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Modular Mansions, Bjt,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Techno Craft Builds Mansions `To Go'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto STC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>McELHATTAN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Want to buy a million-dollar mansion with
hardwood floors, chandeliers and a spiral staircase? A firm here
will build you one on its assembly line and ship it to you in
pieces on flatbed trucks.
   ``It's really an evolutionary thing for home building,'' said
George Oswald, treasurer of Techno Craft Inc., a 3-year-old,
privately held company.
   ``This business started with mobile homes, went to double-wides
and then two-story units. We said that's all well and good but
we're going to go ahead of that,'' said Greg Cunningham, the
company's founder and chief executive officer.
   Each two-story luxury home built by Techno Craft, which began
production last August, has hardwood floors, a spiral staircase,
chandeliers, a fireplace, jacuzzi, bidet and imported tiles.
Options include a steam room, sauna and an elevator.
   Cunningham, 35, started the Techno Craft in 1985 when another
company he heads had trouble finding an adequate supply of upscale
housing in the New York metropolitan area.
   ``This is really the answer to the housing problem in this
country, modular housing and done right,'' he said.
   Techno Craft produced 100 homes on its assembly line last year
and has orders this year for 450, he said.
   Oswald said the company will have to build another plant next
year to meet demand. He said they eventually want to make 1,000
homes a year for sale between Maine and Virginia and increase
employment from 125 to 700.
   Nationally, 51,000 modular homes were produced last year, up
from 39,000 in 1977, according to the 1988 edition of The Red Book
of Housing Manufacturers. Modular homes accounted for 2.8 percent
of the 1.85 million homes built in 1987, according to the book,
which based its findings on a survey of more than 500 companies.
   John J. Smolke Jr., chief of Pennsylvania's Division of
Manufactured Housing, a state regulatory agency, said a shortage of
skilled labor and greater profit for the builder have helped the
growth of the industry.
   But he said the industry still has to overcome the image that
pre-fabricated homes belong in the low-rent district.
   ``When people think of something built in a plant, they still
envision ... the typical mobile home,'' Smolke said.
   Cunningham said building homes in a factory has advantages to
building them on the lot.
   Homes built on site can take eight months to a year to build and
are subject to vandalism and theft, exposed to the weather and
dependent on local labor, he said.
   Techno Craft's factory-built mansions take eight weeks from the
start of construction to the day the homeowner can move in, and 95
percent of the work takes place in the factory, Cunningham said.
   Peter Cornell, president of Cornell Development Corp. in Albany,
N.Y., decided to have Techno Craft build 151 townhouses for a
development near Albany.
   ``They are the only people who can do in the factory what I can
with a real quality crew,'' Cornell said. He said Techno Craft will
do it at a lower cost.
   In the 480-foot-long Techno Craft plant, sections or modules of
a house are assembled along an assembly line with 24 work stations.
   Floors and roofs are constructed at separate stations to the
side of the assembly line and moved to the line by overhead cranes.
   The finished sections are shipped from the plant in central
Pennsylvania on six flatbed trucks and can be assembled in a day.
   After the sections are lifted onto a foundation with a crane and
assembled, siding is added and pre-cut molding and carpeting is
installed, Cunningham said.
   Oswald said modular homes from other builders require more
construction after they are placed on their foundations.
   ``It would take anybody else two or three years to get where we
are and by that time we'll be way ahead,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
