<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1333EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MarrowBrothers     03-21 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marrow Brothers,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leukemia Patient's Brother Does Not Have Bone Marrow Match</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leukemia patient learned today that his
bone marrow does not match that of his brother, a homeless Florida
man who had declined to undergo testing until he was offered $1,000.
   ``You kind of start counting on things and then you have a big
letdown,'' said Steven J. Chapman. ``I've just made up my mind not
to count on anything.''
   Doctors said they were presenting other treatment options to
Chapman, 31, of Oolitic.
   ``It's would have been a very rough treatment,'' said Dr.
Richard S. Fayssoux, the hematology and oncology specialist who is
treating Chapman.
   The patient's brother, Randy Chapman, 32, who was located last
month on the streets of Miami, initially refused to submit to tests.
   ``If he dies, he dies,'' said Randy Chapman, who earns his
living as the subject of medical experiments.
   Randy Chapman eventually accepted an Indiana philanthropist's
offer of a $1,000 testing incentive. The brother, who left home 16
years ago, would have received an additional $2,000 had there been
a match and subsequent transplant operation.
   Steven Chapman said doctors were checking into a partial bone
marrow match that was located through a national registry.
   ``We'll come up with something else,'' said Chapman.
</TEXT>
