<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Athens Taxis,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cabbies Arrested for Challenging Athens Anti-pollution Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 34 taxi drivers Monday for
violating anti-pollution rules that ban half of the capital's
15,000 taxis from the city center each day.
   A spokesman for the cabbies said they intentionally entered the
district to challenge the ban, which they dismiss as illegal.
   The ban is part of a set of wide-ranging restrictions limiting
traffic in Athens. The measures are aimed at dispelling an
eye-stinging brown smog that hangs over the city in calm weather.
   The taxi drivers were arrested because they brought cabs with
even license-plate numbers into the 5-square-mile central zone on a
day reserved for odd-numbered vehicles, said a spokesmen for the
traffic police.
   Nikos Stekas, a spokesman for the Athens Taxi Drivers Union,
said cabbies will defy the ban every day, claiming it cuts their
income in half.
   The taxi drivers face a one-year jail term or a $370 fine,
police said. They could also lose their operating permits for a
month.
</TEXT>
