<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1333EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham-Legislature Bjt   03-21 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham-Legislature, Bjt,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Impeachment Distracts Lawmakers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto covering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Rep. Bill English takes along a
portable television set and earplug when he goes to the House floor
to vote.
   Other lawmakers cluster around a lobby television set or around
TVs and radios in their offices, so focused on them that House
leaders sometimes need six quorum calls to transact business.
   The House is virtually at a standstill, with five members
working as the board of managers for the Senate's impeachment trial
of Gov. Evan Mecham and the 55 others fascinated by testimony that
has included an alleged death threat, sexual affairs, political
paybacks and the governor himself.
   The trial entered its fourth week Monday, and the Senate has
considered only one of three charges against Mecham, a first-term
Republican who is the first U.S. governor to be impeached in six
decades and the first ever in Arizona.
   Many House committees canceled meetings last week for lack of
bills the chairmen wanted to consider, and the House moved to a
three-day week beginning Monday, down from four-day work weeks.
   The 30-member Senate, meanwhile, has scheduled night committee
meetings in an effort to act on the relatively few key areas
lawmakers want to address this session: the budget, taxes, air
pollution and indigent health care.
   Regular sessions are supposed to last 100 days, which generally
would mean ending in late April. But pressure to close does not
begin in earnest until per diem pay is cut in half after 110 days
and stops altogether after 120 days.
   Lawmakers say the pace has been especially slow this year,
despite promises from the House Republican leadership that things
would start moving once the House finished pre-impeachment hearings
and sent the matter to the Senate.
   ``It's not been a terribly productive year so far,'' says House
Minority Leader Art Hamilton, a Democrat from Phoenix.
   ``It's the most difficult session I've seen in 16 years, and it
doesn't seem to be getting any better,'' he added, citing ``a lot
more emotion than probably action.''
   Republican leaders acknowledge that impeaching a fellow
Republican has taken its toll on party unity. Hamilton and others
note the inaction on major bills and the concentration on issues
such as a resolution telling Congress that Soviet troops should
quit Angola.
   Other committee chairmen, meanwhile, have continued to limit
debate, prompting a series of walkouts by Democrats who complain
that important bills are not being given a full hearing.
   Republican leaders say they have been trying to keep the session
as normal as possible, but Hamilton said he thinks lawmakers should
take advantage of the spare time to look in-depth at issues such as
taxes, Arizona's Medicaid alternative and pollution, which normally
get resolved on a rush basis due to the press of other business.
   But because most House members are watching the trial, Hamilton
said, the House is doing little other its ``normal work at a much
slower pace.''
   It's tough to compete with the soap-opera draw of the
impeachment trial.
   Mecham is charged with ordering the Department of Public Safety
director not to cooperate with an investigation of the alleged
threat by a state official against a former Mecham aide. The aide
was about to testify before a state grand jury on the governor's
unreported $350,000 campaign loan.
   Mecham also is accused in the impeachment trial of concealing
the loan and misusing $80,000 in state funds by loaning the money
to his auto dealership.
   Mecham has said he will be exonerated.
   A two-thirds vote of the Senate is required to convict Mecham,
and lawmakers also could bar him from public office. Mecham also
faces an April 21 criminal trial on charges of concealing the
campaign loan, and a May 17 recall election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880321-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1335EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0430 03-21 0871</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0430,860</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 8 grafs new, picking up 3rd graf pvs, We have. Deletes
last 4 grafs pvs to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department today complained of
massive Soviet arms shipments to Nicaragua as the war in the
Central American country cast a shadow over the visit of Foreign
Minsiter Eduard A. Shevardnadze even before he opened talks here.
   Charles E. Redman, the department spokesman, said the Soviets
shipped over 3,000 tons of equipment to the Sandinista government
in January and February alone.
   For a number of years, the Soviets have supplied Nicaragua with
$500 million to $600 million in assistance annually, he said. ``I
certainly don't see it as an issue heating up,'' Redman said. But,
he said Soviet military support is a ``continuing cause for
concern.''
   In another development before Shevardnadze opened talks with
Secretary of State George P. Shultz late in the day, the White
House confirmed that there could be two superpower summit meetings
this year.
   Signing a treaty to sharply reduce strategic nuclear weapons
this spring in Moscow ``is our goal,'' presidential spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater said.
   ``We are hopeful, but there is no guarantee that we'll have a
START agreement ready to sign at the summit,'' he said.
   Therefore, Fitzwater said, Reagan told the International Herald
Tribune last Friday in an interview that ``if there was an
agreement later sure we'd find some way to sign it.''
   While the administration complained about Soviet military aid to
Nicaragua, Shevardnadze was bound to register Moscow's irritation
over the dispatch of 3,200 American troops to Honduras.
   ``We have quite a few problems,'' the Soviet foreign minister
said on his arrival Sunday for three days of talks with Shultz and
a session with President Reagan at the White House. He singled out
the situation in Central America as `'rather grave and of some
serious concern to us.''
   Also, an impasse has developed in negotiations, held in Geneva
under United Nations auspices, for the withdrawal of an estimated
120,000 Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   Still, the visit may produce a date for the next superpower
summit _ speculation centers on late May in Moscow _ and some
progress toward a treaty to sharply reduce U.S. and Soviet
long-range nuclear weapons.
   The treaty is the projected centerpiece for Reagan's fourth
meeting with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev. But negotiations
in Geneva have proceeded slowly.
   ``It's by no means in the bag,'' Shultz said Sunday of the
accord that would reduce by 30 percent to 50 percent the overall
arsenals of U.S. and Soviet long-range bombers, missiles and
submarines.
   ``It's possible, but we're not going to try to have one just for
the sake of a treaty,'' Shultz said on NBC-TV. ``We'll only be
willing to go forward; the president will, if it's something we
regard as good.''
   Shevardnadze, in a statement on his arrival at Andrews Air Force
Base, outside Washington, said he was optimistic about arranging
Reagan's visit.
   ``I think we will be able to decide about the date,'' he said,
then added, ``We have to work hard; we have to work intently.''
   U.S. and Soviet negotiators have been working on drafts for the
strategic arms reduction treaty. One would deal with how nuclear
weapons will be scrapped, another with verifying compliance with
the accord.
   The two sides have exchanged drafts in the past month on how
they would inspect each other's missile sites and make sure
cutbacks are carried out. Shultz and Shevardnadze are also due to
review the procedures for reducing nuclear arsenals.
   The procedures are likely to follow the pattern of the treaty to
ban intermediate-range nuclear missiles. But verification is
considered a more difficult problem since not all the long-range
weapons would be scrapped.
   Shultz indicated strongly that Reagan would go to Moscow to see
Gorbachev _ with or without a treaty to sign.
   ``I think it is important that summit meetings have content,''
he said. ``But it's also true that we are now evolving into a
process where, perhaps, they will come to be a little more normal.
... There are plenty of things on our plate right now that could
come to fruition other than the strategic arms treaty.''
   Reagan, in an interview published in the International Herald
Tribune, said he was willing to meet with Gorbachev a second time
this year if the negotiations for a strategic arms treaty could not
be completed by the summit later this spring.
   Shevardnadze, after resting from his long flight from Moscow,
arranged for a late afternoon meeting with Shultz today. They will
meet again on Tuesday and Wednesday. His call on Reagan at the
White House tentatively is scheduled for Wednesday.
   Shultz and Shevardnadze have been meeting monthly to plan for
the summit. Improving the human rights situation in the Soviet
Union and soliciting Soviet support for an international arms
embargo against Iran also are among the U.S. goals.
   In the meantime, the wars in Nicaragua and Afghanistan
underscore U.S.-Soviet rivalries.
   Guerrillas in both countries are fighting with U.S. weapons
against Marxist governments equipped by the Soviet Union. The
Reagan administration last week turned the heat up in Central
America by sending troops to Honduras.
</TEXT>
