<HEAD>Utah And Colorado Congressmen Announce Re-election Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Republican congressmen _ Dan Schaefer of Colorado and Howard
Nielson of Utah _ announced Monday they are running for re-election
to their fourth terms in office.
   Schaefer, 52, was first elected to Congress from Colorado's 6th
District to serve out the term of former astronaut Jack Swigert,
who was elected in 1982 but died before he could be seated.
   He said this might be his toughest contest if former state Sen.
Martha Ezzard, a former Republican turned Democrat, gets in the
race. She has expressed interest but has not formally announced.
   Nielson, 63, former Utah speaker of the House and one-time
statistics professor at Brigham Young University, won his last
election by a 2-1 margin.
   So far, one Democrat, unsuccessful 1984 U.S. Senate candidate
Craig Oliver, has announced he will challenge Nielson.
