<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PershingLaunch     03-21 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pershing Launch,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pershing 2 Missile Launches Successful</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Army Pershing 2 missiles,
banned from deployment under a treaty with the Soviets, were
test-fired Monday.
   The unarmed missiles were successfully fired under battlefield
conditions by NATO troops, normally based in West Germany, an Army
spokesman said. The tests went off separately from 8:01 a.m. to
11:53 a.m., Army officials said.
   The Pershings have been banned from use under an arms treaty
signed Dec. 8 by President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev, but the treaty has not been ratified by the Senate, a
move that could come in late spring.
   The Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces, or INF, treaty, calls for
the destruction of all missiles with a range of 300 to 3,400 miles.
   Six of the Pershings were tested Feb. 15 at Cape Canaveral Air
Force Station, near the Kennedy Space Center, said Capt. Ken
Warren, an Air Force spokesman.
   The treaty does not require either side to withdraw or destroy
missiles until it has been ratified by both governments.
   The Pershing is a field missile _ each of which costs $4 million
_ launched from its own assembly that can be carried by a truck.
</TEXT>
