<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1427EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Fees     03-21 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Fees,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blackmun Criticizes Denver Lawyer Over Fees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Supreme Court justice Monday criticized a
Denver lawyer over the fees he is charging as the court's ``special
master'' in a case.
   Justice Harry A. Blackmun, dissenting from a court order
granting Charles J. Meyers $69,661.25 in interim fees, complained
about the hourly rates many large law firms charge their clients.
   Meyers, a former dean of Stanford Law School, is a partner in
the Denver office of the Los Angeles-based law firm of Gibson, Dunn
& Crutcher.
   Meyers in 1984 was appointed as special master in a
still-pending dispute between Texas and New Mexico over use of
Pecos River water.
   Texas is being allowed to ``sue'' New Mexico in the Supreme
Court before the case has been heard by any lower court. In such
cases, the justices invoke the court's ``original jurisdiction''
and hire a special master to conduct hearings and make
recommendations.
   The case, in varying forms, has been before the high court since
1975.
   Meyers' submitted bill of over $69,000 represents work he and an
associate of his law firm, Diana Poole, have devoted to the case
since late 1986.
   Meyers' bill, to be paid by Texas and New Mexico, reflects
compensation averaging $275.12 an hour for himself and $191.30 for
Ms. Poole.
   In his dissenting opinion, Blackmun notes that many of the 246
hours Ms. Poole spent working on the case represented getting
herself familiar with the legal issues. Another associate in
Meyers' law firm, Steven Crafton, had been assigned similar duties
before leaving the firm's Denver office.
   ``It seems apparent _ indeed (Meyers) so concedes when he
describes the nature of the `early months' of her work on the case
_ that a substantial amount of Ms. Poole's time was self-education
... and was duplicative background work already performed by ...
Crafton,'' Blackmun said.
   ``The consequences of Crafton's departure hardly are to be
charged to these litigants,'' Blackmun added.
   He added: ``It also is difficult for me to accept the fact that
in Denver, Colo., this partner's time is now worth $290 an hour,
having been increased from $265 on Nov. 1, 1987, and that the time
of Ms. Poole is now worth $200 an hour, having been elevated from
$170 beginning Nov. 1, 1987.
   ``It seems to me that `establishment' law firms are doing
themselves and the public a disservice by asserting fees of this
magnitude so persistently over dissents from the court.
   ``Public dissatisfaction with lawyers is not unknown; neither is
public distrust of lawyers. A fee application of this kind tends to
build that dissatisfaction and that distrust,'' Blackmun said.
   The case is Texas vs. New Mexico, 65 Original.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
