<HEAD>Man Shot Behind Wheel of Limo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman in a black helmet shot dead the driver
of a stretch limousine parked on a Greenwich Village street Monday,
then roared away on a motorcycle into rush-hour traffic, police
said.
   ``The indications we see here are symptomatic of a mob hit,''
Assistant Police Chief Aaron Rosenthal said at the scene.
   ``Obviously, they knew who they were shooting at. They were very
cool about it and very gutsy,'' he said. ``I would characterize it
as cool, gutsy and professional and deliberate.''
   Rosenthal said he had little information on the victim,
limousine owner-driver Gregory DeCurtis, 29, who lived across the
street from the shooting scene.
   His cream-colored Cadillac was parked outside a cafe when two
men, both wearing black helmets, sped up on a red and white
motorcycle at 8:20 a.m., police said.
   One man dismounted and fired five shots into the closed driver's
window, striking DeCurtis three times in the arm and once in the
back, police said. The man then got back on the bike and fled.
   A passenger in the front seat, a man in his late 20s, was
unhurt; his name was not released, said Officer Hugh Barry.
