<2ND_LINE>PM-Honduras Protest, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0650,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>225 Arrested In SF Protest Against Troops in Central America</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top graf ups arrests to 225</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police moved in on a crowd of more than 500
people demonstrating today against U.S. military presence in
Central America, arresting an estimated 225 protesters who tried to
block the entrance to the Federal Building.
   Baton-wielding officers began rounding up demonstrators after
police Capt. William Welch warned the crowd they were gathered
illegally and ordered them to disperse.
   Demonstrators hurled newspaper vending boxes and other debris
into the street, trying to disrupt traffic and stay one step ahead
of helmeted police.
   Shouts of ``No Contra aid'' and ``U.S., CIA, out of Nicaragua,''
filled the air as the demonstrators circled in front of the closed
main entrance while early arrivals for work got in through another
door.
   But the crowd quickly moved to that entrance, holding aloft a
6-foot-long sign reading, ``This building closed for renovation of
morals.''
   Some demonstrators tried disrupting traffic, wandering in the
path of cars and forcing them to swerve or stop. In one instance, a
demonstrator fled, leaving behind a small yellow scooter, which an
officer picked up and hurled into the gutter.
   Most of those arrested were cited for taking part in an illegal
assembly.
   ``We're not going to stop these protests because we want people
to know we are seriously committed to stopping U.S. intervention in
Central America,'' said Bill Nygren, a spokesman for Pledge of
Resistance, one of several groups sponsoring the demonstrations.
   On Friday, about 250 people were arrested when they encircled
the building and tried to stop 5,000 federal workers from entering.
   Today's effort follows a protest through city streets Saturday
night by at least 5,000 people, where _ at one point _ several
hundred protesters battled police for 25 minutes after a fire was
lighted in the street.
   Since Thursday, 278 people have been arrested during troop
deployment protests in San Francisco. Most of those arrested were
cited for failure to disperse at an unlawful assembly, said Sgt.
Dave Ambrose.
   Last Wednesday, Reagan ordered 3,200 troops, 1,100 of them Fort
Ord near Monterey, into Honduras to counter the reported presence
of Nicaraguan soldiers in that country.
</TEXT>
