<HEAD>Explosion Hits Four-Story Apartment Building; 1 Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion ripped through a four-story
apartment building in Moslem west Beirut on Monday night, killing
one man and injuring four others, police said.
   Investigators were trying to determine the cause of the 7 p.m.
blast in the low-income, predominantly Sunni Moslem district of
Tarik Jedideh.
   ``Some surviving tenants claim it was a gas cylinder explosion
and others say it was a small bomb that went off on the
staircase,'' a police captain said
   The explosion wrecked the northern front of the building, but
all four apartments remained intact.
   The dead man was identified as Mohammed Kurdi, 85, the
landlord's father.
   His grandson, also named Mohammed Kurdi, shouted: ``It's him!
It's my grandfather!'' when civil defense rescuers found the body
in the debris.
   Rescuers rushed to the scene after the explosion. All the
tenants had been accounted for.
   In Tripoli, 50 miles north of Beirut, an unfinished eight-story
building collapsed at daybreak, burying six construction workers,
police said.
   One man was rescued after six hours. Although rescue teams
reported hearing moans beneath the wreckage, hopes were fading at
nightfall that any of the other five would be found alive.
   It was not known why the building collapsed.
