<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Salvador     03-21 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Salvador,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Calls Salvadoran Elections a Victory for Democracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Monday hailed El
Salvador's national elections, calling them a strong victory for
the democratic process in that country.
   Department spokesman Charles Redman said some experienced
observers described Sunday's balloting as being the most well run
and secure of the five elections held in El Salvador since
democracy was restored in 1982.
   ``There was virtually no evidence of election fraud or
pre-election violence by any of the contending parties,'' Redman
said.
   ``The strong turnout, apparently around 70 percent, in the face
of a concerted guerrilla campaign of terrorism and intimidation
should make it clear that the vast majority of the Salvadoran
people reject the revolutionary violence and rhetoric of the
communist guerrillas,'' he said.
   The election produced sizable gains by a rightist party, one of
whose leaders, Roberto D'Aubuisson, has been denied a U.S. visa
from time to time because of his alleged association with death
squad groups.
   Redman was asked whether the United States had any reservations
about the outcome of the elections.
   ``Our basic policy is that we don't choose sides in these kinds
of elections,'' Redman said. ``The U.S. government is committed to
the support and the consolidation of democratic government in El
Salvador, no matter which party wins power through free and fair
elections.''
</TEXT>
