<2ND_LINE>AM-Marrow Brothers,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brother's Bone Marrow Doesn't Match, Other Options Sought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leukemia patient learned Monday his bone
marrow does not match that of his brother, a homeless Florida man
who had refused to undergo testing until an anonymous donor offered
him $1,000.
   Stephen L. Chapman, 38, said that although he was disappointed
the marrow was not suitable for transplant, he had tried not to get
his hopes too high.
   ``You kind of start counting on things and then you have a big
letdown,'' said Chapman. ``I've just made up my mind not to count
on anything.''
   His doctors said they were presenting other treatment options to
Chapman, whose leukemia is in remission.
   ``The next best step is unknown, but there are choices,'' said
Dr. Richard S. Fayssoux, the hematology and oncology specialist
treating Chapman.
   ``The chances for him to live longer would have been better
(with the transplant), but it's not like he's guaranteed a 50-year
life with the transplant,'' Fayssoux said.
   The patient's brother, Randy Chapman, 32, was located last month
on the streets of Miami. He earns his living as a test subject for
medical experiments and initially refused to submit to tests to
determine whether his marrow matched that of his ill brother.
   He eventually accepted an Indiana philanthropist's offer of
$1,000 to take the tests. The brother, who left home 14 years ago,
would have received an additional $2,000 had there been a match and
subsequent transplant.
   Chapman, the father of two children, continues to undergo
chemotherapy treatments. Doctors have told him that forms of
treatment other than the bone marrow transplant might be less risky
and painful, but also potentially less effective.
   ``He wouldn't have the immediate risk, but he also wouldn't have
the long-term possibilities,'' said Fayssoux.
   Chapman said doctors were checking into a partial bone marrow
match located through the national marrow registry.
   ``We'll come up with something else,'' Chapman said. ``It's
pretty difficult, but I wasn't counting on it either way.''
</TEXT>
