<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1651EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IdlingTrucks     03-21 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Idling Trucks,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Argonne Researchers Find Truck Idling Wastes Money, Damages
Engines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Letting a truck's diesel engine run at idle
causes twice as much damage as driving, and truckers who let their
rigs idle during rest stops are wasting money and diesel fuel, a
researcher said Monday.
   Some truckers have a misconception that idling is good for their
rigs, but researchers at Argonne National Laboratory found that
excess idling can shorten the life of a diesel truck engine by six
months to a year.
   ``There's a lot of misinformation out there (among truckers),''
said Larry R. Johnson, director of Argonne's Center for
Transportation Research. ``They realize it's using fuel, but some
of them perceive that it's good for the engine to keep it running.''
   In one of a series of studies for the U.S. Department of Energy
aimed at improving fuel efficiency in the trucking industry,
Johnson said Argonne researchers found that one hour of idling
causes as much engine wear as two hours of driving.
   Based on interviews with trucking company officials and drivers,
they calculated that a typical 18-wheeler idles about 800 hours a
year, the equivalent of 64,000 miles of driving, Johnson said
Monday in a telephone interview.
   He said that much idling would make the engine need an overhaul
up to a year sooner than under normal driving conditions.
   ``It wears out an engine twice as fast as being under load,''
Johnson said.
   Diesel engines usually require an overhaul every five years or
500,000 miles, he said.
   Many truckers leave their rigs running when they stop to rest as
a way of keeping the engine and diesel fuel warm in the winter, and
keeping the cab heated or cooled in summer, he said.
   But the Argonne researchers found that idling in the winter
cools the engine faster than if it were shut off because fans blow
cold air over the engine block and fuel lines, Johnson said.
   The lower idling temperature damages the engine by causing water
vapor to condense in the crankcase, said Raj Sekar, a mechanical
engineer at the Argonne transportation center.
   The water mixes with unburned sulfur oxides from diesel fuel
combustion and produces sulfuric acid, which corrodes the piston
rings and cylinder liners, he said.
   The Argonne researchers also calculated that the typical trucker
idles his engine at least three hours each workday, wasting an
estimated 800 gallons of fuel a year, Johnson said.
   As an alternative to idling, Johnson said, the Argonne study
recommended that truckers or trucking companies buy heaters for the
fuel system, engine block, cab and sleeping compartment. He said
the cost of buying each heater would pay for itself in one year
through fuel savings alone.
   Argonne, located 25 miles west of Chicago, is operated by the
University of Chicago for the Department of Energy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880321-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1658EST</FILEID>
