<HEAD>McPeak Tapped to Command Pacific Air Forces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has nominated Air Force Lt.
Gen. Merrill A. McPeak for promotion to general and assignment as
commander-in-chief of the Pacific Air Forces, the Pentagon said
Monday.
   Assuming he is confirmed by the Senate, McPeak, 52, would
receive his fourth star and the rank of full general and replace
Gen. Jack I. Gregory, 56, who will retire on Aug. 1 after 35 years
of active-duty service.
   Gregory, a native of Somerset, Ky., has commanded the Pacific
Air Forces since December 1986. McPeak, of Santa Rosa, Calif., now
commands the 12th Air Force.
   Maj. Gen. Peter T. Kempf, 51, was chosen by Reagan for promotion
to lieutenant general and command of the 12th Air Force.
   Kempf, a native of Elizabeth, N.J., now commands the Air Force
Tactical Fighter Weapons Center.
