<DATELINE>SANTA YNEZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagans won't be the only famous
family in the neighborhood after Michael Jackson moves his furry,
feathered and scaled friends to a 2,700-acre spread now in escrow
for $28 million.
   Jackson has also been rumored to be interested in a $5 million
hotel near the ranch, but the owner of the Grand Hotel, William
Healey, said Monday he has not talked with the singer or his agent.
   ``It's a rumour,'' real estate broker Healey said. ``There's
absolutely no truth to it.''
   The ranch in the scenic Santa Ynez Valley 100 miles northwest of
Los Angeles was on the market for $32 million and includes a main
house on a 32-acre section, a large clubhouse and 50,000 oak trees.
Jackson had originally offered $17 million, the Los Angeles Times
reported Sunday, quoting unidentified real estate sources.
   His menagerie includes monkeys, llamas, snakes, birds, and
barnyard animals, except for a cow.
   The animals had been kept on a one-acre Encino compound near the
home where he and his family have lived since the 1960s. It's
unknown whether Jackson will sell the home, which he enlarged in
1982.
   The 1,570-sqare-foot house in Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley
is now Jackson's recording studio. He built an 11,500-square-foot
house in front and a four-car garage with 850 square feet for
living quarters.
