<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua-Talks 5thLd-Writethru a0684 03-21 0760</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Talks, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0684,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua, Contras Suspending Military Operations During Peace
Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 11th graf pvs `Alfredo Calero...' with 1 graf to CORRECT
first name of Calero to Adolfo, sted Alfredo as sent. PICKS up 12th
graf pvs bgng, The peace talks...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAPOA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandinista government and Contra rebel
leaders today announced a suspension of military operations during
the first cease-fire talks ever held inside the country.
   Gen. Humberto Ortega, the nation's defense minister and brother
of President Daniel Ortega, made the announcement that government
troops were halting military operations and urged the Contras to
``act in kind.''
   He called the three days of peace talks that began today in this
small town on the border with Costa Rica ``an historic encounter.''
   Bosco Matamoros, spokesman for the Contra delegation, later
announced a suspension of offensive military operations in
Nicaragua as an ``expression of our good will.'' He also said the
conversations were ``frank and of mutual respect.''
   The talks began at 11:10 a.m. (12:10 p.m. EST), more than an
hour late. Both delegations started meeting behind closed doors in
the Custom House on the border just outside Sapoa, the only
building large enough here for the event.
   Humberto Ortega is heading the Nicaraguan delegation to the
peace talks. Alfredo Cesar is the leader of the Contra delegation.
   The Sandinista delegation includes Brian Wilson _ an American
pacifist whose legs were severed when he was hit by a train during
a protest last year _ and singer Kris Kristofferson. Wilson and
Kristofferson are longtime Sandinista supporters.
   Cheering Sandinista supporters lined both sides of the
90-mile-long road from Managua to Sapoa as Ortega drove by. Many
carried red-and-black Sandinista flags, and school children waved
Nicaraguan blue-and-white paper banners.
   Mariachi bands played music along the route. The crowds shouted:
``We insist on the surrender of the mercenaries,'' as the Contras
are called by the Sandinistas.
   The Contra delegation arrived a few minutes after the
Sandinistas in a bus escorted by a group of cars and jeeps. The
entire town was closely guarded by Sandinista troops and security
agents in plainclothes.
   Adolfo Calero, another Contra leader, said the Contras came
``here with an open agenda, and that it includes democratization,
includes amnesty. We insisted on speaking about all the problems
facing Nicaragua.''
   The peace talks were held despite an earlier Sandinista
offensive along the Honduran border.
   In a break with the past, both sides agreed that the talks would
have an open agenda.
   But on Sunday, Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco
reiterated a previous Sandinista position that the negotiations
strictly deal with the mechanics of a cease-fire.
   And the Contras indicated that they wanted to talk about other
matters, such as democratization and free elections.
   The Contras replaced Calero, the top-ranking leader of the
Nicaraguan Resistance, with Cesar as head of their delegation in
the hope that his familiarity with the Sandinistas might pressure
the Nicaraguan government into serious negotiations.
   Cesar was a former high-ranking Sandinista official before he
broke with the Sandinistas in 1982.
   Also scheduled to attend was Aristides Sanchez, a third member
of the directorate of the resistance, the Contra umbrella
organization.
   Entering today's sessions, Contra leaders indicated they were
not optimistic.
   ``The Sandinistas don't object to making tactical concessions,
but they will never enact reforms that risk their grip on power in
Nicaragua,'' said Contra adviser Gonzalo Facio.
   Cesar asserted the Contras had recently suffered military
setbacks, but that the Sandinista offensive had helped their cause
politically.
   Rebel fighters ``are going to be militarily weakened by the
suspension of United States aid and the growth in Soviet aid to the
Sandinistas,'' Cesar said.
   But he added that ``politically we are going to be stronger and
the Sandinistas weaker because the international community
condemned them for their bombardments last week of our positions.''
   Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, the mediator in previous talks
and an observer to today's discussions, also seemed pessimistic
about their outcome.
   ``I see the situation as quite complicated,'' he said during his
Sunday homily in Managua. ``It is very difficult to reconcile two
things that are completely opposite.''
   The cease-fire talks are called for under a Central American
peace plan signed by the region's five presidents last Aug. 7.
   The Sandinistas have already complied with some stipulations in
the peace accord by lifting a nearly 6-year-old state of emergency
and allowing more press freedom.
   The rebels have been fighting the government since 1981 in a
conflict that has killed more than 40,000 people.
</TEXT>
