<1ST_LINE>r w AM-People-Benedict     03-21 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Benedict,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AP Aerospace Writer Honored for Lifetime Achievements</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Howard Benedict, veteran aerospace writer for
The Associated Press, was awarded the 1987 Lauren D. Lyman Award
for distinguished achievement Monday by the Aviation-Space Writers
Association.
   Benedict, who has covered the nation's space program for nearly
three decades starting with the earliest space and missile shots,
expressed concern at the awards luncheon about the future of
America's space program.
   ``We need a space program that transcends political boundaries.
It cannot be a political football or a partisan event,'' he said.
``... Sadly I don't see that commitment on the horizon.''
   Benedict, who is the AP's correspondent at Cape Canaveral, Fla.,
was cited for his lifetime of distinguished achievement as the news
service's senior aerospace writer. His career included coverage of
man's first steps into space, his first walk on the moon and the
Challenger shuttle disaster.
   The Aviation-Space Writers Association established the Lyman
Award in 1972 in memory of Lauren ``Deac'' Lyman, a Pulitzer
Prize-winning aviation writer for The New York Times. The award is
sponsored by United Technologies Corp., for which Lyman also once
worked.
