<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WilliamsburgBridge     03-21 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Williamsburg Bridge,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Engineers Propose Replacements for 85-Year-Old Bridge</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising to what one called a ``once-in-a-lifetime
chance,'' engineers from around the world unveiled designs Monday
for a new Williamsburg Bridge from Brooklyn to Manhattan _ even
though the old bridge may not have to be replaced.
   The 85-year-old span over the East River is slowly
disintegrating, although officials have not decided whether to
rebuild or replace it.
   One of the 25 designs submitted calls for a bridge with two
48-story towers topped by V-shaped structures, one holding a
restaurant and one a museum.
   Another, designed by an international consortium that includes
the architect I.M. Pei, feature a roadway held by two metal
wishbones slightly twisted like a ribbon pulled taut and given a
half turn.
   But the designs may never span anything but the imagination.
   Since announcing the competition for a new bridge last year,
local officials have discovered that the bridge may not be as close
to collapse as was feared. Although a 1985 study showed that the
bridge would have to be replaced by 1995, later inspections have
indicated that it might last longer.
   Preliminary estimates indicate that the bridge could be
renovated for about $250 million. Estimates for a new bridge range
from $200 million to $600 million.
   Still, bridge engineers attending Monday's unveiling said they
could not resist the opportunity to design a major new bridge for
one of the world's largest cities.
   ``Such a location you'll never find again,'' said Swiss engineer
Bruno Thurlimann of Zurich, who collaborated on a Swiss-American
proposal with I.M. Pei & Partners and three other companies. ``It's
a once-in-a-lifetime chance.''
   Asking why an engineer submitted a design is ``like asking Sir
Edmund Hillary, `Why did you climb (Mount Everest)?''' said Nils D.
Olsson of DRC Consultants Inc.
   ``Structural engineers are always looking for fresh challenges,
and this is one of the most important projects since the
Verrazano,'' he said.
   Olsson, whose New York firm proposed the restaurant-topped
bridge, was referring to the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge, a link
completed in 1964 between Brooklyn and Staten Island. With 4,260
feet between supports, it is one of the world's longest suspension
bridge.
   Most of the designs for the Williamsburg call for a 1,600-foot
cable-stayed bridge that would be the longest of its type in the
world.
   A cable-stayed bridge has cables stretching from its towers to
the roadway, while a suspension bridge has a roadway hung from
cables stretching from one side to the other.
</TEXT>
