<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Milk-Mexico     03-21 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Milk-Mexico,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Selling 30,000 Tons Of Non-Fat Dry Milk To Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has sold Mexico 30,000
metric tons of surplus non-fat dry milk for $1,260 per ton, about a
third less than it cost American taxpayers, the Agriculture
Department said Monday.
   Acting Undersecretary Richard W. Goldberg said the surplus
powdered milk was sold by the department's Commodity Credit Corp.
to CONASUPO, the Mexican government's food purchasing authority.
   Goldberg said the sale ``reflects the world market price for
non-fat dry milk at the time the sale was negotiated'' with Mexico.
Deliveries are scheduled through March 1989. In addition, the CCC
provided Mexico with a three-year credit arrangement at commercial
rates of interest, he said.
   According to a recent CCC report, about 454 million pounds of
non-fat dry milk were held in storage, with a value of more than
$385 million, or about 85 cents per pound.
   There are approximately 2,205 pounds in a metric ton, which
translates to a U.S. value of $1,874 per ton.
   The surplus was acquired by CCC through purchases of cheese,
butter and non-fat dry milk to support the price of milk paid to
dairy farmers.
   Congress in 1985 farm law mandated the export sale of 150,000
tons of dairy products annually for the three fiscal years ending
Sept. 30, 1988. The latest deal with Mexico boosted sales this year
to 77,520 tons, Goldberg said.
</TEXT>
