<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SecuritySquabble Bjt   03-21 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Security Squabble, Bjt,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Who's Screened, Who's Not Creating Furor in Chicago's Federal
Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest squabble between prosecutors and
defense attornyes isn't about cases, tactics or money. It's about
being able to bypass new security procedures at the Dirksen Federal
Building, and it's headed for _ where else? _ the bench.
   Complaints from the public have been few, but the security
system brought the entire U.S. District Court system here to a
screeching halt one afternoon and prompted 39 attorneys _ including
several of Chicago's best-known defenders _ to petition the
district's 21 judges for the same exemptions granted to prosecutors
and building employees. A decision is expected Thursday.
   ``Things are bad enough when the lines stretch all the way
around the (elevator) bank,'' attorney Judith Halprin, who is
spear-heading the defenders' effort, said Monday.
   ``But when they decided to give exemptions to prosecutors,'' she
added, ``that was the last straw.''
   Replied U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas: ``We're being given
exemptions because we're employees of the building, no more, no
less. ... This seems to be a means by which certain people can keep
their names in the paper.''
   The U.S. Marshal's office said the procedures were in response
to a growing number of threats against the federal judiciary
nationwide and an increase in terrorism trials. They follow recent
trials of members of the El Rukn street gang and the Puerto Rican
independence group, FALN, on terrorism-related charges.
   Ms. Halprin's first act of defiance came March 8, the day the
airport-type screening began with federal marshals using metal
detectors for all people heading to courtroom floors and X-ray
machines for briefcases.
   Ms. Halprin, invoking her constitutional rights against
unreasonable search and seizure, refused to step through the metal
detector on her way to U.S. District Judge Brian Duff's courtroom.
   That was 10 a.m. Ms. Halprin waited in the lobby for more than
two hours while her client, charged with selling phony immigration
papers to an undercover agent, stood before Duff.
   The judge issued an order exempting Ms. Halprin, but she
remained there for another two hours because a marshal refused to
disobey Chief U.S. District Judge John Grady's original directive.
   Duff responded by ordering Chief U.S. Marshal John Adams to
appear before him and explain why he should not be held in contempt
of court.
   Duff himself was then called to an emergency meeting of the
district's judges and a new order resulted: Attorneys working
trials that began prior to March 8 could be exempted for the
duration of that trial.
   But that hasn't satisfied Ms. Halprin and her colleagues.
   ``They're exempting whole classes of people, Chicago policemen
for example,'' she said. ``Well one of us was representing a cop
subpoenaed by a grand jury.
   ``So, the target of the investigation gets to go through
untouched,'' she added, ``and the lawyer is the one subjected to a
search of his person and papers.
   ``Now is that silly or not?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
