<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1904EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DeafEducation     03-21 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaf Education,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Placing Deaf Students in Regular Schools Isn't Working, Panel Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Efforts to place deaf students in regular
public schools have backfired, leaving many deaf students with an
inadequate education, a government commission told a Senate panel
Monday.
   ``The state of the art in deafness education today at all levels
is unsatisfactory,'' Frank R. Bowe, who chaired the Commission on
Education of the Deaf, told the Senate Labor and Human Resources
subcommittee on the handicapped. ``We still have high school
graduates reading below a third-grade level.''
   The 13-member commission, established by Congress in 1986,
concluded that the Education Department should consider placing
deaf students in special schools or centers for the deaf, instead
of forcing them to compete with their hearing counterparts.
   ``Those of us who are deaf have had access to some form of
education, but it's not been a good one, and it's not getting
better,'' said Bowe, a regional commissioner of the Rehabilitation
Services Administration, who also is deaf.
   Two-thirds of the panel themselves are deaf. The commission,
made up of government officials and educators of the deaf, also
included actress Nanette Fabray MacDougall.
   The report also recommended that a majority of the board of
trustees of Gallaudet University be hearing impaired, which was a
demand made by students at the school for the deaf during protests
earlier this month.
   The commission concluded that significant improvements have been
made in techniques for educating the deaf since 1965, when a
federal panel last suggested changes.
   The report also determined, however, that ``the actual
implementation of these changes has been inadequate and sometimes
misguided, and that progress has been at best spotty and sporadic.''
   The commission found that 95 percent of America's deaf students
are ``prelingually deaf'' _ left without hearing at birth or
deprived of it in infancy _ and recommended improvements in
identifying these children and teaching them English.
   ``Early intervention programs are very important,'' said
Gertrude Galloway, a commission member. ``Right now, many children
come to school at 4 or 5 with no language.''
   The commission also called for expansion of post-secondary
education programs, including vocational and technical training,
junior college and college programs. Currently, there are two
colleges in the nation for deaf students, and four regional
post-secondary programs housed at hearing colleges.
   The commission also recommended that the Department of Education
include American Sign Language _ the native language to most of
those born deaf _ under the Bilingual Education Act, which would
treat ASL like any other foreign language. This would give deaf
students access to special training programs other foreign-language
students now receive.
   Establishment of a National Institute on Deafness as part of the
federal National Insititutes of Health is another priority of the
commission, along with the creation of a National Technical
Insititute for the Deaf at Gallaudet.
   The commission also instructed Congress to pass legislation
requiring the Federal Communications Commission to issue rules
making new televisions capable of decoding closed-caption
broadcasts. Until those sets are common, decoders should be
distributed free, the commission said.
   The commission took 20 months to interview deaf education
specialists, students and school administrators before coming up
with the 52 recommendations included in the 144-page report.
   A House panel will hold hearings on the commission's study next
week, and Senate and House committees then will work with the
Department of Education to establish some of the proposed changes.
   Members of the deaf community lauded the report.
   ``The commission is on target,'' said Philip Bravin, an IBM
executive named last week to chair Gallaudet's board of trustees.
``The education of the deaf in America needs to be improved. I'm
doing OK, but many of my friends and peers aren't.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880321-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1922EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DriftingBottle     03-21 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drifting Bottle,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bottle Released By High School Biology Class Turns Up In France</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE WORTH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bottle containing a note from a high
school class probably languished for two years in the Gulf Stream
before a hurricane swept it to the coast of France, a marine
biology teacher said.
   The bottle was found by Pierre Maupin the day after the storm
hit the Brittany village of Carnac in northwest France last
October, said John Gregory, a teacher at John I. Leonard High
School.
   ``It was ironic _ the guy who found it didn't show excitement,''
Gregory said Friday. ``He just filled out the information sheet,
sent it back, and that was it.''
   But students at the school, who received Maupin's reply in late
December, are enthusiastic about the bottle-releasing project,
which is aimed at helping them learn more about ocean currents.
   ``(When) he told us what we would be doing, at first it didn't
seem as exciting. But when we started getting the letters back, it
seemed interesting,'' said 16-year-old Anthony Izzarone.
   Since 1976, Gregory's classes have released about 900
silicone-sealed bottles 30 miles off Florida's Gold Coast into the
Gulf Stream. So far, 104 bottles have been found in locations
ranging from Cape Canaveral and Melbourne, just up the Florida
coast, to the Azores Islands in the mid-Atlantic.
   The high school's experiments have a return rate of 11 percent.
That's much better than the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, which gets back only about 2 percent of the bottles
it puts in the ocean to test currents, Gregory said.
</TEXT>
