<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrainDerails     03-21 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Derails,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train Hits Truck, 16 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW LENOX, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commuter train on Monday slammed into a
truck that crashed through the railroad crossing gates, injuring at
least 16 people, authorities said.
   The semi tractor-trailer, carrying medium-duty trucks, burst
into flames upon impact, and the driver was seriously injured,
authorities said.
   The force of the crash sent two passenger cars off the train
tracks and broke the engineer's leg, authorities said.
   The Metra commuter train, headed from Joliet to Chicago, was
carrying 16 passengers and five crew members, and likely was
traveling at about 50 mph when it hit the truck a mile west of New
Lenox, said Metra spokesman Chris Knapton.
   ``As the crossing signals became activated, the driver of the
tractor-trailer combination continued southbound and attempted to
beat the train,'' said Will County sheriff's Lt. Jim Srygler.
   ``The truck driver smashed through railroad crossing gates. The
gate came down on his hood,'' Knapton said.
   Sixteen people, including the engineer and the truck driver,
were taken to Silver Cross Hospital in Joliet, a spokeswoman said.
Most were treated and released.
   The truck driver, Terry Lewis, 34, of Drayton Plains, Mich., was
in serious condition, said the spokeswoman.
   Police would not immediately talk about any charges that could
be filed.
</TEXT>
