<HEAD>Bush Has Commanding Lead in New York Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush is the
overwhelming favorite going into New York's April 19 primary among
likely Republican voters questioned for a statewide poll released
Monday.
   The Marist County Institute for Public Opinion reported that of
the 292 likely Republican voters sampled, 68 percent favored Bush,
22 percent opted for Kansas Sen. Bob Dole nd 3 percent went for Pat
Robertson. Six percent said they were undecided and less than 1
percent picked another candidate. The margin of error was plus or
minus 6 percent.
   The institute also reported that in theoretical matchups between
Bush and the major Democratic candidates, the vice president came
out ahead of every Democrat except Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Libertarian Candidate Criticizes President Reagan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libertarian Party presidential candidte Ron Paul
said Monday that President Reagan has acted like a ``bully boy in
Central America'' by sending troops to Honduras.
   ``By sending troops to Honduras on his own say-so, the president
is flouting the Constitution,'' Paul said.
