</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ohio Primary Too Late, Professor Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The political damage Ohio and other
urban states may be doing to themselves by holding late-season
presidential primaries could go beyond having fewer candidate
choices, an elections researcher says.
   Linda L.M. Bennett, a political science professor at Wittenberg
University, says the problems of Ohio's cities and others in the
Northeast and Midwest may be ignored as candidates look past Ohio's
May 3 primary and toward the clincher _ California, which holds its
primary June 7.
   The problem begins with the emphasis placed on the February Iowa
caucuses, Ms. Bennett says.
   ``It emphasizes all the old classic themes of American
politics,'' such as the romanticized notion of farming, she said.
But urban problems are getting lost in the shuffle.
   ``It would be nice if they addressed the issues of the 90
percent of us who live in urban areas,'' Ms. Bennett said.
</TEXT>
