<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1941EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DeafRecommendations     03-21 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaf Recommendations,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Deaf Education</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the recommendations made
Monday by the Commission on Education of the Deaf in a
congressionally ordered report:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _The U.S. Department of Education should put less emphasis on
placing deaf students in the ``least restrictive environment'' and
more on providing an appropriate education. For many, that means
special schools and centers for the deaf.
   _The department should specify that removing a deaf child from a
regular classroom does not require ``compelling evidence.''
   _Congress should grant full recognition to American Sign
Language as a ``native'' language, just like Spanish, under the
Bilingual Education Act and programs.
   _More help and services for low-achieving deaf students, not
just the college bound.
   _Congress should require the Federal Communications Commission
to force broadcasters to caption their programming, and consider
the same requirement for film producers.
   _Congress ``should caption its own televised proceedings.''
   _Congress should require the FCC to issue rules making new TV
sets capable of decoding closed captions. Until such sets become
widely available, decoders should be distributed free to the deaf.
   _Earlier identification of deaf infants. It isn't necessary to
test the hearing of every newborn, just those at high risk of
hearing impairments.
   _The U.S. Department of Health and Human Services should issue
guidelines to help states improve screening procedures.
   _Parents should have the option to choose what type of school
their child attends, and must ``believe in whichever communication
method is chosen for their child's educational program.''
   _Congress should pass a ``Quality in Deaf Education'' bill.
   _Changes should be made in the management of Gallaudet
University, including appointment of a majority of deaf people to
its board of trustees.
   _Congress should bar hearing undergraduates from Gallaudet,
which in 1985 began to admit a handful interested in careers in
education of the deaf.
   _The Model Secondary School for the Deaf at Gallaudet should
admit more low-achieving deaf students so that it ``more closely
mirrors the national demographics of secondary school-age deaf
children.''
   _The government should expand its regional postsecondary
education program to the Southwest. It now has programs in other
regions.
   _Congress should establish a National Center on Deafness
Research at Gallaudet.
   _Congress should create a National Institute on Deafness and
Other Communication Disorders at the National Institutes of Health.
   _Gallaudet and the National Technical Institute for the Deaf in
Rochester, N.Y., should limit enrollment of foreign students to 10
percent, and charge them 75 percent of the actual costs, or about
$18,250 a year.
   _Both Gallaudet and NTID should do a better job of hiring the
deaf. Only 12 percent of the staff at NTID and 25 percent at
Gallaudet are deaf.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
