<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1945EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmStockholders     03-21 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Stockholders,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stockholders in Failed Credit Associations Receive Cash or Par
Value</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eligible stockholders in six financially
troubled production credit associations in the Omaha, Neb., and
Spokane, Wash., districts will receive par value cash or credit for
their stock, the Farm Credit System Assistance Board said Monday.
   Eric P. Thor, head of the board, said the compensation will go
to those whose stock was either frozen or not retired at par when
the associations went into liquidation.
   Acting under the new Agricultural Credit Act of 1987, the board
``initiated a series of agreements resulting in the issuance of
preferred stock on behalf of the associations in liquidation'' to a
related entity, the Farm Credit System Financial Assistance Corp.
   The corporation will provide more than $20.5 million to retire
the frozen stock, Thor said. As a result, association borrowers
whose stock was frozen or retired at less than par value will be
able to collect par value for their stock.
   Stockholders should receive checks or notification of credit
within a few weeks, he said.
   The associations in liquidation in the Omaha district are the
O'Neill and Valentine production credit associations. In the
Spokane district, the PCAs are Glendive, Milk River, Western
Montana and Western Washington.
   The associations, which are cooperatively owned by the
borrowers, extend loans to farmers to meet production expenses.
</TEXT>
