<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RacialAssault     03-21 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Racial Assault,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abrams: We'll Protect Grand Jury Process</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 9th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Attorney General Robert Abrams said
Monday he will prevent representatives of Tawana Brawley from
disrupting the grand jury hearing evidence into the black
teen-ager's allegations that she was sexually attacked by six white
men.
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, a New York City minister advising the
16-year-old girl, has threatened to stop anyone from testifying
Tuesday at the grand jury hearing. Sharpton said he'd risk arrest
to stop the proceedings.
   ``I don't think there is a need or necessity to move the grand
jury, but we would take any and all steps that are necessary to
protect the integrity of the grand jury process,'' Abrams said at a
news conference.
   Representatives of Miss Brawley have refused to cooperate with
state prosecutors investigating the alleged racial and sexual
attack. They have criticized suggestions that witnesses might be
granted immunity in exchange for their testimony.
   The teen-ager's lawyers want a special prosecutor named to
investigate race-related crimes, for Abrams to be removed from the
case and for a new grand jury to be convened outside of Dutchess
County.
   Abrams also said he was appalled at the telecast of photos of
Miss Brawley shortly after her alleged November attack by a group
of white men and is investigating how a television station got the
pictures.
   He said no one in his office authorized the release of the
photos, which were shown Thursday night on WNBC in New York City
and nationally on the NBC's network news.
   ``I was indeed quite upset,'' Abrams said, adding ``it's a
serious invasion of the privacy of the victim.''
   One of the photos shows the word ``nigger'' scrawled on Miss
Brawley's stomach and another shows her lying in her hospital bed
with monitoring devices attached to her upper torso.
   Mary Lou O'Callaghan, director of news information for NBC, said
the network would not reveal the source of the photos. ``We covered
what has become a significant news story,'' she said in defense of
the telecast.
   Abrams said he was confident that no one in the attorney
general's task force released the photos. Other law enforcement
agencies that investigated the case might have given the photos
away, he said.
</TEXT>
