<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Panama-Security     03-21 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Security,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Increases Security Force in Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon has quietly increased the number
of security personnel in Panama, dispatching more than 300 soldiers
to the strife-torn country in the past three days, officials said
Monday.
   Two-thirds of those dispatched during the latest troop movement
were members of the 503rd Military Police Battalion, which is
headquartered at Fort Bragg, N.C., the Pentagon said.
   The remainder were dispatched from Fort Eustis, Va., and Fort
Hood, Texas.
   Capt. Nancy LaLuntas, a Pentagon spokeswoman, said in response
to a query that ``212 members of the 503rd Military Police
Battalion have deployed to Panama to augment U.S. security forces
in that country.''
   ``This deployment of military police is not in response to any
incident, but simply good planning in view of the current unrest in
Panama,'' she continued.
   The deployment began last Friday ``and is a prudent measure,
consistent with the Panama Canal Treaty, to further safeguard the
canal and U.S. lives, property and interests in the area,'' she
said.
   In addition to the MPs, about 100 soldiers from Forts Eustis and
Hood were dispatched ``to assist in the movement of these
additional security force personnel and to augment U.S. Southern
Command security forces,'' she added.
   Those soldiers are ``Army airfield movements control
personnel,'' the spokeswoman said.
   The latest dispatch of troops comes less than a week after the
Pentagon ordered slightly more than 100 Marine and Air Force
security personnel to Panama to bolster security around the Panama
Canal and nearby military bases.
   All told, about 420 security personnel have now been sent to
Panama to join the roughly 600 servicemen who already were assigned
to security duties with the U.S. Southern Command, which is
headquartered there.
   The Southern Command, which oversees all U.S. military
operations in the region, has about 10,000 servicemen assigned to
it.
   The Pentagon's security concerns stem from the administration's
efforts to unseat Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Although no moves have been reported against American servicemen
or their dependents, defense officials are said to be concerned
that Noriega might lash back at the United States by attacking or
sabotaging facilities there.
</TEXT>
