<1ST_LINE>r p AM-DenverRecall     03-21 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Denver Recall,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Confident They Will Force Recall of Denver's Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of a drive to oust Mayor Federico Pena say
they expect to collect 50,000 signatures, 10,000 more than
necessary to force a new election, by the April 13 deadline.
   ``I think we're going to be in real good shape,'' said Marge
Doty, whose Metropolitan Action Committee is heading the recall
effort. She said the names would be counted Wednesday.
   ``Just because Marge says it, doesn't mean it's true,'' said
former Denver Election Commissioner Susan Duncan, leader of a group
fighting the recall.
   Recall organizers must prove at least 39,091 signatures are of
registered voters in order to force a new election. The ballot
would include Pena and all candidates who collected 300 valid
nominating signatures.
   The recall drive against Pena, now in his second term, is rooted
in the public works department, where employees began gathering
after last summer's mayoral election to air their grievances.
   By fall, the workers, who complained Pena is a poor manager, had
hired Doty, retired director of admissions at Denver General
Hospital.
   ``Basically, we're guiding ourselves by intuition,'' Doty said
in an interview last week. ``The political expertise is coming from
the seat of my pants.''
   The petition drive was launched Jan. 15 amid criticism of Pena's
snow-removal efforts after a Christmas weekend snowstorm left
unplowed, impassable streets. The effort was fueled by television
reports last month that street crews, who were followed and
secretly filmed, were loafing on duty.
   But even if enough valid signatures are collected, it could be
months before an election is held.
   After April 13, Pena will have 10 days to challenge signatures,
and the election commission will have 50 days to conduct hearings
on the mayor's appeal.
   If there are enough valid signatures, the City Council will have
to schedule an election within 60 to 90 days.
   Pena would be reimbursed by the city for any legal challenge to
the petitions. If he won the recall election, the state would
reimburse him for campaign expenses.
</TEXT>
