<HEAD>Sentimental Return to `St. Elsewhere' Produces Anger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Ed Flanders, making a sentimental
return for the last episode of NBC's ``St. Elsewhere,'' surprised
fellow actors and angered producers by delivering an unscripted
soliloquy on death, it was reported Monday.
   Flanders, who earlier this season left his role as Dr. Donald
Westphall, was back for a farewell to the series, which is leaving
the air at the end of the season.
   The script taped Friday called for Flanders, as Westphall, to
make a touching statement about beginnings and endings at St.
Eligius Hospital, otherwise known as ``St. Elsewhere.'' Instead,
USA Today reported, he talked about death as his fellow actors
looked on bewildered.
   ``He spoiled the moment for everybody,'' producer Tom Fontana
told the newspaper.
   Executive producer Bruce Paltrow called Flanders' speech ``a
tragedy.''
   Fontana and Paltrow declined to talk about the incident Monday,
but Larry Bloustein, a spokesman for MTM Enterprises, which
produces the show, said they confirmed the accuracy of the report.
   There was no immediate word on what the producers would do,
although there was talk of refilming it with Dr. Mark Craig, played
by William Daniels, reading the lines.
