<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSFamily     03-21 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Family,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family With AIDS Says They're Being Ostracized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS has meant isolation and poverty
for a family of four, two with AIDS and two exposed to the fatal
disease, said the father.
   The parents, who agreed to be interviewed by The Tampa Tribune
if their identities were protected, lost their jobs and were forced
to seek government assistance. Their two cars were repossessed and
furniture sold to pay debts and buy food, said the couple, who are
in their 30s.
   The woman said she confided in a friend at work, who told the
boss. She and her husband, who worked in the entertainment field,
were fired, she said.
   ``We were rejected by almost everyone we knew, everyone we
worked with,'' he said.
   The couple said they filed a discrimination complaint with the
Florida Commission on Human Relations but dropped the case after an
investigator told them that fighting their ex-employer would expose
the family to a traumatic public argument, possibily involving
their children.
   The father said he was infected with the AIDS virus through a
sexual encounter with another man years ago, The Tribune reported
Monday.
   Unknowingly carrying the virus, he married in 1980 and two years
later fathered a son. He was healthy, he said, except for a nagging
cough and a shortness of breath one doctor attributed to asthma.
   Then, early last year, while his wife was pregnant with their
second child, he learned he had acquired immune deficiency
syndrome, the newspaper reported.
   Worse, he learned his 6-year-old son has AIDS. His wife is being
treated for AIDS-related complex, a less-severe condition
associated with the AIDS virus.
   And their 7-month-old son has tested positive for AIDS
antibodies, but doctors don't know if he will develop the disease.
   A couple of months ago, the father said, ``I was ready to die.''
But his outlook changed, he said, mainly because of an AIDS support
group and the realization that his family needed him.
   ``Before you die of AIDS,'' he said, ``you have to live with
it.''
   Today, the family primarily lives on Social Security disability
payments. Medical costs average more than $1,100 a month, and they
must pay $251 before Medicaid's catastrophic health-care plan picks
up the rest.
   ``When you look at it from the financial point of view, it looks
pretty bleak,'' he said. ``So we don't look at it that way.''
</TEXT>
