<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Gunman-Deaths     03-21 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gunman-Deaths,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Took Wife And Two Sons Hostage Dies After Killing One Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who held his ex-wife and two sons
hostage in a deadly burst of violence at his trailer home had been
jailed recently for a similar, less violent episode, authorities
said Monday.
   Police said Jerry Staggs, 40, shot one man to death outside the
trailer Sunday morning and, after holding his children and ex-wife
hostage for eight hours, shot himself in the head Sunday night.
Staggs died Monday morning.
   Sheriff Joe Patterson said Staggs, who worked for the city's
maintenance department, had been taken into custody earlier this
month and accused of abducting Sherry Staggs, 27, who had been
married to him for 11 years.
   The sheriff said officers ``tried to get the mental health
center to talk with him when we had him in jail for kidnapping his
ex-wife ... but they wouldn't talk to him.''
   Gary Porier, County Mental Health Center director, said he had
``no direct knowledge'' of the sheriff's request. ``We always go to
any law enforcement emergency call if they ask us,'' he said.
   There were no reports of any injuries in the earlier incident.
   But on Sunday morning Staggs killed Don Pressnell, 41, as he
drove up with Mrs. Staggs and her brother, Eddie Hamilton, 28.
   Hamilton said the Staggs' marriage legally ended March 16 with
Mrs. Staggs getting custody of their 9-year-old son, Michael.
Hamilton said she was going to take the boy on an outing when
Staggs became irritated at seeing Pressnell and pulled a gun.
   ``He shot him (Pressnell) once in the head and then started
shooting at me,'' said Hamilton. ``He emptied that gun but he
missed me. I threw a cup of coffee on him and he pulled another gun
out of his pocket and pointed it at Sherry's head and made her and
Michael go back inside.''
   Scotty Staggs, his 15-year-old son from an earlier marriage,
also was at the home and held hostage.
   About 25 law enforcement officers surrounded the trailer and
evacuated residents of other mobile homes in the trailer park.
Staggs used his 15-year-old son to communicate with police. The boy
told officers ``we'll all be dead'' if authorities tried to enter
the trailer. ``My daddy's word is worth gold.''
   About 6 p.m., the 9-year-old was released and about a half-hour
later, the 15-year-old was freed. Then a shot rang out and Mrs.
Staggs fled the trailer. She said Staggs had shot himself in the
head.
   Police found the critically wounded man inside and had him flown
by helicopter to the hospital, where he died shortly before 5 a.m.
Monday.
</TEXT>
