<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dole 1stLd-Writethru a0697 03-21 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Promises Spending Freeze If Elected President</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with comments on death penalty for drug dealers in
new grafs 2-3</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMERY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential contender Bob Dole,
trailing George Bush in Wisconsin as well as nationally, challenged
Bush anew to a debate on Monday and won applause from a farm crowd
for his proposal to freeze most federal spending.
   Later, in Eau Claire, Dole called for stiffer penalties for drug
dealers, including capital punishment.
   ``If that person is tried and convicted and found guilty, I
can't think of any penalty that's severe enough _ including the
death penalty,'' Dole said. ``We've got to set an example. We've
got to stop it. We're not going to do it by just a slap on the
wrist.''
   Vern Peterson, acting mayor of Amery, a farm community in
northwestwern Wisconsin, said during Dole's appearance that he
would send a debate invitation to Bush this week ``and of course
you, Mr. Dole, are invited.''
   ``I'll be here. In fact, maybe I'll just stay here,'' said Dole,
who has unsuccessfully pressed Bush for a one-on-one debate for
weeks.
   Bush is far ahead of Dole in the race for the Republican
nomination. And a poll published Sunday in The Milwaukee Journal
showed the vice president leading Dole by nearly 3-to-1 among
Wisconsin voters likely to vote in Wisconsin's April 5 primary.
   Dole's remarks about his proposed spending freeze drew cheers
from more than 900 farmers who packed a small barn to hear him
speak during Farm City Days.
   Dole said his deficit-reduction plan would allow ``no
exceptions, except some things for low-income Americans.''
   ``That one-year freeze will save $150 billion over three years,
no taxes, no gimmicks, no phony accounting, just $150 billion in
real savings,'' Dole said.
   He said the freeze would give him time to negotiate a budget
deficit reduction plan that would provide a lasting solution to the
problem of rising federal red ink.
   On another topic, in an interview after he toured the festival
grounds, Dole said he thought a newly proposed aid plan for
Nicaragua's Contra rebels could pass the Senate if brought to a
vote, ``but the big question is whether it can be brought to a vote
in the Senate.''
   Dole said that although Wisconsin Gov. Tommy G. Thompson has
endorsed Bush, the Republican governor is a good example of a
lawmaker who makes a good executive.
   ``My opponent says Bob Dole is a good opponent but he doesn't
have any executive experience. Governor Thompson had 20 years of
experience in the Legislature and now he's governor and he's doing
a good job of saving you money because he can go back and deal with
the legislators he knows,'' Dole said. ``I can do the same.''
</TEXT>
