<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1802EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PLOMission     03-21 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO Mission,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Preparing Legal Action To Close PLO Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestine Liberation Organization on
Monday defied a U.S. order to shut down its U.N. observer mission
and Washington prepared to take legal action to close it.
   The General Assembly, meeting in its second emergency session on
the dispute, was expected to urge Washington to desist from its
efforts to close the mission.
   Diplomats said the assembly also would request U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar to take legal action if
necessary to protect the PLO mission and provide alternative
accommodations to its members on U.N. international territory.
   The 1987 Anti-Terrorist Act passed by Congress went into effect
Monday. It requires the government to close the PLO mission, whose
offices are in a townhouse in New York City.
   Zehdi Labib Terzi, the PLO's permanent representative to the
U.N., said he would not voluntarily close the 13-year-old mission
near Park Avenue as ordered by Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   ``Once we see what the U.S. government does, then we will
respond,'' Terzi said.
   In Washington, Justice Department spokesman Mark Sheehan said in
a telephone interview that the government probably would file suit
Tuesday in U.S. District Court in New York City seeking a court
order to close the mission.
   ``We will lay out our belief that continued operation of the PLO
U.N. observer mission is in violation of the law passed by Congress
and ask the court to agree and issue an order directing him (Terzi)
to close down,'' Sheehan said.
   He said he did not expect an immediate ruling by the court, and
the PLO probably would have at least 20 days to file a response to
the civil suit.
   In a message to Terzi on March 11, Meese said if the mission was
not closed voluntarily by March 21, the PLO would be in violation
of the law and a suit would be filed.
   A source at the United States' U.N. mission, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said if a court rules against the PLO, the
government might try to render the PLO mission ineffective by
turning off electricity and water.
   PLO officials have said repeatedly the dispute is between the
United States and the United Nations, not between Washington and
the PLO.
   The United Nations and the PLO say the 1987 Anti-Terrorist Act
violates the 1947 U.N. Headquarters Treaty, by which the United
States agreed to allow all U.N. missions to operate.
   The PLO was granted observer status by the 159-member world
body, which considers the organization the only legitimate
representative of the Palestinian people. The PLO participates in
U.N. debates on the Middle East but does not have the right to vote.
   Former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark, the PLO's legal
counsel, has said that if the United States sues to close the PLO
mission, he would seek to have the complaint dismissed on grounds
the United States lacks jurisdiction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
