<DOCNO> AP880321-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1840EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PuertoRico-Primary     03-21 0758</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puerto Rico-Primary,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Victory Surprises Democrats; Bush Prevailed Despite GOP
Confusion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Party officials and even Jesse
Jackson's campaign staff were at a loss Monday to explain why he
beat Michael Dukakis, Albert Gore, Jr. and other rivals in a
primary-day Democratic straw poll.
   Among the Republicans, Vice President George Bush prevailed in
his party's primary Sunday in an atmosphere of confusion in which
most polling stations did not have ballots and few Republicans
voted. Bush garnered all 14 national convention delegates.
   ``You all stood in there and got the job done,'' Bush told
supporters in a telephone call Monday from Air Force Two as he
traveled between campaign stops in the Northeast.
   ``I have no idea'' why Jackson won, said Miguel Hernandez
Agosto, a leader of the Popular Democratic Party slate of delegates
who will travel to the July presidential nominating convention in
Atlanta.
   Jackson never visited this island 1,000 miles southeast of
Florida, and never allowed himself to be pinned down on its main
political interest _ should Puerto Rico remain a U.S. commonwealth
or become the 51st state.
   Asked why he thought Jackson won, press aide Tom Schade said in
a telephone interview from Jackson's headquarters in Chicago, ``I
don't have an answer for that.''
   Jackson's victory may or may not help him at the Democratic
National Convention. Puerto Rico's 56-member delegation is going
uncommitted, as Hernandez Agosto and Gov. Raphael Henandez Colon
stressed after Sunday's balloting.
   The straw poll was ``merely an expression of affection and good
wishes for the candidates,'' Hernandez Agosto said Monday. ``It
does not commit the delegates in any way. Each member of the
delegation is aware of that.''
   Gov. Hernandez Colon said, ``At this time, we have not made a
decision on which U.S. presidential candidate we are going to
support.''
   The latest unofficial results showed that with 1,494 of 1,650
precincts reporting, or 91 percent, Jackson had 87,757 votes, or 32
percent, to 70,733 votes, or 26 percent, for Dukakis, and 57,639
votes, or 21 percent, for Illinois Sen. Paul Simon.
   Simon made one campaign trip here, as did Dukakis. The
Massachusetts governor also sent a videotaped speech to PDP
delegates, in Spanish, noting he honeymooned in Puerto Rico.
   Among other Democrats, Tennessee Sen. Gore finished fourth with
45,361 votes, or 17 percent, Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt, fifth
with 9,159 votes, or 3 percent, and Lyndon LaRouche last with 3,753
votes, or 1 percent.
   Bush swamped Kansas Sen. Bob Dole, 1,935 votes to 48, or 98
percent to 2 percent, according to the latest unofficial results
with 582 of 1,650 stations reporting, apparently just 35 percent.
   Dole backers tried up to the last to call off the primary and
allocate the 14 GOP delegates by caucus.
   On Sunday, GOP ballots and election material sat unused in
trucks because no one came to distribute them to precinct stations.
Local party chairman Luis Ferre, expecting a very low turnout,
approved a plan Sunday morning whereby 1,650 polling stations were
consolidated to 104.
   The State Election Commission, which conducted the election, was
not consulted about the maneuver and on Monday was unsure how to
tally Republican votes. The consolidation might mean that Bush's
1,935 votes represent much more than 35 percent of all GOP votes
cast.
   ``Dole had no following here,'' Ferre said. ``His supporters
tried to stop the primary'' because they knew that otherwise, Dole
had no chance of defeating Bush.
   On the Democratic side, 33 delegates were selected. Those 33
will choose 18 more. The remaining five seats in the delegation
automatically go to party officials such as Gov. Hernandez Colon.
   The main issue was not Simon's advocacy of statehood for this
Caribbean island of 3.5 million, or Gore's defense of tax breaks
that generate jobs here, or Dukakis' position that federal minimum
wage laws be applied here. The main issue was control of the local
Democratic Party.
   The party currently is split exactly in half _ the Popular
Democratic Party of Gov. Hernandez Colon and the rival New
Progressive Party of ex-Gov. Carlos Romero Barcelo each has its own
chairman, vice chairman and national committeeman and
committeewoman.
   The entire 33-member PDP delegate slate won Sunday, 373,950 to
297,408, giving Hernandez Colon an island-wide base to press for
federal patronage, legislation and the political status quo whereby
Puerto Ricans are U.S. citizens with almost every right and
obligation except they cannot vote for president and pay no federal
taxes.
   The NPP favors statehood for Puerto Rico.
</TEXT>
