<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0767 03-21 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0767,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Pledges End To Apartheid If Elected; Urges End To Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS 4 grafs with Jackson, Hart comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOE WHEELAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Jesse Jackson
pledged Monday to bring an end to apartheid in South Africa if
elected.
   Jackson, speaking at a Denver high school, was asked whether he
supported a protest by University of Colorado students against the
university's investment with a company that has South Africa
holdings.
   ``I support the ambition of those students,'' said Jackson. ``A
university must maintain a moral integrity and should not invest''
in South Africa.
   Broadening his statements to include U.S. policy toward South
Africa, Jackson said, ``It doesn't make much sense to mine harbors
in Nicaragua and send troops to Honduras in the name of open and
free elections and then say nothing when South Africa locks up
labor leaders and kills innocent men, women and children.''
   ``The integrity of our nation is at stake,'' he said.
   Jackson said pressure and sanctions by the United States and its
allies could end apartheid.
   ``The sure way to end apartheid in South Africa is to elect
Jesse Jackson president,'' he said.
   Jackson, who has made anti-drug comments a part of most campaign
appearances, exhorted the students at George Washington High School
to stay away from drugs.
   He also urged the students to participate in Colorado's precinct
caucuses April 4, noting that they coincide with the 20th
anniversary of Martin Luther King Jr.'s assassination.
   ``Since Gary Hart is not in the race, let me be Colorado's
favorite son,'' said Jackson, who later met briefly with Hart at
Stapleton International Airport. Hart withdrew from the
presidential race for the second time March 11.
   ``I have appealed to him (Hart) for help in our campaign to give
assistance in the direction of policy development, and he will help
do so,'' Jackson told reporters after meeting with Hart.
   Hart said this did not mean he was endorsing Jackson. ``Direct
endorsements are old-fashioned,'' he said. ``I can't deliver any
votes to Jesse.''
   But he said he was willing to work with Jackson _ or any
Democratic candidate _ on policy matters.
   ``I think the best assistance I can give him or any other
candidate for president is in the area of policies,'' said Hart.
``I want to work very closely with Jesse and his people to help him
develop a policy to govern this country.''
</TEXT>
