<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 2036EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PhoneSuit     03-21 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phone Suit,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney General, Consumer Advocate Allege Sales Deceptions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BLOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deceptive marketing by Bell of
Pennsylvania results in many customers paying for optional
telephone services they don't want or need, state officials charged
Monday.
   In a joint announcement, Attorney General LeRoy Zimmerman and
Consumer Advocate David Barasch said Bell has been engaged in a
longstanding sales practice that misleads customers about service
options. In some cases, they said, lower-income residents were
saddled with costly extras.
   The attorney general and consumer advocate filed separate but
related legal actions to restrain Bell from using the allegedly
illegal marketing practices, to make refunds to customers and to
pay civil penalties.
   ``In many cases, Bell representatives assign services such as
call waiting and wire maintenance plans without ever telling the
consumer that the services are optional,'' Zimmerman said during a
news conference.
   Bell, the state's largest telephone company, said the
allegations were unjustified and ``an affront'' to its employees.
   Regis F. Filtz, Bell vice president and chief operating officer,
said company representatives often spend a half-hour or an hour
with customers to ensure they make informed choices.
   ``Certainly we sell. But we have no interest in overselling, or
selling services by misleading customers as to the cost, value or
benefits of our services,'' Filtz said.
   Bell serves about 3.7 million customers, representing about 80
percent of the state's telephone lines.
   Barasch said consumers have spent about $176 million on Bell's
optional services since 1984. But he was unable to determine how
many customers may have been mislead about the charges. Optional
services include Touch-Tone service, call forwarding, call waiting,
three-way calling and speed calling.
   The allegations were based on 32 test calls made to Bell
representatives by agents posing as customers.
   In one test call, an agent identifying herself as a single
mother living on welfare was assigned a package of services costing
$28.55 monthly, when basic phone service could be obtained for
$6.65 per month, officials said.
   Of the callers, more than 70 percent were assigned up to three
optional services they had not requested or were not told were
optional, officials said. Three-quarters of the callers were
assigned Touch-Tone service without requesting it or without being
told it was optional, they said.
   In a complaint filed with the Public Utility Commission, Barasch
labeled the sales practices ``unlawful, unfair and deceptive.''
Besides the penalties and refunds, Barasch also asks the commission
to force the company to set up new procedures for initiating and
re-establishing service.
   Zimmerman, in a suit filed in Commonwealth Court, asks that the
company be assessed civil penalties for violating
consumer-protection laws.
   Barasch estimated the company would have to pay ``many millions
of dollars'' in refunds and fines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
