<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Israel,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Clash With Israeli-Backed Militiamen In South Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas in south Lebanon made one of
their biggest assaults of the year before dawn Monday, attacking
six positions manned by Israeli-backed militiamen, a U.N. spokesman
said.
   There was no immediate report on casualties and it was not clear
which faction was involved. It was the second battle between
anti-Israel guerrillas and the South Lebanon Army reported in three
days.
   Security sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
attackers fired machine guns and rocket-propelled grenades into
militia positions in the central sector of Israel's self-proclaimed
``security zone'' just north of the border.
   The mainly Christian militia, which is financed by Israel and
acts as its surrogate, retaliated with mortars and tank cannon.
   Timur Goksel, the U.N. spokesman, said several positions manned
by Irish troops of the U.N. peacekeeping force were caught in the
crossfire but reported no casualties.
   ``There was very heavy shooting in the area,'' he said. ``Seven
Irish battalion posts were caught in the crossfire.''
   Sources said Israeli soldiers rushed to the militia's aid in
Qantara, Shoumariyeh, Rashaf, Haddata, Beit Yahoun and Braachit, a
string of villages 13 miles southeast of Tyre, and opened up on the
raiders with tank cannons.
   The fighting lasted for two hours and the attackers withdrew,
the sources said, speaking privately.
   Militiamen and Israeli gunners later shelled the Shiite Moslem
market town of Nabatiyek. Two Lebanese women were reported wounded.
   Monday's hostilities came two days after Israeli troops and
South Lebanon Army militiamen, led by tanks, raided guerrilla bases
four miles northeast of the security zone.
   Israeli fighter-bombers raided a Palestinian guerrilla camp in
the Chouf Mountains southeast of Beirut last Thursday, killing one
guerrilla.
</TEXT>
