<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ArcticTrek     03-21 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arctic Trek,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientific Team in Third Week of Journey to Find Second Pole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian-Soviet research team has completed
nearly a fifth of its 1,100-mile trek across the Arctic with only
the anticipated problems like frostbite and blisters, its
spokeswoman said Monday.
   The 13 Soviet and Canadian team members skied 13 miles Monday,
Shirley Smyth said by telephone from Ottawa. She said the team
covered 16 miles Sunday, its greatest single-day distance, in minus
33 cold.
   Using an angle-measuring device called a theodolite, which
resembles a surveyor's transit, scientists are trying to find a
second magnetic pole on their journey over untrodden territory.
   She said a Canadian and Soviet doctor on the 3-week-old
expedition are treating team members for frostbite and blisters.
   Team members took a two-day break last week to begin scientific
tests and repair broken equipment. They also varied their steady
diet of dried-meat known as pemmican with fruit, eggs and steak.
   ``They could have a bit of a picnic,'' said Smyth. ``It was a
break from pemmican.''
   She said relations between Canadians and Soviets were warm and
spirits high.
   The expedition left the Severnaya Zemlya Archipelago, the
northernmost point in the Soviet Union, to ski and walk to the
North Pole. The three-month journey will end in Canada at Cape
Columbia on Ellesmere Island.
</TEXT>
