<HEAD>Comedian Bob Hope Has Surgery For Benign Prostate Condition,
Publicist Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Bob Hope underwent surgery Monday
for what was described as a ``benign condition'' of his prostate
gland, his publicist said.
   The 84-year-old comedian ``does not have cancer,'' said
spokesman Jim Mahoney after the surgery.
   Hope was operated on at the USC Kenneth Norris Jr. Cancer
Hospital, but Mahoney explained that Hope was at the facility
because he had been referred to Dr. Donald G. Skinner, chief of
urology at USC who performs his operations at the cancer hospital.
   Skinner said Hope was in ``excellent'' condition after the
operation.
   Mahoney said the comedian is expected to be hospitalized for
three or four days. The operation was scheduled in advance, not
emergency surgery, he said.
   Last week, the comedian was one of the presenters at the Writers
Guild of America awards at the Beverly Hilton Hotel. He chatted
with reporters and photographers there, but didn't mention the
surgery.
   Mahoney said the operation, common for older men, was similar to
a procedure performed on President Reagan in January 1987. The
surgeon removed fibrous tissue filling the prostate, using small
instruments and working through a catheter.
