<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Honduras-USTroops     03-21 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-US Troops,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joint US-Honduras Maneuvers To Start Tuesday</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Central America, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 3,200 U.S. troops rushed here
after an alleged incursion by Nicaraguan troops will begin a set of
joint maneuvers with the Honduran army Tuesday, a U.S. military
spokesman said.
   Maj. Gary Hovatter, spokesman for the American forces in
Honduras, made the announcement Monday but refused to disclose
details.
   The announcement came as Nicaragua's Sandinista government and
Contra rebels agreed to halt all offensive military operations
during three days of talks that began Monday. The negotiations are
to achieve a permanent cease-fire.
   U.S. troops arrived in Honduras last week at the request of
President Jose Azcona Hoyo and are stationed at five bases
throughout Honduras. The soldiers are from the 82nd Airborne
Division based in Fort Bragg, N.C. and the 7th Light Infantry
Division from Fort Ord, Calif.
   In an exercise Monday, a U.S. helicopter crashed near a base in
the southern town of Juticalpa with 10 people aboard. Hovatter said
there were injuries but would not give further information until
relatives are notified. Pentagon spokesmen in Washington said there
were no fatalities and that the injuries did not appear serious.
   Some of the U.S. soldiers are based at Jamastran, about 20 miles
from the Nicaraguan border, but 80 miles from the site of the
alleged Nicaraguan incursion at the Bocay region in the Honduran
province of Olancho. The Bocay area straddles the
Nicaraguan-Honduran border.
   Others are at Tamara and at San Lorenzo in southern Honduras,
and a corps of about 200 soldiers remained at American military
headquarters at the Honduran air force base of Palmerola, about 45
miles northwest of Tegucigalpa.
   President Reagan dispatched the troops both as a show of support
for Honduras and as a warning to Nicaragua against further action
in the area.
   President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua repeatedly has denied his
country's troops were inside Honduras. The Contras maintain supply
and staging camps in Bocay region.
   Honduran presidential spokesman Lisandro Quesada said Monday the
estimated 2,000 Sandinista troops who entered this country last
week in pursuit of Contra rebels have dwindled.
   Col. Manuel Suarez Benavides, the Honduran armed forces public
relations director, said it will be ``days only'' before the U.S.
troops return home.
   Neither Suarez nor Quesada would say the threat from the
Sandinistas has ended.
   ``When the last Sandinista crosses the Segovia River into
Nicaragua then this subject will be forgotten,'' Quesada said.
</TEXT>
