<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-21 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Lows in Michigan, Ohio, New Yor Mich.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Records for low temperatures were set in Alpena, Mich., 5
degrees below zero; Binghamton, N.Y., 3 degrees; Marquette, Mich.,
15 below; and Youngstown, Ohio, 7 degrees. Records were tied in
Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., 9 degrees, and El Paso, Texas, 28.
   Tuesday's forecast called for rain along the northern Pacific
Coast; widely scattered rain showers and mountain snow in the
northern Plateau and the northern and central Rockies; scattered
showers from southern Montana and northern Wyoming into southern
Minnesota, with scattered snow in northern Minnesota; and sunny
skies over eastern and southern sections of the nation.
   High temperatures were expected to reach only into the 20s in
northern New England, in the 30s and 40s over the rest of New
England and from North Dakota to the mid-Atlantic states; in the
40s from Washington into northwest Montana; and in the 70s and 80s
from southern California across the desert Southwest, the southern
Rockies, the southern Plains, the upper and middle Mississippi
Valley and the Southeast; and in the 50s and 60s in most of the
rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
