<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0694 03-21 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0694,0844</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Arab Killed, Army Widens Search For Concealed Weapons</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs after 9th pvs `Protests were ...' to UPDATE
with demonstration in Sidon. PICKS up 10th pvs, `At Rafah...' SUBS
17th pvs, `Time and Newsweek...' with 1 graf to include Reuters
joined suit.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troopers on Monday shot a Palestinian
teen-ager dead and a PLO leaflet exhorted Arabs to ``shower
soldiers and herds of cowardly settlers'' with stones, firebombs
and iron bars.
   Troops expanded their search for weapons in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip the day after an Arab shot and killed a soldier
in Bethlehem.
   At least 106 Palestinians and the Israeli soldier have been
killed since riots began in the occupied lands Dec. 8, according to
U.N. figures.
   Israeli police arrested a prominent Arab-American attorney
Monday and assailants attacked the homes of two moderate
Palestinians _ a newspaper editor and a member of Jordan's
parliament.
   The army announced a new military law permitting any security
prisoner to be held up to six months with less judicial review than
before. It said the law eliminated the requirement that a military
judge review a case within 96 hours.
   Israeli officials said the measure would apply for six months
and would ease an overload on the military court system, which has
handled nearly 3,000 cases since December. Arab lawyers said they
feared detention without trial could become more common.
   Arabs mounted a general strike Monday in the West Bank and Gaza
to mark the anniversary of a 1968 battle resulting from an Israeli
raid on Palestinian guerrillas inside Jordan.
   Graffiti scrawled on walls overnight urged Arabs to attack
Israeli troops and civilians in memory of the battle at Karameh,
Jordan.
   Protests were reported at more than a dozen sites in the West
Bank and Gaza. Palestinian flags, outlawed by Israel, flew from
utility poles and were raised on mosques.
   An estimated 12,000 Palestinians demonstrated at the Ein
el-Hilweh refugee camp in the southern Lebanese port city of Sidon
to show support for the uprisings in the occupied territories.
   Ein el-Hillweh is the largest refugee camp in Lebanon with about
60,000 inhabitants.
   At Rafah, a seaside town in the Gaza Strip, Israeli troops tried
to restrain protesters by dropping tear gas from helicopters, and
then used live ammunition, Arab witnesses said.
   Soldiers shot Abdel Ahmed Jaber al Mudalal, 17, in the chest and
he died of his wounds, according to the Palestine Press Service and
other Arab reports.
   Army spokesmen confirmed the death but said the family took the
body from Nasser Hospital at Khan Yunis and the cause of death
could not be determined.
   Israeli gunfire wounded 16 Palestinians on Monday, according to
hospital officials and the Arab-run press service, which provided
names and ages. The army said 11 Arabs were wounded.
   Leaflet No. 11, the latest distributed by the Palestine
Liberation Organization, told Arabs to prepare for a long struggle
against the Israelis by developing ``home economy, raising
chickens, rabbits and planting vegetables.''
   It urged Palestinians to ``shower soldiers and herds of cowardly
settlers with stones, firebombs and iron bars'' and designated
March 26 as a day of struggle against Israeli-appointed Arab
municipal officials in the West Bank and Gaza.
   ``The people of the uprising will be severe with anyone who
remains outside the national consensus and refuses to resign
immediately,'' it said.
   Time and Newsweek magazines and the Reuters news agency filed a
suit with the Supreme Court in an effort to recover film
confiscated after Sunday's fatal shooting of Israeli Sgt. Moshe
Katz in Bethlehem. Photographers took pictures moments after Katz
was shot in the head.
   ``Demands for the return of the film made repeatedly to Israeli
authorities have been unavailing, and as a result legal action is
being pursued,'' the magazines said in a statement.
   Military officials said soldiers had widened the search for
illegal weapons since the Katz shooting. The Jerusalem Post quoted
one as saying ``substantial amounts of weaponry'' were in the Gaza
Strip but many caches were in mosques, ``beyond the grasp'' of
Israeli soldiers.
   Army policy prohibits soldiers from entering mosques.
   Jonathan Kuttab, the Arab-American lawyer, was charged with
supporting an illegal organization _ a reference to an art exhibit
at the Hakawati Theater that he said included Palestinian
nationalist work.
   Kuttab, who is the theater's attorney and on its board, called
the charge ``ridiculous and an infringement of the freedom of
artists.'' He was released on bail of 1,000 shekels, or about $750.
   Attackers fired shots at the home and car of Jack Khazmo, a
moderate Palestinian editor who lives in Ram, a village just north
of Jerusalem, and threw three firebombs at the home of Mousa Abu
Ghosh, a member of Jordan's parliament, in the West Bank city of
Ramallah.
   Israel captured the West Bank and Gaza Strip from Jordan and
Egypt in 1967.
</TEXT>
