<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Evans 1stLd-Writethru a0759 03-21 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Evans, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0759,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gil Evans, Great of Jazz Orchestration, Dead at 75</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th graf pvs, `They were...', to add
comment from Miles Davis. Picks up 6th graf, `Trumpeter Dizzy...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gil Evans, a composer, pianist and band leader
considered one of the greatest orchestrators in jazz, has died in
Mexico, his widow said here Monday. He was 75.
   Evans died Sunday in Cuernavaca of peritonitis while
recuperating from prostate surgery, Anita Evans said in New York.
   Evans, who had led his band in a New York City club in December
and January, decided not to return to the club in March but to go
to Mexico to recuperate. Mrs. Evans said that he felt energetic
when he left on the trip and he took his synthesizer and their two
sons, Noah and Miles.
   Evans made his mark in the 1950s and 1960s with innovative
arrangements for trumpeter Miles Davis, particularly three
recordings that showcased Davis' cool style: ``Miles Ahead,''
``Porgy and Bess'' and ``Sketches of Spain.''
   ``They were really among the most brilliant orchestral jazz
records made by anybody,'' said jazz historian and writer Leonard
Feather. ``He made brilliant use of tone colors.''
   Through his spokeswoman, Terry Williams, Davis said: ``Whenever
I had a question about the music, composing or which way to go, I
would think about what Gil would do. I'll really miss him.''
   Trumpeter Dizzy Gillespie, reached in Los Angeles, said Evans
would be missed ``for keeping time with the age that he's in.''
   ``Whatever new thing, new ideas come up, Gil Evans was right on
top them,'' said Gillespie, who knew Evans well but did not perform
with him. ``He will be missed for having a very strong feeling for
the soloist. He was tender. One of a kind.''
   Evans was born in Toronto May 13, 1912, and grew up in Stockton,
Calif., where he organized a jazz band in high school. His first
professional band, in Stockton, was taken over by Skinnay Ennis,
but Evans stayed on as arranger.
   He was beginning the style that deployed instruments to bring
out richness of tone and textures. He never left jazz as his base,
and his arrangements never conflicted with the sense of spontaneity
vital to jazz.
   After he worked as arranger for the Claude Thornhill Orchestra
during the 1940s, Evans' reputation grew with his work for Davis'
nine-piece band in 1949. He blended French horn and tuba on Davis'
``Boplicity'' and ``Birth of the Cool,'' which proved influential.
   His first recording with his own band, ``The Arranger's Touch,''
used French horn, muted trumpet and bassoon in arrangements marked
by originality. Evans arranged for Davis again in 1959, with Davis
playing flugelhorn over a 19-piece orchestra, on the album ``Miles
Ahead.''
   Evans orchestrated two more Davis albums, ``Porgy and Bess'' and
``Sketches of Spain,'' tailoring them to Davis' artistic
temperament. He worked as a free-lance arranger, doing works like
Cannonball Adderley's ``Pacific Standard Time'' album and his own
``Out of the Cool.''
   A project to arrange for rock guitarist Jimi Hendrix was
canceled by Hendrix's death in 1970. Later, Evans recorded ``Gil
Evans Plays Hendrix.'' He scored the film ``Absolute Beginners'' at
age 74.
   An upcoming tour of northern Europe by the Gil Evans Orchestra,
plus appearances at jazz festivals in Umbria, Italy, and New York
will go on, Mrs. Evans said, with son Miles Evans conducting.
   She said that a memorial service will be held, probably on
Easter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880321-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 2041EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NicaraguaTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0760 03-21 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0760,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Both Sides Agree to Stop Fighting During Negotiations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with Monday's talks ending,
both sides propose cease-fires. PICKS up 10th graf pvs, `Cheering
Sandinista...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAPOA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sandinista government and
U.S.-backed rebels on Monday opened three days of talks in this
border town by exchanging cease-fire proposals and agreeing to a
truce during the negotiations.
   ``Neither side seeks a military victory over the other,'' said
Alfredo Cesar, head of the rebel delegation, after the completion
of the first day of talks _ the first face-to-face negotiations on
Nicaraguan soil.
   He said the Contra rebels proposed a 30-day cease-fire and
continuous talks to reach a permanent truce.
   Cesar told reporters the Contras also proposed total amnesty and
guarantees of free expression to lead toward reconciliation. He
called Monday's talks, which were behind closed doors, ``a step
ahead.''
   Defense Minister Humberto Ortega, leader of the government
delegation, said he proposed an ``immediate and definitive
cease-fire.'' He did not elaborate.
   The rebels, battered by a two-week-old Sandinista offensive,
agreed to accept a truce for the duration of the negotiations in
what Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros called ``a gesture of good
will.''
   Frank Arana, another Contra spokesman, said the two sides
discussed military and political issues including ``concepts of
democracy.''
   If so, it would be the first time the Sandinistas consented to
discuss political issues with the rebels.
   In two rounds of indirect talks in the Dominican Republic and
Costa Rica, the Sandinistas demanded the negotiations deal
exclusively on the mechanics of a cease-fire.
   Negotiations opened after Ortega, brother of President Daniel
Ortega, said the Sandinistas were suspending military operations
for the duration of the talks and called on the Contras to do the
same.
   Sandinista spokesman Manuel Espinoza said the ``reciprocation of
the Contras'' in agreeing to suspend hostilities and ``the fact
that this meeting is taking place are the first positive steps''
toward a permanent cease-fire. He spoke to reporters during the
lunch break.
   The rebels entered the talks in this small town on the border
with Costa Rica without high expectations of Sandinista concessions.
   Cesar told reporters earlier that he feared the rebels were
being weakened ``by the suspension of United States aid and the
growth in Soviet aid to the Sandinistas.''
   Unlike the two previous rounds of negotiations, the Sapoa agenda
was supposed to be open. On Sunday, however, Sandinista officials
said they would focus on a cease-fire in the civil war, which began
in 1981 and has cost an estimated 40,000 lives.
   Cheering Sandinista supporters calling for a Contra
``surrender'' lined both sides of the 90-mile road the government
delegation traveled from Managua to Sapoa. The Contras arrived from
Costa Rica.
   Soldiers and security agents in plainclothes guarded Sapoa.
Security was especially tight at the customs house, where the talks
were being held.
   With the Sandinista were Brian Wilson, an American pacifist
whose legs were severed by a train in Califoria during a protest
last year, and singer-actor Kris Kristofferson. Both are Sandinista
supporters of long standing.
   The Contras made Cesar, once a high Sandinista official, head of
their delegation in hopes of gaining benefit from his familiarity
with the Sandinistas.
   Cesar said he last visited Sapoa as a Sandinista revolutionary
fighting the late President Anastasio Somoza, who was overthrown in
July 1979.
   ``It has been nine years since I was last in Sapoa and I am
still struggling for the freedom of Nicaragua,'' he said. Cesar
broke with the Sandinistas in 1982.
   Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, Nicaragua's Roman Catholic
prelate who mediated earlier talks, and Joao Baena Soares, general
secretary of the Organization of American States, attended the
meeting as observers.
   Cease-fire talks are required under the peace plan signed by the
presidents of Nicaragua, Honduras, Costa Rica, El Salvador and
Guatemala last August. Among other provisions are amnesties,
greater democracy and an end to the use of one nation's territory
for attacks on another.
</TEXT>
