<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MobKilling 1stLd-Writethru a0753 03-21 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mob Killing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0753,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Charged With Manslaughter After Crowd Beats Robbery Suspect
To Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `The killing...', to CLARIFY that drug war
zone description was applied to section of Spanish Harlem, sted the
entire neighborhood. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `This is...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men and a teen-ager who ``thought they had
done the right thing'' were charged Monday with manslaughter in the
beating death of a man who allegedly stole $20 and was chased by a
mob in a drug-ravaged neighborhood.
   The four were surprised when told they were being charged in the
death of Raymondo Caraballo, 41, said detective Capt. William
Quigley.
   ``They thought they had done the right thing, chasing and
capturing this guy,'' Quigley said. ``Well, somebody's dead.
Somebody's got to be responsible for it.''
   Three others were being sought and arrests were expected, he
said.
   The killing took place in a section of Spanish Harlem that
residents and area workers described as a drug war zone.
   ``This is Vietnam here. It's bad, it's bad,'' said a city worker
cleaning out a room on the ground floor of the building outside
which Caraballo was beaten. He insisted on anonymity.
   The suspect entered a bakery shortly after noon Sunday and
grabbed $20 from 21-year-old Anna Beteran, witnesses told police.
   ``I heard the people screaming,'' bakery co-owner Orlando Testa
said Monday. ``The guy stole the money from the girl and ran away.''
   As Caraballo ran out, Beteran and her unidentified sister-in-law
chased him, police said. The women lost sight of him when he ducked
into the Jefferson Houses project about a block away, Quigley said.
   As the women asked members of a crowd on the corner if they had
seen the man, Caraballo appeared and the group gave chase.
   ``They started to beat him (with) fists and feet,'' Quigley said
at an afternoon news conference. A garbage can cover was thrown at
Caraballo, but it was deflected and did not hit him, as reported
earlier, Quigley said.
   ``He was getting beaten all over, the legs, the ribs,'' said Al
Rivera, 27, who was visiting a friend in the area of the beating
Sunday.
   ``He was yelling, `Please stop. No more, no more,''' Rivera
said, pointing to the blue scaffolding under which the beating took
place.
   Housing police who were called in broke up the crowd. The man
stood up and was handcuffed, but the officers radioed for an
ambulance as they took him away.
   The man died about five hours later at Mount Sinai Hospital.
Hospital personnel said, according to Quigley, that Caraballo had
irreversible brain trauma and internal injuries. An autopsy was
scheduled.
   Quigley identified the four charged with first- and
second-degree manslaughter as David Andino, 22, Charles Mimms, 20,
Jesus Negron, 23, and Isidore Cuadrado, 14. None knew the man who
was killed or the others arrested, Quigley said.
   Negron was arrested about 10 p.m. Sunday and the other three
surrendered overnight because ``the word was out in the street,''
Quigley said.
   In the neighborhood bodegas, in the housing project and on the
street, the talk Monday was about drugs and robberies and an
exasperating way of life that causes people to live by looking over
their shoulders.
   ``It's frightening. ... It's crazy,'' Julia White, a 16-year
resident and supervisor with the Jefferson Houses Tenants
Association, said about the presence of drug users.
   ``There's no answer to it. And there's no end to it,'' she said,
shaking her head.
   ``Last year, a girl was found killed ...'' she said, hesitating
as he suddenly remembered where: ``In here. Oh, my goodness.''
</TEXT>
