<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IslamicConference 2ndLd-Writethru a0665 03-21 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Islamic Conference, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0665,0759</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jordan Ask Arabs to Support Rebellion Against Israel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Iranian envoy saying Iran
would accept help in ending war; Iraq's U.N. ambassador accusing
Iran of using chemical weapons. PICKS up 4th graf pvs, `The king
...' ADDS 6 grafs at bottom with details of Iranian allegations.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press WWiter</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein on Monday urged the Moslem
world to support the revolt in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip, where more than 100 Palestinians and an Israeli soldier
have been killed since Dec. 8.
   Opening a meeting of foreign ministers of the 46-member
Organization of Islamic Conference, the Jordanian monarch also
expressed hope that Iran would agree to a cease-fire in its war
with Iraq.
   The Iranian envoy to the conference, Mohammed Ali Tashkiri, told
reporters that his nation would accept the help of any ``truthful
hand'' that tried to end the devastating Iran-Iraq missile duel on
each other's cities.
   At the United Nations Monday, Iraq's U.N. ambassador accused
Iraq of using chemical weapons which he said killed 5,000 people
and wounded 5,000 in Kurdish border cities inside Iran.
   King Hussein told the conference in his opening address: ``The
Palestinian people have a rightful claim on us to support their
uprising both on the national and international level so that the
uprising (in the occupied territories) may bear fruit.''
   The king did not elaborate on what forms aid should take, but
asked the ministers to support an international conference on
Middle East peace.
   Sharifuddin Pir Zadeh, secretary-general of the Islamic
conference, said earlier that protesters in the Israeli-occupied
territories should be supported ``financially and morally.''
   Hussein said the Palestinian were ``heroically fighting for
their freedom and national rights and defying in their uprising the
arrogance of the forces of occupation.''
   He said there should be a seat for the Palestine Liberation
Organization at an international peace conference, which would
involve the parties to the conflict and the five permanent members
of the U.N. Security Council: the United States, Soviet Union,
Britain, France and China.
   By calling for a PLO seat at the conference, Hussein set himself
apart from U.S. peace proposals, which he discussed in Amman on
Sunday with U.S. envoy Philip Habib. The U.S. plan does not call
for a PLO seat at the conference.
   ``The uprising of the Palestinian people is not an end in itself
nor is it a transient coincidental event that will soon wither
away,'' Hussein said. ``It is rather an expression of the will of
an entire nation to fight for its freedom and right of
self-determination in its own land.''
   The rebellion in the occupied territories, which Palestinians
call ``the uprising,'' and the Iran-Iraq war dominate the agenda of
the meeting, at which all members of the Conference except Chad are
represented.
   King Hussein, who supports Iraq in the war, called the conflict
a ``deep wound in the body'' of the Moslem world that is ``bleeding
and draining our resources and energies.''
   ``Our hope is that Iran ... will accept Security Council
Resolution 598, which represents the will of the international
community,'' he said.
   The resolution, passed last July, provides for a cease-fire and
return to pre-war borders.
   Iraq has said it will stop shooting if Iran does but the
Iranians demand that Iraq be named the aggressor before a truce
takes effect. Iraq invaded Iran in September 1980 after several
border skirmishes.
   Tashkiri, who heads the foreign relations department in Iran's
Ministry of Information and Religious Guidance, told journalists
that he would attempt to get the conference to discuss the missile
duel.
   ``We support a halt in the war of the cities and we will back
any truthful hand that tries to stop it,'' he said.
   The relatively low-ranking level of the Iranian delegation in
Amman appeared to make it unlikely such negotiations would start at
the conference.
   Iran's U.N. ambassador, Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati, accused Iraq
of sending planes to bombard border cities with nerve gas on a
scale ``unprecedented'' in the Persian Gulf war, and also of
employing mustard gas and cyanide gas in a campaign that began
March 17.
   Iraq's ambassador, Ismat Taha Kittani, refused comment.
   Mahallatti asked the U.N. Security Council to denounce Iraq, to
send a fact-finding team to verify his claims and to mobilize the
World Health Organization and similar agencies to aid victims.
</TEXT>
