<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Explosions     03-21 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Explosions,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Explosions in Downtown Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion Monday near the imperial palace and
another blast close to the Israeli Embassy shattered windows but
caused no injuries and apparently were the work of radicals, said
police.
   A motorcycle rigged as a bomb burst into flames and exploded at
7:17 p.m. near Hibiya Park, about 900 yards southeast of the
imperial palace, breaking windows in the Saudi Arabian Airlines
office, said a police official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   About 15 minutes later, explosives in the trunk of a parked car
went off 3{ miles away, near the Israeli Embassy, breaking windows
in buildings nearby, he said. There were no reports of damage at
the embassy.
   The police official said Japanese radicals, who sometimes fire
homemade missiles from cars parked in streets, may have been
responsible for the explosions in downtown Tokyo. No more details
were immediately available.
   In February, four shuttle buses used to transport passengers to
and from airports were burned in Tokyo in apparent attacks by
radicals opposed to expanding the New Tokyo International Airport
at Narita. There were no reports of injuries.
   Narita area farmers and their supporters, including
anti-government radical groups, have resisted plans to expropriate
farmland for a second runway at the $2.5 billion airport at Narita.
   In 1986, radicals fired homemade missiles at the state guest
house, U.S. Embassy, imperial palace, crown prince's residence and
Osaka police headquarters before the seven-nation summit meeeting
held in Tokyo in May.
   One attack occurred during Japan's welcoming ceremonies for the
heads of government of the United States, Canada, Britain, France,
West Germany and Italy.
</TEXT>
