<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Irish 2ndLd-Writethru a0822 03-21 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0822,0729</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Policeman Slain by IRA; Announce Manhunt For Killers of Soldier</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RESTORES exact figure of 2,638 in last graf, Since 1969 ...
Separate toll lists kept and figure unaltered</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   IRA gunmen killed a policeman
Monday at a checkpoint in Londonderry, the 12th victim in two weeks
of heightening tension and sectarian violence.
   Britain announced a massive manhunt in West Belfast's Roman
Catholic ghettos for the killers of two British soldiers caught in
an IRA funeral procession.
   Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King said in London that the
Royal Ulster Constabulary has launched an immediate review of its
new policy of keeping a low profile at Irish Republican Army
funerals. The policy was aimed at avoiding clashes between police
and supporters of the outlawed IRA.
   The policeman who was killed Monday, Clive Graham, 25, was shot
in the head in a jeep while at a checkpoint in the Roman Catholic
Creggan district of Londonderry, Northern Ireland's second-largest
city. He died later in the hospital.
   The IRA claimed responsibility for Graham's killing in a
clandestine message to Belfast media.
   He was the 12th person to die since March 6, when British
commandos shot dead three IRA guerrillas who allegedly were
plotting a car bombing in Gibraltar.
   The funeral policy was started Wednesday at services for the
guerrillas killed in Gibraltar. A Protestant gunman opened fire and
hurled grenades at the Catholic Milltown cemetery, killing three
people and wounding 68.
   King's announcement of a review of the policy stopped well short
of demands by leaders of Northern Ireland Protestant parties to
return to a heavy presence at IRA funerals.
   As expectations grew of an imminent wave of arrests in West
Belfast, there was also speculation that dozens of IRA supporters
who were filmed surrounding and beating the soldiers' unmarked car
with iron bars and dragging them out had gone into hiding.
   ``A massive murder investigation is under way in which all
possible resources are involved to identify all those
responsible,'' King said of the manhunt in West Belfast.
   Three people were arrested Saturday and police sources said
Monday that up to 30 others were being sought after hours of
scrutiny of film taken by an army helicopter which hovered over the
scene and by TV networks. Gruesome scenes of the attack also were
shown on television.
   Cpls. Derek Wood and David Howes, in plainclothes, were
surrounded when they drove up to the cortege, dragged from their
car, stripped, beaten and shot dead.
   King said an emergency meeting of senior government ministers
from Britain and the Republic of Ireland will be held this week to
consider stepped up security.
   King denied charges by Northern Ireland Protestant politicians
that police and troops failed to come to the soldiers' aid because
of political orders to stay away from IRA funerals.
   He said it was not immediately clear to police watching film
relayed from the helicopter that soldiers were under attack because
police ``were certain there were no security forces in the area
whatsoever.''
   He said the soldiers were under general orders to keep out of
Catholic districts unless on operational duty and had ``no reason
to be in the vicinity of the funerals.'' He said he did not know
why they were there.
   As the Commons listened in silence, King praised the corporals,
identified as signals corpsmen heading back to barracks after doing
maintenance work at a base in Belfast, for their restraint in
firing only one shot into the mob that surrounded them.
   ``The truth is that there will be new depths (of horror) again
as long as this awful and evil campaign of terrorism and revenge
continues,'' King said.
   ``It has got to stop in the name of humanity and if there is to
be any decent future for the people of Northern Ireland and for all
those living in the island of Ireland, and if the evil shroud of
terrorism is to be lifted from the United Kingdom as whole.''
   Since 1969, 2,638 people have been killed in the sectarian
violence in this Protestant-dominated province. The IRA is fighting
to end British rule and unite Northern Ireland with the Catholic
Republic of Ireland under a leftist administration.
</TEXT>
