<HEAD>Drug Charges Added Against Attorney In Lisa Steinberg's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury has added drug and weapons charges
to the indictment against an attorney charged with murder in the
beating death of a 6-year-old girl he had illegally adopted, a
prosecutor said Monday.
   Officers found heroin, cocaine and marijuana in Joel Steinberg's
Greenwich Village apartment on Nov. 2 when they discovered Lisa
Steinberg comatose and brain dead, Manhattan District Attorney
Robert Morgenthau said.
   The apartment also contained scales, crack pipes and drug recipe
cards for cocaine and heroin derivatives along with a .45-caliber
revolver and bullets for another weapon, Morgenthau said.
   The child's death touched off a nationwide debate on child abuse
and the role of school and welfare officials in trying to prevent
it.
   A nine-count indictment, which supersedes a November indictment,
also charges that Steinberg abused the girl during the two months
before her death, the prosecutor said. The original indictment
charged him with endangering the welfare of a child on Nov. 2.
   The new abuse charge is a felony. The weapons, drug and
drug-paraphernalia possession charges are misdemeanors.
   Steinberg has been held without bail in protective custody at
Rikers Island. His longtime companion, Hedda Nussbaum, remains at
Columbia-Presbyterian Hospital, where she has been undergoing
psychiatric treatment.
   After the girl's death, Ms. Nussbaum, an author and former
children's book editor, was treated for a broken nose, injured eye
and other injuries apparently stemming from a beating.
   She was charged by police in connection with Lisa's death but
has not been indicted. Prosecutors said they would let her receive
treatment before she decides whether to testify before a grand jury.
   Lisa's biological mother, an unwed teen-ager, has testified she
gave her newborn daughter to Steinberg to arrange an adoption. The
lawyer has admitted during a Family Court hearing that he kept the
child without legally adopting her.
</TEXT>
