<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites Sub a0748 03-21 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites, Sub, a0748,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS for Grand Rapids, Mich.-dated second item to CORRECT
name of village to Sand Lake, sted Nelson Village, in 2nd graf, add
background in 6th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralph Boerman is the lucky winner of
an election in which candidates and voters stayed away in droves.
   Boerman, Bob VandenBerg and Earl Thomas got exactly one write-in
vote apiece in the coolly contested March 14 election in Sand Lake,
a northern Kent County village of about 200 people.
   On Monday, three Kent County employees gathered around a box to
see if Boerman, VandenBerg or Thomas would be the next village
trustee.
   VandenBerg's and Thomas' proxies drew slips marked ``Not
Elected.'' Boerman's proxy drew the slip marked ``Elected'' and
Boerman, who like the other candidates didn't attend the draw-off,
became the new trustee of the village north of Grand Rapids.
   The 22-year-old winner, who has never held elective office,
confessed Monday he's got a lot to learn about his new job. He
isn't sure how many people are on the Board of Trustees, what it
does or how much he gets paid.
   ``I guess it just helps run (Nelson) Township and decides what
happens,'' Boerman said, referring to the township in which Sand
Lake is contained. ``I really don't know but I will find out, the
hard way.''
   Election law requires tie votes to be resolved by a drawing.
   Vandenberg, 51, just resigned as the village president, a post
he held for six years. Thomas, 40, is a former village clerk.
</TEXT>
