<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0716,0785</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Ships Attacked as Tanker War's Worst Casualties Reported</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Tuesday attack, at least
one injury, details; PICKS up 3rd graf pvs, `There was ...' Minor
editing thruout to TRIM and conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shipping executives said Iranian gunboats
attacked a Norwegian-operated tanker in the Persian Gulf early
Tuesday, three days after an Iraqi attack on a Norwegian ship left
54 seamen missing and presumed dead.
   Three rockets hit the the 380,534-ton Havglint, a liquified
pertroleum gas carrier that was carrying ammonia from Saudi Arabia,
a shipping source said on condition of anonymity. The ship flies
the Singapore flag but is operated by the Oslo-based company
Havtor, shipping executives said.
   At least one person was injured in the latest attack 12 miles
northwest of Dubai, said the executives, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The executives said the Havglint was leaking chemicals that
could pose be a pollution problem.
   It was the seventh shipping attack since Friday, when Iran, in
apparent reprisal for the resumption of Iraqi strikes against its
oil lifeline, ended a five-week hiatus in assaults on commercial
shipping in the gulf.
   On Monday, Iran attacked and set ablaze a Spanish freighter and
a Liberian tanker.
   There was no word on casualties aboard the 10,168-ton Spanish
refrigerator ship Iberian Reefer, which was ``burning fiercely'' at
dusk, hours after it was attacked in the Strait of Hormuz, maritime
salvage experts said.
   Salvage tugboats went to the scene. There was no word on
casualties.
   Earlier, shipping executives said at least one Iranian gunboat
fired rocket-propelled grenades at the 61,762-ton
Liberian-registered Fumi, setting its engine room ablaze and
blasting holes in one of its tanks.
   The Japanese-managed tanker, carrying Saudi Arabian oil, was on
its way out of the gulf. Shipping executives said salvage tugboats
helped the Fumi's crew extinguish the blaze.
   Spain called the attack on the Iberian Reefer ``an act of
aggression'' and summoned Teheran's ambassador to Spain to the
Foreign Ministry for an explanation.
   The maritime insurance firm, Lloyd's of London, said 37 ships
have been damaged in attacks by Iraq and Iran this year, more than
twice as many as in the first 2{ months of 1987, which was the
worst year for shipping since the gulf war began in 1980. The
figure did not include the attack on the Havglint.
   A Norwegian foreign ministry spokesman told The Associated Press
that 54 crewmen were presumed dead after Iraqi jets bombed two
Iranian tankers at the Kharg island oil terminal in the northern
gulf on Saturday.
   Most of the crew were Iranians or Asians, although a Swedish
officer was among the missing.
   If the Norwegian report is correct, it would be the highest
casualty toll in any attack by either side in the 4-year-old
``tanker war.''
   Christen Puntervold, spokesman for the Norwegian Shipping
Association in Oslo, said only four of 29 crewmen aboard the
253,837-ton Sanandaj were known to have survived, and all 29 aboard
the second tanker, the 316,379-ton Avaj, were missing.
   Both ships are owned by the Iran's National Iranian Tanker Co.
   A senior official of the Bahrain government suggested it was
time for a joint ``declaration'' that no interference with shipping
was tolerable.
   Information Minister Tariq Al-Moayyed told NBC News that foreign
forces should ``reach a declaration ... that they will not allow
interference with freedom of shipping in the gulf.''
   The Iraqi attacks are aimed at disrupting Iran's oil exports,
through which it finances the war, and forcing Tehran to accept a
peace proposal put forth by the United Nations.
   Iraq, meanwhile, fired a long-range missile into Tehran on
Monday in the 105th such attack in three weeks. Iran said 14
civilians, including two young girls, were killed in the explosion.
   The missile attack followed an unabated 24-hour artillery and
rocket barrage on Basra, Iraq's second-largest city and its only
outlet to the gulf.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, also monitored in Nicosia,
reported ``heavy casualties'' in Basra.
   Both sides have fired nearly 250 missiles into each other's main
cities and border towns since Feb. 29, reportedly killing hundreds
of civilians.
   Iran said that scores of Kurdish children, aged two to 10, were
being treated in Tehran hospitals for injuries they sustained when
Iraqi troops dropped outlawed chemical bombs in a border region
last week.
   Iran had said 5,000 Kurds were killed and 4,000 wounded when
Iraqi planes dropped chemical bombs on the town of Halabja and
adjacent villages after their capture in a land offensive.
</TEXT>
