<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-AcidSpill     03-21 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Acid Spill,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Tons Of Sulfuric Acid Spill On City Street</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tank loaded with sulfuric acid tumbled off the
back of a truck Monday, spilling six tons of the chemical onto a
street in the Volga River city of Ulyanovsk, the Tass news agency
said.
   The six tons of acid poured out onto the asphalt, but
specialists neutralized it with soda and none of the acid got into
Ulyanovsk's sewer system or ground water, Tass said.
   The agency said no injuries were reported in the accident in the
city of more than 480,000 people, about 500 miles east of Moscow.
   It said an investigation was under way.
   Tass blamed negligent workers at the Kontaktor plant for failing
to make certain the tank was securely fastened.
   Vladimir I. Lenin, founder of the Soviet state, was born in the
city in 1870, when it was called Simbursk. Lenin's real name was
Ulyanov, and Soviet authorities renamed the city in his honor
following his death in 1924.
</TEXT>
