<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest squabble between prosecutors and
defense attornyes isn't about cases, tactics or money. It's about
being able to bypass new security procedures at the Dirksen Federal
Building, and it's headed for _ where else? _ the bench.
   Complaints from the public have been few, but the security
system brought the entire U.S. District Court system here to a
screeching halt one afternoon and prompted 39 attorneys _ including
several of Chicago's best-known defenders _ to petition the
district's 21 judges for the same exemptions granted to prosecutors
and building employees. A decision is expected Thursday.
   The U.S. Marshal's office said the procedures were in response
to a growing number of threats against the federal judiciary
nationwide and an increase in terrorism trials. They follow recent
trials of members of the El Rukn street gang and the Puerto Rican
independence group, FALN, on terrorism-related charges.
