<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 0838EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Philippines-Plantation Adv30   03-21 0802</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Plantation, Adv 30,0829</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs March 30 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Run Plantation Flourishes Despite Rebel Threats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANOLO FORTICH, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although Communist rebels
threaten to attack U.S. businesses in the Philippines, one American
company is growing pineapples on a substantial chunk of Mindanao
island and showing little fear in doing it.
   ``It's a very open company and a very open society,'' said Brian
Carew, field operations manager of the Philippine Packing Corp.,
local subsidiary of RJR Reynolds, which now owns the Del Monte
brand of products. ``I feel safer here than in New York.''
   Communist rebels, who operate near this giant plantation some
500 miles southeast of Manila, have threatened to attack American
interests in retaliation for U.S. support of Philippines
governments that have been fighting the insurgents for 19 years.
   This past November the rival Dole-Philippines Inc., considered
abandoning its fruit plantation in Mindanao's South Cotabato
province after raids by Communist rebels resulted in more than
$250,000 worth of property and equipment damage.
   The Del Monte plantation, in Bukidnon province, has no fencing
and only a small security force.
   In December, Communist New People's Army guerrillas raided a
military camp in the Bukidnon town of Don Carlos and made off with
a machine gun, more than 20 automatic assault rifles, grenades and
thousands of rounds of ammunition.
   Carew, a native of Dorchester, Mass., said Communist bands
occasionally pass through the western side of the plantation but
have not attacked. He said Del Monte does not pay the rebels
protection money.
   Since Del Monte began operations in the Philippines in 1926, its
holdings have grown from about 9,880 acres to more than 61,750
acres around the towns of Impasugong, Sumilao, Libona and Manolo
Fortich.
   One-third of the land is leased from the government's National
Development Corp. for about $16 an acre a year. The rest is leased
from local farmers.
   Company officials said in interviews with The Associated Press
that Del Monte employs about 10,600 workers, including about 100 at
company headquarters in Manila. Most workers come from Bukidnon and
neighboring Misamis Oriental province.
   The subsidiary had gross sales of $110 million last year and net
income of $20.7 million. It earned $78.8 million in hard currency
for the Philippines and paid the Philippines peso equivalent of $21
million in taxes.
   Company officials estimate that about 60,000 people in the area
depend on the plantation.
   At Camp Philipps, the largest of the subsidiary's seven camps,
workers's quarters are simple but adequate. A large social hall
dominates the main road, next to a cooperative store where workers
buy most of their daily needs.
   ``Speak English'' signs are posted on the walls of the camp's
vocational school for boys.
   Children of management officials, including Carew's 12-year-old
daughter, Jessica, attend the Del Monte School up to seventh grade.
The school teaches 20 to 25 children, about three-fourths of them
Filipino.
   Private secondary schools and colleges are subsidized by the
comany and tuition fees are comparatively low.
   Officials said the average daily salary is 105 pesos ($5.25),
nearly double the mandated minimum wage. Medical treatment is free.
Housing, including electricity and water, is free for some 2,000
senior employees while others get housing allowances.
   Brian Haycox, the Philippines company president, said Del Monte
believes in above average worker benefits because ``we can't run
our business, manage it and address all the issues facing us today
unless we have good human resource development.''
   The company does not allow visiting journalists to interview
workers unless accompanied by an official.
   ``I don't apologize to anybody about what we do because we do it
well,'' Carew told a group of visiting reporters.
   The company came in for criticism this past October in report by
a Swiss mission that visited in February 1987. The mission, made up
of the Migros Cooperative Society, Swiss Aid, Helbetas, Swiss
Lenten Fund and Bread for Brethren, said many workers complained of
harassment and intimidation by lower- and middle-grade supervisors
and of unjustified promotions.
   ``The overriding feeling is one of fear of losing the job,'' the
report said. ``Mistrust of the company is widespread.''
   It added that workers showed ``little confidence'' in their
unions, the Associated Labor Union and the Workers Alliance of
Trade Unions, which it said are perceived as pro-management.
   But worker activity against the company has been limited.
   Some workers have been picketing the company's cannery in nearby
Gugo, and a company bus was set afire early this year.
   The Swiss mission report also criticized the company's policy of
leasing land from local farmers, charging the leases are couched in
language the farmers can't understand.
   Adrian Pabayo, the company's public relations manager, defended
the policy.
   ``There is enough land available here not being used,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs March 30</NOTE>
