<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv 31,0539</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, March 31</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Thursday, March 31, the 91st day of 1988. There are 275
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   Twenty years ago, on March 31, 1968, President Lyndon B. Johnson
stunned the country with a surprise announcement at the end of a
broadcast address on the Vietnam War, telling the audience, ``I
shall not seek, and I will not accept, the nomination of my party
for another term as your president.''
   On this date:
   In 1831, Quebec and Montreal were incorporated as cities.
   In 1870, Thomas Peterson Mundy cast a ballot in a municipal
election in Perth Amboy, N.J., becoming the first black to vote
following ratification of the 15th Amendment.
   In 1880, Wabash, Ind., became the first town to be completely
illuminated with electrical lighting.
   In 1889, the Eiffel Tower, in Paris, was officially opened to
the public.
   In 1917, the United States took possession of the Virgin Islands
from Denmark.
   In 1923, the first dance marathon in the United States, held in
New York City, ended with Alma Cummings setting a world record of
27 hours on her feet.
   In 1932, Ford Motor Co. publicly unveiled its V-8 engine.
   In 1933, during the Great Depression, Congress authorized the
Civilian Conservation Corps.
   In 1943, the Rodgers and Hammerstein musical ``Oklahoma!''
opened on Broadway.
   In 1949, Newfoundland entered confederation as Canada's 10th
province.
   In 1953, the United Nations Security Council nominated Dag
Hammarskjold of Sweden to become Secretary-General.
   In 1976, the New Jersey Supreme Court ruled that Karen Anne
Quinlan, in a coma for almost a year, could be disconnected from
her respirator. Quinlan, who remained in a coma, died in June 1985.
   In 1980, former track and field star Jesse Owens, hero of the
1936 Berlin Olympics, died in Tucson, Ariz., of lung cancer at the
age of 66.
   In 1986, 167 people died when a Mexicana Airlines Boeing 727
crashed in a remote mountainous region of Mexico in that country's
worst aviation disaster.
   Ten years ago: President Jimmy Carter arrived in Nigeria on the
first official visit by an American president to black Africa.
   Five years ago: Some 5,000 people died when a major earthquake
struck southern Colombia, devastating the mountain city of Popayan.
   One year ago: The judge in the ``Baby M'' case in Hackensack,
N.J., awarded custody of the girl born under a surrogate-motherhood
contract to her natural father, William Stern, instead of her
biological mother, Mary Beth Whitehead.
   Today's Birthdays: Radio and TV personality Henry Morgan is 73.
Actor Richard Kiley is 66. Actor William Daniels is 61. Labor
leader Cesar Chavez is 61. Former hockey star Gordie Howe is 60.
Actress Shirley Jones is 54. Actor Richard Chamberlain is 53.
Musician Herb Alpert is 53. Senator Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., is 48.
Actor Christopher Walken is 45. Comedian Gabe Kaplan is 43.
   Thought for Today: ``The most important thing about Spaceship
Earth -- an instruction book didn't come with it.'' -- R.
Buckminster Fuller, American architect and author (1895-1983).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
