<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv 02,0476</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Saturday, April 2</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, April 2, the 93rd day of 1988. There are 273
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On April 2, 1917, saying, ``The world must be made safe for
democracy,'' President Woodrow Wilson asked Congress to declare war
against Germany.
   On this date:
   In 1513, Spanish explorer Juan Ponce de Leon landed in Florida.
   In 1792, Congress authorized establishment of the U.S. Mint.
   In 1805, storyteller Hans Christian Andersen was born in Odense,
Denmark.
   In 1834, Frederic Auguste Bartholdi, the sculptor who created
the Statue of Liberty, was born in Colmar, France.
   In 1860, the first Italian Parliament met at Turin.
   In 1865, Confederate President Jefferson Davis and most of his
cabinet fled the Confederate capital of Richmond, Va.
   In 1872, Samuel F.B. Morse, the developer of the electric
telegraph, died in New York.
   In 1932, aviator Charles A. Lindbergh and Dr. John F. Condon
turned over $50,000 to an unidentified man in a Bronx, N.Y.,
cemetery as ransom for Lindbergh's kidnapped son.
   In 1956, the soap operas ``As the World Turns'' and ``The Edge
of Night'' premiered on CBS television.
   In 1974, French president Georges Pompidou died in Paris.
   In 1982, several thousand troops from Argentina seized the
disputed Falkland Islands from Britain. Britain would seize them
back by the following June.
   In 1986, four Americans were killed when a bomb exploded aboard
a TWA jetliner that was en route from Rome to Athens, Greece.
   In 1986, Alabama Gov. George C. Wallace announced he was
retiring from public life.
   Ten years ago: President Jimmy Carter told reporters during his
visit to Nigeria that the United StAtes and Britain were trying to
bring all sides in the Rhodesia dispute together in an effort to
arrange a peaceful transition to black majority rule.
   Five years ago: Soviet Foreign Minister Andrei Gromyko issued a
stinging rejection of President Reagan's proposal for reducing
medium-range missiles in Europe, telling a news conference in
Moscow the plan was ``unacceptable on all counts.''
   One year ago: The U.S. Senate, rejecting a plea from President
Reagan, overrode his veto of an $88 billion highway and mass
transit bill that the president had denounced as containing
``pork-barrel'' items.
   Today's Birthdays: Actor Buddy Ebsen is 80. Producer Irene Mayer
Selznick is 78. Actor Sir Alec Guinness is 74. The Archbishop of
Chicago, Cardinal Joseph Bernardin, is 60. Actress Sharon Acker is
53. Singer Emmylou Harris is 40. Actress Debralee Scott is 35.
Actor Ron Palillo is 34.
   Thought for Today: ``Birth, ancestry and that which you yourself
have not achieved can hardly be called your own.'' -- Greek proverb.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
