<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Blacks-PoliticalProgress Adv27   03-21 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Blacks-Political Progress, Adv 27,0765</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 27, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With BC-Blacks and Politics</HEAD>
<HEAD>20 Years Of Black Politics: `Progress, Long Way From Parity'
^With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   They are a new breed of leaders, protesters turned politicians,
outsiders turned insiders, the powerless become powerful.
   Blacks are reshaping politics across America, calling the shots
today in towns where they risked beatings, cattle prods, jail and
even death a generation ago as they fought for the right to vote.
   Nationwide, almost 6,700 blacks held elected office last year,
more than four times that of 1970, according to the Joint Center
for Political Studies, a black-oriented think tank in Washiks now lead
four of the nation's six largest cities _ Tom
Bradley in Los Angeles, Eugene Sawyer in Chicago, Wilson Goode in
Philadelphia and Coleman Young in ngton.
   BlacDetroit. Thirteen other big
cities have black mayors, including Marion Barry of Washington,
D.C., and Andrew Young of Atlanta.
   Blacks have more than doubled their ranks in Congress in 20
years. And Jesse Jackson, a one-time lieutenant of Martin Luther
King Jr., is making surprising inroads among white voters in his
second White House bid.
   ``Twenty years ago, it would have been unthinkable,'' said U.S.
Rep. John Lewis of Georgia, a veteran civil rights activist.ch some
manufacturers of distilled spirits avoid a significant share of the
$12.50-a-gallon liquor tax by mixing some products with a
grape-based alcohol. This is expected to raise $360 million over
five years.
   The committee's bill does nothing about a 1986 law, also aimed
at tax evaders, that requires about 82,000 state, city and county
government units to pay taxes of 9.1 cents a gallon on their
gasoline and apply later for a refund. That provision took effect
Jan. 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880321-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1847EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-BlacksandPower Adv03-1stAdd   03-21 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Blacks and Power, Adv 03-1st Add,0838</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: had done.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Black power was to me a black version of ethnic American
politics,'' said Charles Hamilton, a Columbia University political
science professor and co-author with Carmichael of ``Black Power _
The Politics of Liberation in America.''
   ``We're talking about no more than what Italians have done, what
the Irish have done,'' he said. ``Before we almost had to
assimilate in order to achieve. I saw that as wrong. It denied
one's heritage.''
   Black power gave birth to a new sense of self-worth.
   ``What the black power movement was all about was you've got to
shed the negative image,'' Morris said. ``That's why you got (the
phrase) `black is beautiful.' There was a profound evaluation of
black people, of who they are.''
   ``It was a repudiation of the notion blacks had to judge their
own beauty and importance by white standards,'' he added.
   New styles and customs emerged, emphasizing black roots:
Afro-American names, mushrooming Afro hairdos and loose-fitting,
boldly patterned dashikis.
   One symbol _ the clenched fist _ stirred anger, and sometimes
fear. At the 1968 Mexico City Olympics, just six months after
King's assassination, sprinters Tommie Smith and John Carlos, the
gold and bronze medal winners in the 200-meter dash, raised
black-gloved fists high overhead as the national anthem was played.
For what they termed a display of black unity and protest of black
poverty, the two athletes were suspended by the U.S. Olympic
Committee.
   The symbols and words of black power shocked many whites, even
some who marched in civil rights demonstrations.
   Some ``found it extremely threatening,'' said Douglas McAdam,
associate sociology professor at the University of Arizona. To
them, ``it smacked of reverse racism _ no longer equality, but
black power, black domination.''
   McAdam has written a book chronicling how financial
contributions dropped when groups such as the Student Non-Violent
Coordinating Committee, a civil rights organization, shifted focus
from the fight for equality to more incendiary urgings.
   The movement also divided blacks. King, who preached non-violent
tactics, said the slogan carried the wrong connotations and was
potentially destructive.
   Separatism wasn't the answer, he argued, because blacks and
whites needed each other. ``There is no salvation for the Negro
through isolation,'' King wrote in his book, ``Where Do We Go From
Here: Chaos or Community?''
   ``He thought it was too divisive, too difficult to explain,''
Hamilton said. ``He was right.''
   Other black leaders and groups, including the NAACP, also
opposed the black power term, creating friction as two movements
competed for center stage.
   ``The civil rights movement was overrun,'' Walters said. ``Many
of its leaders would not join black power. ... More fundamentally,
it took away the allegiance of the people.''
   But academics also note that black leaders eventually supported
many of the movement's goals. King, in particular, embraced the
psychological need for black power and the importance of black
economic strength.
   After his assassination, the movement took new forms as some of
its causes became mainstream.
   ``Once blacks got the vote and began to elect more (blacks),
people began to believe they at least had channels,'' said Linda
Williams, senior political analyst at the Joint Center for
Political Studies.
   The black power movement also weakened as radicals were jailed
and the government cracked down; the FBI conducted a secret
campaign of ``dirty tricks'' involving faked Panther documents and
letters, informants and infiltrators.
   ``It was surprising to me the movement was destroyed so
completely,'' said Newton, Panther co-founder. Newton today
believes any gains made by the black power movement have been wiped
out.
   ``Black unemployment is very high,'' he said. ``Police actions
are as belligerent as ever. Overt racism is on the rampage as if
there never was a movement.''
   With the hindsight of 20 years, some criticize black power as
merely words without a program. Others say it left a strong legacy.
   Academics point to the growth of black-owned businesses,
newspapers and radio stations, as well as greater numbers of black
journalists and literature and arts programs.
   Others cite the thousands of black officeholders and Jesse
Jackson's strong presidential bid. ``Black power today is being
carried out in the electoral arena,'' Jennings sai.
   Universities offer hundreds of black studies programs, and
Hamilton credits the movement for the formation of such groups as
the Congressional Black Caucus.
   Still, the movement has not given all blacks power.
   ``In economics, there have been a lot of gains, but they've been
concentrated in the black middle class,'' said Clayborne Carson, a
Stanford University history professor and editor of the Martin
Luther King Papers Project.
   ``The group left out is the poor,'' he said. ``The irony is
that's who black power was supposed to help the most.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sharon Cohen is the AP Midwest regional
reporter, based in Chicago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 3</NOTE>
