<DOCNO> AP880321-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1849EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Blacks-Activists Adv03   03-21 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Blacks-Activists, Adv 03,0483</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Black Activists Of '60s: New Politics, New Lives, New Religion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Blacks And Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a rundown of some 1960s black activists and where they
are today:
   _ H. Rap Brown, who said ``violence is as American as apple
pie,'' is now a devout Muslim known as Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin. He
runs a convenience store in Atlanta.
   _ Huey P. Newton, who helped found the Black Panthers, lives in
Oakland, Calif., and says he lectures around the country about
``political philosophies'' and ``the realities of the 1960s.'' He
also said he is writing his memoirs.
   _ Eldridge Cleaver, one-time Panther information minister and
author of the acclaimed ``Soul On Ice,'' lives in Berkeley, Calif.
A Mormon and conservative Republican, Cleaver recently told Ebony
magazine he lectures to conservative groups and makes and sells
ceramic objects.
   In 1986, Cleaver unsuccessfully sought the Republican nomination
for the U.S. Senate in California.
   Cleaver fled the country for several years in the late 1960s
after a shootout between the Panthers and the police. He told Ebony
that after spending time in China, Algeria and North Vietnam he
ended his advocacy of communism and ``developed an understanding
and respect for free enterprise and the democratic political
system.''
   _ Stokely Carmichael, a former chairman of the Student
Non-Violent Coordinating Committee, whose chant of ``black power''
became a slogan for a movement, is now known as Kwame Toure and
travels between Guinea and the United States, said Charles
Hamilton, a political science professor at Columbia University.
Hamilton and Carmichael wrote a book together.
   Toure is a full-time organizer for the All-African Peoples
Revolutionary Party, working toward Pan-African socialist
principles, Hamilton said. Pan-Africanism is the unity of all
people of African descent.
   _ Bobby Seale, who also helped organize the Panthers, is working
for Temple University in Philadelphia as a community liaison for
the department of African American studies and a recruiter for
students for the college of arts and sciences.
   _ Marion Barry, first chairman of SNCC, is mayor of Washington,
D.C.
   Barry once dressed in dashikis and urged blacks not to celebrate
the Apollo moon landing because ``white America's money and
technology'' had not reached the inner city.
   A former chemistry teacher, Barry went to Washington for SNCC
and worked as a fund-raiser. He later ran a job-training program,
Pride Inc., and served on the Washington school board and city
council.
   _ John Lewis, also a one-time SNCC chairman, is a Georgia
congressman. A former member of the Atlanta City Council, Lewis was
among those leading a line of 600 marchers to the Edmund Pettus
Bridge in Selma, Ala., where officers clubbed, tear-gassed and
bull-whipped blacks trying to march to Montgomery in March 1965.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
