<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1407EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--ArtDeco-NightLife Adv03   03-21 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Art Deco-Night Life, Adv 03,0778</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv03
^AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 3
^With BC-APN--Art Deco</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new generation has discovered
``America's Riviera,'' replacing the glitz and glamour that faded
decades ago with rock music clubs, quaint restaurants and
neighborhood bars.
   Instead of Frank Sinatra, Sammy Davis Jr., Jerry Lewis or others
who frequented Miami Beach in the '50s and '60s, recent visitors
saw Mick Taylor and Ron Wood, Rolling Stones past and present, at
Woody's On The Beach. Others heard Stephen Stills and Savoy Brown
at the China Club, where Doobie Brothers jammed with Steely Dan,
and where rocker David Bowie, tennis star Vitas Gerulaitis and
former Beatles' producer George Martin were among the crowd.
   ``The night life plays a great role in the revitalization of the
entire community,'' says Mayor Alex Daoud, 44, a Miami Beach native
who can recall passing Clark Gable, Gary Cooper and Kirk Douglas on
the streets of his youth.
   ``One of the largest concerns people have is: `Where can I go at
night?' When I was growing up here, entertainment was very
expensive. Now we have more affordable entertainment, and also
family-oriented entertainment.''
   In less than five years, nearly 20 music clubs and restaurants
have sprung up in formerly rundown hotels, some deserted, others
occupied by the elderly poor or Mariel Cuban refugees.
   The first time David Giles, a British-born investment
consultant, walked into the future site of Woody's, ``there were
six guys on the floor doing crack cocaine. It was absolutely
derelict.''
   Months later, Giles, 37, welcomed 600 people who paid $100 to
$150 each to attend a New Year's Eve opening featuring the music of
Wood, a minority investor in a European ownership group assembled
by Giles.
   ``I still don't know if it will sustain itself, but the area
appears to have turned a corner,'' says Giles, who plans to expand
his club into a beach club with sauna, exercise facilities and a
gallery showcasing Wood's artwork.
   Jud Kurlancheek, city director of planning and zoning, says the
night life is ``a magnet for things that happen. It gets people to
come here, and they look around and decide they'd like to live
here.''
   Unlike in suburbia, where entertainment follows residential
development, the reverse appears true in urban areas, Kurlancheek
says.
   In the art deco district undergoing restoration as a national
historic area, the first wave brought upscale restaurants such as
the European-style cafe The Strand, and trendy music clubs such as
China Club, Woody's, Club Nu and the Tropics International. Now,
the neighborhood is adding the trappings of a settled-in
professional community: a sushi restaurant, chummy neighborhood
bars, an art deco-style Burger King and, soon, Domino's Pizza,
McDonald's and Wendy's fast-food restaurants.
   The average age of Miami Beach's 100,000 people dropped from 66
in 1980 to 54 in 1985 and is projected to be under 50 by 1980, says
Kurlancheek.
   ``Young people are happy to live blocks from the beach,'' says
Jeffrey Cohen, a partner in the China Club. ``The weather has
always been the finest on the continent and now, with the
resurgence of the young people, it's like a rediscovery.''
   The shift in entertainment tastes and the onset of jet travel to
the Caribbean and other competing resorts spelled the end to Miami
Beach's heyday in the '60s, Beach veterans say. The South Beach
area was hitting bottom by the time thousands of jobless Cubans
from the 1980 Mariel boatlift crowded in with the elderly Eastern
European immigrants who couldn't afford the condominium retirement
communities springing up in South Florida.
   Two efforts to gain legalization of casino gambling failed.
Finally, developers stopped looking for the ``quick fix'' and
instead concentrated on more lasting solutions such as widening the
eroded beach from 15 feet in places to 300, adding a boardwalk and
reviving interest in preserving art deco styles. At the same time,
tougher zoning ordinances forced landlords to make costly
improvements. The higher rents that resulted helped chase away many
of those responsible for raising the crime rates.
   Many involved in the night life comeback are people in their 30s
and 40s who have been interested in Miami Beach redevelopment for
years. Woody Graber, a Buffalo-born publicist who's been working
for redevelopment and art deco preservation since 1979, says he's
finally confident.
   ``People are finally realizing the potential. It's sort of like
helping people find a buried treasure,'' Graber says. ``This isn't
going to die; there's too much going on for it to die now.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
