<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--Niger-Glance Adv03   03-21 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Niger-Glance, Adv 03,0641</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv03</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 3</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Niger's Nomads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures on Niger:
   THE LAND: Located on the southern edge of the Sahara, between
Libya and Nigeria, Niger is a landlocked nation of 490,000 square
miles (the size of Texas and California combined), most of it
uninhabited desert.
   More than a century of French colonial rule ended peacefully on
Aug. 8, 1960. The Nigeriens adopted a constitution three months
later that was suspended following a military coup in 1974.
   THE PEOPLE: The population, estimated at 7 million, is largely
made up of three ethnic groups. The Hausa, who also constitute the
major ethnic group of northern Nigeria, represent half the total
population and the Djerma-Songhai, a quarter. Most are concentrated
in the southern, more fertile, part of the country. The rest of the
Nigeriens are nomadic or seminomadic peoples wandering the deserts
of the north, including the Tuareg, Fulani, Kanouri and Toubou.
Each ethnic group has its own language and customs but the Hausa
language is the one most widely spoken. Ninety-eight percent of the
population is Moslem. The birthrate is one of the world's highest,
increasing at 3.4 percent per year. The average life expectancy is
45.
   THE ECONOMY: Despite the development of uranium mining in recent
years, Niger remains a very poor country, 97 percent covered in
sand. Uranium output peaked in 1981 and declined after prices fell
owing to worldwide cuts in nuclear power programs. The falling
uranium prices caused the rate of economic growth to plummet from
12 percent in 1979 to 4.2 percent in 1985.
   Niger's gross national product per head declined, in real terms,
by an average of 1.6 percent annually between 1960 and 1981. Per
capita income in 1987 was estimated at $270 a year. The decline in
the economy combined with an exploding population and recurring
drought. Niger is thought to be the country that was most severely
affected by the 1984 drought and resulting food shortages.
   About 90 percent of Niger's work force is employed in some form
of agriculture or herding. The principal food crops are millet and
sorghum. The main cash crops are peanuts, cotton and cowpeas.
   HISTORY: The British were the first to explore the upper reaches
of the Niger River, beginning with the Scotsman Mungo Park, who
disappeared there in 1806. But it was the French who colonized it
between 1891 and 1911. The country was not fully ``pacified'' until
much later and there were a number of resistance movements which
challenged colonial power, the most serious being the siege of
Agadez by Tuareg nomad warriors in 1916-17.
   Its colonial history and development paralleled that of other
French West African territories, administered from Paris through
the governor general at Dakar, Senegal, and governors in the
individual territories. The country gained independence in 1960,
but remained staunchly pro-French.
   The constitution adopted in 1960 was suspended in April 1974
following a coup in which Seyni Kountche ousted Hamani Diori, who
had served since independence but was accused of corruption,
particularly with regard to the distribution of food aid.
   In November 1987, Kountche died in a Paris hospital following a
long illness and was immediately replaced by his chief aide and the
head of the 4,000-man Nigerien military, Ali Seibou.
   The country has been ruled since 1974 by a Supreme Military
Council and all basic powers have been vested in it. Political
parties are banned. A cabinet, composed of both civilians and
military personnel, administers the country. The government has
promised to reinstate a constitution and parliament.
   Niger pursues a neutral, moderate foreign policy and maintains
friendly relations with both East and West.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 3</NOTE>
