<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv03   03-21 0997</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 03,1035</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv03</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 3</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liliane Montevecchi is a French singer-dancer
whose cabaret show, ``On the Boulevard,'' opened in February and
keeps getting extended at the tiny off-Broadway Kaufman Theater.
   Whether she will let it extend into the summer, she can't say.
``I don't make plans. I do whatever pleases me.
   ``I'm like a cork on the ocean and just let it ride,'' she says
in French- accented English, her words punctuated by a hearty laugh.
   Her father was Italian, her mother French. She grew up in Paris.
She was the star of the Folies Bergere for 10 years. Minus the
feathers of the Folies, she's doing her first one-woman show.
   In ``On the Boulevard,'' she wears a black long-sleeved,
mini-skirted dress, accenting her gamine face, svelte figure and
shapely legs. After intermission, for a ``boulevard stroll,'' she
belts on a very French-looking trench coat. She bought it for $25
in a Salvation Army store near the Manhattan apartment where she's
staying. This ``cork on the ocean'' doesn't keep a permanent
apartment in Paris or New York.
   The songs in the show, sung mostly in English, aren't all
French. But the singer, whose name is pronounced Montevekky, makes
``It Might as Well Be Spring'' sound as French as ``Autumn Leaves.''
   Critic Clive Barnes called her ``an American-styled, but never
Americanized, impression of a reality that is itself so brilliant,
so telling and so touching that it becomes a new and lovely reality
in its own right.''
   Tommy Tune, who chose Miss Montevecchi for ``Nine'' on Broadway,
planned ``On the Boulevard'' with her, but his name isn't in the
program. She says, ``He did it for me as a friend. The critics were
so good he should have the recognition he deserves. I asked him and
he said, `Now that you're well on your way, do what you want.' It
is so brilliantly pulled together in that little theater, not an
easy theater to work with.
   ``The first time we came to the theater and sat there, he said,
`I see you higher.' We didn't know how yet. A boulevard was not
even thought of.'' They eventually decided on a raised, diagonal
walkway across the tiny stage.
   ``We were there, moved around, thought aloud, did boo-boos. It
was being unafraid to do things that are not good, then clean it
up. I always rehearse in a black leotard; I can see where the body
goes. We started with a leotard covered with diamonds I had from a
long time ago, for the show. It was too much.''
   They didn't try for a single mood, like nostalgia. ``We should
have variety,'' she says. ``Alive, alive, alive. And true. You
cannot cheat the public. They don't know why but they feel when it
is true. The public is very intelligent, you see.''
   Miss Montevecchi thinks her singing has improved. ``Life makes
you different, the sorrow, joy, people you lose. The songs are
closer to my heart and I'm not afraid any more. Tommy and I say we
are finished to be afraid. Now we attack!
   ``Tommy decided no more hats or glittering gowns. I attack with
pleasure. I feel very comfortable with that. I took a risk, I
guess. If one doesn't take a risk, one stays in a rut.''
   Tune first saw and heard the 5-foot-6-inch dancer-singer during
auditions for Broadway's ``Nine,'' which he directed.
   She had played in Atlantic City for 18 months, on contracts
renewed in three-month increments. From Atlantic City, she went to
Hollywood, where she once had a seven-year MGM contract, to try to
re-enter films.
   ``I didn't get a thing, not even a radio spot. I can't wait. I
try and if it doesn't work, I disappear. I decided to go back to
Paris. I stopped here, to visit a friend, and called my agent. He
said, `It's funny you called. Tomorrow there's an audition for a
play which requires accents.'
   ``I went there. I was not prepared at all. I didn't have a
pianist. I sang `La Vie en Rose.' Tommy liked me. He didn't have a
part for me but he wanted me in the show. Why not have me play the
part of a producer originally written for a man? Because of me, the
cast, except for Raul Julia, became all women.
   ``The timing of things is incredible.''
   In Paris, at age 9, Miss Montevecchi started ballet lessons,
sent by a mother who had wanted to be a ballerina. ``She didn't
push me too hard. I loved it. I still love it today. I go to ballet
class every day. It is my drug, my equilibrium, my love, what makes
me breathe.''
   Roland Petit saw Miss Montevecchi dance as a teen-ager, hired
her for his ballet company and three months later, when she was 18,
named her prima ballerina. She stayed three years before a screen
test took her to Hollywood, where she attended school with
kindergarteners to learn English.
   After Hollywood came ``La Plume de Ma Tante,'' on Broadway and
on tour; a play in Europe, and 10 years of starring in the Folies
Bergere, in New York, where it flopped, Las Vegas and Paris. She
wasn't topless, Miss Montevecchi says. ``Ballet is a very proper
thing and I always kept this. And I was the star of it, in 17
enormous costumes a night, with huge, huge feathers, from Catherine
of Russia to a tango queen.''
   Her mother died last year in Paris. Miss Montevecchi says, ``I
spent five months in Paris; I had to do things. I came back here
with her little dog that I bought her 12 years ago. I do this show
for her. She made me do it, in my heart and mind.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 3</NOTE>
