<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 27 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>South African Blacks Beginning to Move Up in Business, But ...</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An accompanying story is BC-Black Business-Taxis, b0651.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As an angry young man in the
1960s, Jackie Ntuane spent more than three years in prison for his
political activism.
   As a prosperous insurance executive today, he says his focus is
on economic independence.
   Ntuane is part of a growing black South African middle class,
which has found opportunities in the business world even while
locked out of national politics.
   This emerging business class, though still small, sees black
economic development as the neglected partner of black political
advancement. Both are viewed as necessary ingredients in
dismantling apartheid, the government's policies of racial
segregation.
   ``Economics and politics are part of the same struggle for
blacks,'' said Ntuane, who manages a 50-member branch office for
the Old Mutual insurance company.
   ``Blacks must succeed in both areas if they are to take control
of their own lives,'' added Ntuane, who was imprisoned for
belonging to the outlawed Pan Africanist Congress.
   The South African economy, by far the largest and most advanced
in Africa, requires an ever increasing number of middle-class
professionals. Blacks have begun to fill that demand, and some
clear signs of black economic progress are emerging:
   _Black households earned an average of 406 rand ($203) a month
in 1986, more than double the figure in 1981 and nearly six times
higher than in 1975, according to Market Research Africa, a private
firm. However, black households still earn less than 20 percent of
the average white family income.
   _The new Lesedi City shopping mall, east of Johannesburg, has
more than 50 black-run businesses and is the largest shopping
complex yet built in a black area.
   _Black taxi drivers, banding together in a nationwide
association, over the past decade have taken away a huge portion of
black commuter ridership from white-owned bus companies.
   _Shareworld, a Disneyland-style amusement park in Soweto, opened
several months ago and is believed the largest enterprise in the
country controlled by black shareholders. A total of 880 black
investors hold 60 percent of the stock.
   ``There are success stories, but they remain the exception,''
said Gabriel Mokgoko, spokesman for the National African Federated
Chamber of Commerce. ``Blacks still are not part of the economic
mainstream.''
   The middle class remains a small fraction of the country's 26
million blacks. Blacks make up about 75 percent of the population,
but only 5 percent of the executives and managers. Black businesses
account for only 1 percent of South Africa's gross national
product, according to Black Enterprise magazine.
   Black businesses face obstacles on several fronts, including
hostility from their own community, where many younger blacks see
the business world as an extension of apartheid and white
domination.
   ``Capitalism has become a discredited system to hundreds of
thousands of (black) South Africans,'' the editors of Black
Enterprise wrote recently. ``To many of our younger students and
graduates, even its name is an anathema (and) earns thinly
disguised ridicule and contempt.''
   Dr. Nthato Motlana, a prominent anti-apartheid activist, said
blacks have become increasingly hostile to business and have failed
to perceive black buying power as a political weapon.
   ``The attitude of young black activists and the unions is most
unfortunate,'' he said recently. ``This message must go out to the
political activists _ blacks need to make money too. Blacks have no
political power, but they should translate their consumer power
into economic power.''
   A long-held theory in the white business establishment is that
apartheid will wither as the economy develops and blacks are drawn
into the middle class.
   Business has proved less resistent to blacks than most other
fields, and the workplace is the most frequent point of multiracial
interaction in a country where neighborhoods and public schools
remain segregated.
   But black leaders say white business has done far less than it
could to assist blacks.
   ``White business climbed on the back of the apartheid political
system years ago and that's where it remains today,'' said Mokgoko.
``Business pays lip service to racial reform, but they have never
exercised their power to help dismantle apartheid or assist blacks
economically.''
   Blacks are the largest consumers of most basic necessities, such
as food and clothing, yet most black businesses are relatively
small operations limited to black townships.
   South Africa has no nationwide black-owned chains, and only one
of the more than 500 companies listed on the Johannesburg Stock
Exchange (a group of six bakeries) is run by blacks.
   ``Blacks have no credible representation in any of the major
economic sectors such as mining, agriculture, manufacturing, the
financial institutions, even retailing,'' Reuel Khoza, the black
managing director of Shareworld, wrote recently in Leadership
magazine.
   ``By whatever index we use, black economic activity is so
insignificant as to be almost non-existent,'' Khoza wrote.
   Economic life in Soweto, the huge township outside Johannesburg,
is typical of many black areas. Most shops are mom-and-pop
operations and a substantial informal business sector of street
vendors exists.
   But the township of an estimated 2.5 million people has no
large, central business district or shopping area. Soweto residents
are more likely to shop at white-owned businesses in Johannesburg
than in their neighborhoods.
   By far the largest industry in Soweto is shebeens, illegal bars
_ an estimated 4,000 of them, outnumbering all other businesses
combined.
   Black businessmen say the townships will remain underdeveloped
until bankers become willing to invest in black areas. South Africa
has more than 50 banks, but only one, the African Bank, is
black-run and makes most of its loans to the black community.
   ``Regulation and statute have reduced us to a nation of
small-time merchants running essentially one-man operations,''
Khoza wrote.
   ``Our political spirit has never been crushed, but our assault
on the economic edifice of apartheid has been lamentable,'' he
added. ``In the economic field, we must create a mythology of
competence, of high motivation and high ideals in pursuit of
economic liberation.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
