<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 27 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Black Taxi Drivers Take Road to Success in South Africa</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Black Business, b0650</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every workday morning and
evening, the road between Johannesburg and Soweto is lined with
vans taking blacks to and from their jobs.
   Known as ``combis,'' the vans are privately owned taxis that
have contributed to one of the country's leading black business
success stories.
   An estimated 100,000 combis operate nationwide, and almost all
are run by blacks for blacks.
   ``The black taxi industry is a clear example of the black
entrepreneurial flair that exists in South Africa when it is
allowed to flourish,'' said James Chapman, a white who is spokesman
for the Southern African Bus and Taxi Association (SABTA).
   For decades, most urban blacks were at the mercy of inefficient
and inconvenient train and bus systems for their daily trips from
the outlying townships into the cities where they worked.
   When black taxi drivers began appearing in the late 1970s, they
faced a range of restrictions, including limits on the number of
passengers and the requirement that those in each ride be of the
same race.
   But SABTA, a co-operative with 45,000 members, successfully
fought regulatory curbs and has become an increasingly powerful
force in the transport industry since its formation in 1979.
   SABTA has an annual budget of more than 60 million rand ($30
million), runs 16 gas and service stations for members, and
arranges discounts on parts and repairs. The organization also has
persuaded the Toyota and Nissan automotive plants in South Africa
to modify their vans to better accommodate the needs of taxi
drivers.
   Seventy percent of the association's members own only one or two
taxi vans, but most are doing well financially, SABTA says.
   Successful black taxi drivers in urban areas earn as much as
1,000 rand ($500) a month, making them among the highest-earning
black group in the country, said Godfrey Ntlatleng, the
association's vice president. The average monthly income for a
black household in South Africa is 406 rand ($203).
   ``I had to work a lot of 16-hour days, but I always wanted to be
my own boss,'' said Ntlatleng, who started with one taxi and now
oversees a fleet of several combis.
   To join SABTA, members pay an annual 100-rand ($50) fee, and
become part of the local association that sets rates and handles
administrative functions. The current fare for the trip between
Johannesburg and Soweto costs the equivalent of 60 cents and most
vans carry 10 or 15 passengers.
   SABTA's membership and resources have been expanding rapidly,
although the organization failed last year in an attempt to
takeover the nation's largest bus system, PUTCO, for 150 million
rand ($75 million).
   ``It was a temporary setback,'' said Chapman. ``But we've proven
we're a force to be reckoned with.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
