<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Blacks-Memphis Adv27   03-21 0926</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Blacks-Memphis, Adv 27,0952</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 27, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Memphis to Mark Anniversary of King Assassination</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Blacks and Politics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The shabby 64-room motel where Martin
Luther King Jr. died is closed, emptied of its last stubborn
resident, surrounded by a chain-link fence 8 feet high and awaiting
renovation. The slums are as full as ever.
   ``Dr. King was about the business of poor people at the time of
his death, and today there are more poor black people in Memphis
than there were then,'' said Maxine Smith, executive secretary of
the local NAACP.
   King was shot to death at The Lorraine Motel on April 4, 1968,
and civil rights leaders say the 20th anniversary of his
assassination should remind the nation that the battles he fought
remain unwon.
   ``The attention of the country should be on Memphis,'' said
James E. Smith, director of Local 1733 of the American Federation
of State, County and Municipal Employees.
   King was in Memphis to support striking city garbage men when he
was slain. On April 3, the union will sponsor a memorial service at
the Mason Temple, where he delivered one of his most famous
speeches.
   ``I've been to the mountain top,'' King told his followers the
night before his death. ``I may not get there with you, but I want
you to know tonight that we as a people will get to the promised
land.''
   A ``poor-people's pilgrimage'' through Mississippi, Alabama and
Georgia will begin April 4 in Memphis with a wreath-laying ceremony
at The Lorraine.
   A program of speeches and music to be staged at a downtown
theater April 4 will be the first event the city has ever sponsored
in King's honor.
   ``I think anybody who is familiar with Memphis politics, Memphis
society, would have thought you were crazy if you said five or 10
years ago that Memphis was going to sponsor an official city
tribute to Dr. King,'' said the Rev. Kenneth Whalum Jr., chairman
of a commission appointed by Mayor Richard Hackett to coordinate
the city program.
   ``It speaks volumes about the progress we have made,'' Whalum
said.
   The city and county governments have put up $2.2 million each to
match $4.4 million from the state for a civil rights museum at The
Lorraine, and museum supporters say it indicates Memphis is less
worried about being identified as the city where King was killed.
   ``There had to be time for people to realize that the impact of
the movement and Dr. King was not a passing moment,'' said D'Army
Bailey, a prime mover behind the project. ``The Lorraine didn't
become less important over the years. It became more important.''
   The city must recognize it has a special place in history
because King was killed here, he said.
   ``It is a remarkable challenge that we have to continually
answer to show we are making some progress toward racial and
economic justice,'' Bailey said. ``There is essentially a white
Memphis and a black Memphis, but I don't see that most other
American cities are any different. I think we are trying here.''
   Despite progress, however, other community leaders say racial
and economic divisions in Memphis are still sharp.
   ``We have a long way to go in healing the wounds of King's
assassination and in addressing racial polarization,'' said Willie
Herenton, superintendent of Memphis schools. He said conditions for
the hard-core poor had changed little in two decades.
   ``There's a lot of hopelessness and despair,'' he said.
   Jacqueline Smith, 37, who was forcibly evicted from The Lorraine
on March 2 after living there nine years, remains camped out on the
sidewalk in protest. The former Lorraine chambermaid and waitress
thinks the motel should be converted to a shelter for the homeless.
   ``I'm trying to help the people who live in this area,'' she
said as she was being evicted. ``We're being forced out'' of the
neighborhood.
   The U.S. Census Bureau says Memphis' population of 558,000 in
1968 was about 40 percent black. In 1987 the population was
estimated at 652,000 and 50 percent black.
   In 1970, the median income for blacks in Memphis was about half
that of whites, and a 1987 report on local poverty by the Shelby
County mayor's office says that margin has not lessened.
   Almost half of the black families in Memphis live in poverty,
the report says, and 79 percent of the children in city schools
live near or below the poverty level. Seventy-eight percent of the
107,000 students in the schools are black.
   ``If you look at the percentage of property ownership and things
like that, where the money is, blacks are still mainly on the
outside,'' said Charles Crawford, a history professor at Memphis
State University.
   But King's assassination in this city permanently changed the
city's racial attitudes.
   ``There was a feeling of real shock that it had happened and,
maybe like (President John) Kennedy's assassination in Dallas, that
it had happened here,'' Crawford said. ``It brought about a much
more sudden acceptance of the necessity of integration.''
   After King's death, blacks greatly increased their involvement
in city politics, Crawford said, and white politicians began taking
them more seriously.
   In 1967, the city's registered voters broke down to 152,562
whites and 78,655 blacks. Now, 181,539 whites, 175,395 blacks and
14,180 others are registered.
   Three of the 13 city council members are black, the same as 20
years ago, and four members of the 11-member Shelby County
commission are black.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
