<TEXT>
   Less than a week before insider trader Ivan F.
Boesky was to start serving a federal prison term, officials
declined to discuss his whereabouts and there were indications he
might already be in custody.
   The mystery Friday of the ex-financier's location came against a
background of death threats made against him, raising the
possibility that he might have sought federal protection prior to
his scheduled surrender date of March 24.
   Boesky, the central figure in Wall Street's biggest insider
trading scandal, was sentenced to a three-year prison term for
securities fraud.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has set a January court date in
Polaroid Corp.'s $5.7 billion patent infringement claim against
Eastman Kodak Co.
   Judge Rya Zobel on Friday set a Jan. 9, 1989, trial date in the
12-year-old case and ordered pre-trial evidence be presented to the
court on July 27.
   In 1985, Zobel ruled that Kodak had infringed on seven of about
150 Polaroid patents on instant cameras and film.
   Polaroid claims $3.2 billion in lost camera and film sales and
seeks an additional $2.5 billion for lost opportunities to develop
and market new products.
</TEXT>
