<HEAD>Beazer-Shearson Sweetens Offer For Koppers To $56 A Share From $45</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koppers Co.'s board of directors will consider
a sweetened buyout offer totaling about $1.5 billion from a group
led by British investor Brian Beazer and the firm Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc., the company says.
   The new offer disclosed Sunday of $56 for each of Koppers'
roughly 27.2 million common shares outstanding tops the group's
initial $45 a share offer that Koppers rejected as inadequate last
week.
   Koppers stock rose 12{ cents to $53.75 a share Friday in New
York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Charles R. Pullin, Koppers chairman, said that in addition to
considering the sweetened offer the construction materials and
chemical company would continue exploring ways to enhance
shareholder values.
   In rejecting the investor group's initial offer, Koppers' board
authorized management to examine defensive alterantives that might
include a recapitalization plan under which shareholders would
receive a substantial dividend payment while retaining equity in
the company.
   Pullin also reiterated a disclosure made last week in a
Securities and Exchange Commission filing that Koppers was engaged
in discussions with third parties regarding the possible sale of
the company's construction materials and services businesses.
</TEXT>
