<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Germany-Volkswagen     03-21 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Germany-Volkswagen,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germany to Sell its Stake in Volkswagen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany said Monday it will sell
its remaining shares in Volkswagen AG, returning to its
twice-delayed plans to privatize the government's stake in the
giant car company.
   The government will sell its 16 percent Volkswagen stake at 238
marks, or $140, a share beginning Thursday, according to a
statement by the Finance Ministry. The price set by the Finance
Ministry is a slight discount from Volkswagen's current cost of 240
marks a share.
   The government owns 4.8 million shares in the company, and
expects to make some 1.14 billion marks on the deal, the ministry
said.
   The shares will be sold through a consortium of 75 West German
and foreign banks led by Dresdner Bank, Deutsche Bank, Commerzbank
and others.
   West Germany announced plans to sell its Volkswagen stake more
than a year ago, but the move has been delayed twice in recent
months.
   The sale was delayed last summer after Volkswagen was hit by a
scandal in the company's foreign exchange division that cost
millions of marks.
   Plans to reschedule the sale for late in the year were shelved
shortly after the Oct. 19 stock market crash that sent share prices
plummeting around the world.
   Analysts say the government is going ahead with the transaction
now because it is faced with a wider-than-expected federal budget
deficit in 1988.
</TEXT>
