<DOCNO> AP880321-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1137EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Roper 1stLd-Writethru f0033 03-21 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Roper, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0033,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GE Boosts Bid For Roper; Files Suit Against Whirlpool</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: new throughout to UPDATE with GE filing suit, details; no
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. today boosted its bid for
Roper Corp. to $507 million and filed lawsuits seeking to block
Roper from merging with Whirlpool Corp.
   GE, which sweetened its bid by $9 a share, announced the new
$54-a-share tender offer today.
   The offer betters Whirlpool's second tender bid for Roper, made
last week, which amounts to $50 a share, or about $470 million.
GE's latest bid expires April 1, unless extended.
   Whirlpool's initial $37.50-a-share offer prompted the bidding
war for Augusta, Ga.-based Roper. On March 6, GE entered the fray
by offering to pay $45 a share for Roper's 9.4 million outstanding
shares.
   After jumping $5.75 a share on Friday, Roper stock had risen
another $2.625 a share on the New York Stock Exchange by midday.
   GE's lawsuit, filed in Delaware State Court, is the second wave
of legal action in the battle for the Augusta, Ga.-based appliance
and lawn equipment maker.
   On Friday, Whirlpool filed suit charging that GE tried to
``sabotage the definitive merger agreement Whirlpool reached with
Roper's board of directors last month.
   Moving aggressively, GE today alleged that the Roper board made
no effort to ``test the price'' before agreeing to merge with
Whirlpool on Feb. 29. GE charged that Roper concealed GE's interest
in the company when it advised shareholders to tender to Whirlpool.
   GE contends that it had expressed ``prior interest in acquiring
Roper and had asked to be informed if Roper became available for
acquisition.''
   The suit was filed against the Roper board and names Whirlpool
as a defendant.
   In a separate lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court in Delaware,
GE charged that both Whirlpool and Roper failed to adequately
disclose terms of their merger agreement under Securities and
Exchange Commission laws.
   GE said in a statement earlier that it would ``vigorously defend
itself'' against Whirlpool's charges that GE tried to ``sabotage''
the Whirlpool-Roper merger agreement. GE seeks to transfer that
suit from U.S. District Court in Grand Rapids, Mich., to federal
court in Delaware.
   In its lawsuit, Whirlpool charged that GE intentionally sought
to block Whirlpool's merger with Roper.
   Whirlpool alleged that the head of GE's appliance business
personally tried to persuade Roper to break its contract with
Whirlpool. The suit said GE ``intentionally, maliciously and
unjustifiedly engaged in a continuing course of conduct to
sabotage'' the deal.
   GE said in a statement today the suit ``grossly misstated the
facts and was totally without legal merit.'' GE noted that its
offer was made directly to shareholders who ``are not bound by the
acquisition agreement between Whirlpool and the Roper board.''
   Whirlpool said its suit is ``similar in theory'' to Pennzoil
Co.'s billion-dollar legal battle with Texaco Inc. over Texaco's
acquisition of Getty Oil Co. Texaco agreed to settle the suit for
$3 billion after Pennzoil won a $10.3 billion judgment against the
oil giant on charges that Texaco prompted Getty to back out of an
agreement with Pennzoil.
   Roper has been supportive of Whirlpool's efforts. Last week
Roper Chief Executive Officer Robert Cook said the company ``has a
strong desire to see this combination successfully completed.''
   Analysts say a Roper-Whirlpool merger will move Whirlpool ahead
of GE as the nation's leading appliance maker. Whirlpool has said
it would expand Roper from a maker of cooking ranges into a
producer and marketer of a full line of appliances.
   Roper reported net income of $24 million on sales of $703
million in fiscal 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
