<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1157EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Scotus-Petro-Lewis     03-21 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Petro-Lewis,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Lets Ruling Stand on Investors Suing Brokers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling
that makes it easier for investors to sue their brokers over the
collapse in 1984 of a $3 billion oil and natural gas investment
fund.
   The court, without comment, rejected appeals by three brokerage
firms seeking to force investors who lost money in the fund to sue
individually rather than as a group.
   The case stems from the collapse of the Petro-Lewis fund, in
which some 180,000 people purchased securities and limited
partnerships from 1970 to 1984. The average initial investment by a
limited partner was $8,600.
   Petro-Lewis' financial problems began when a supply glut caused
oil and gas prices to plummet in the early 1980s.
   The fund revealed in February 1984 that its condition was
critical, cutting partnership distribution by as much as 50 percent
and selling up to one-third of its reserves.
   That prompted numerous lawsuits against Petro-Lewis, and also
against brokers who helped market the fund.
   Some investors settled with Petro-Lewis, which set up a $23.5
million fund to handle the claims. But that agreement did not
preclude investors from suing their brokers.
   The investors said the brokerage houses and individual brokers
``knowingly or recklessly participated with Petro-Lewis in
disseminating misleading information'' about the financial
condition of the funds.
   At issue in the case acted on today is whether the investors can
maintain ``class action'' suits that permit them to apportion the
costs of fighting the case and divide up any court award.
   Robinson-Humphrey Co., Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and
Painewebber Inc. appealed a ruling by the 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals in Atlanta favoring the investors.
   The appeals court said investors who claimed they were defrauded
are arguing a common theory.
   They allege ``that the Petro-Lewis shares, which were not traded
on the open market, could not have been marketed but for the
defendants' fraud,'' the appeals court said.
   The appeals court rejected the brokers' argument that because
investors relied on information given them orally by different
brokers their claims should be tried separately.
   ``The complaints alleged that the defendant brokerage firms and
individual officers engaged in a common course of conduct to
misrepresent ... the financial condition of Petro-Lewis,'' the
appeals court said. ``These claims involve common issues that
clearly overwhelm the individual issues that may be present.''
   It would be repetitive, wasteful and an unnecessary burden on
the courts to require separate trials, the appeals court added.
   The cases are Robinson Humphrey vs. Sanders, 87-835, and
Painewebber vs. Parker, 87-836.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
