<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mostly
higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to reports
of real and rumored grain purchases by the Soviet Union.
   On Friday, the Agriculture Department targeted the Soviet Union
for 1 million metric tons of U.S. wheat under the Export
Enhancement Program.
   The USDA also announced late Friday that the Soviets had bought
500,000 metric tons of U.S. corn.
   Rumors early today that the Soviet Union had purchased some
South American soybean meal helped boost soybean futures, said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``That's not as friendly as if they'd bought U.S. meal but if
the rumors are correct, it shows that Russia is in the market for
meal again,'' Lespinasse said.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 2 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.01 a bushel; corn was 1 cent
to 1} cents higher with March at $1.99 a bushel; oats were \ cent
lower to 1} cents higher with March at $1.95} a bushel; soybeans
were 5{ cents to 7\ cents higher with March at $6.27 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .27 cent lower to .37 cent higher with April at
73.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .27 cent lower
with March at 81.85 cents a pound; hogs were .50 cent lower to .10
cent higher with April at 45.70 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .15 cent lower to .55 cent higher with March at 55.65 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed mostly higher on Friday.
