<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0315</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks fell broadly this morning in a spate of
selling that reflected what brokers called another dose of
post-crash anxiety, but volume slowed considerably after the first
hour of trading.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which hit the highest
level since the Oct. 19 collapse twice last week and flirted with
the 2,100-point barrier, fell 23.38 points to 2,063.99 by noon on
Wall Street.
   ``There are very nervous people out there,'' said Hank
Striefler, vice president on the trading floor at Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. ``Everybody is concerned. By reaching 2,100, that's
sort of a top for the Dow at the moment.''
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues fell 1.34 to 151.31. On the
American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 1.39 to 297.72.
   Losing issues outnumbered gainers by about 5-to-3 on the NYSE,
with 1,001 down, 394 up and 422 unchanged. Volume totaled 65
million shares in the morning session, less than half the 140.41
million shares traded Friday morning.
   Brokers said some of the selling pressure came from slumping
prices in the bond market, a sensitive barometer of inflation and
interest rates. Evidence of economic strength that emerged from
government reports last week suggested that inflation could
intensify, eroding the value of fixed-income investments.
   Among the most prominent losing blue-chips, IBM fell } to 113{,
DuPont fell 1| to 87[, Philip Morris fell 1] to 92} and Merck fell
1| to 158{.
   Takeover action buoyed some notable issues. Koppers rose 3 to
56} following another takeover offer of $56 a share from Beazer
PLC. American Standard rose { to 76| after Kelso said it would
consider an increase in its $78-a-share offer to thwart
counter-offers from rival Black & Decker.
