<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions March 26-27 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Company Specializes In Apparel For Nursing-Home Residents</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY HELEN GILLESPIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Claire Molloy sits in her
wheelchair mulling the possible purchase of a knit jogging suit
that just happens to be in lilac, currently her favorite color.
   ``What I really need are lilac sneakers,'' said the 65-year-old
resident of the Bartley Manor nursing home before tossing the
jogging suit back on the rack.
   She and other residents were choosing their spring wardrobes
over coffee and doughnuts in the nursing home's sunny recreation
room.
   The at-home shopping service is made available by Silverthreads
Inc., an Audubon, N.J.-based company that specializes in
health-care apparel.
   Silverthreads actually is a traveling store that sets up shop in
nursing homes in Delaware, Maryland, New Jersey, Pennsylvania,
Virginia and West Virginia. Its mail-order catalog serves other
customers, many of whom are cared for at home by their families.
   Silverthreads President Martin Misiaszek, who started the firm
10 years ago, said the company tries to provide its elderly
customers with everyday apparel such as nightgowns and dresses as
well as specialized apparel such as washable shoes for patients who
may be incontinent.
   ``What we try to do is bring a clothing store to a nursing
home,'' said Misiaszek, who has a degree in health-care management.
   Silverthreads treats its customers, most of whom are over 85
years old, with respect and understanding, he said.
   ``We all like to see what we're going to purchase, whether it
has two pockets or a belt. These people are no different,'' he said.
   While on the road, Silverthreads packs its inventory, racks,
bins and mirrors in a 20-foot truck. It's driven by Misiaszek's
younger brother, Bob, the company's vice president.
   Silverthreads' most popular lines are shirts, dresses and night
clothes that close in the back, and mens' pants with snaps on the
sides, he said.
   ``These are for people who can't dress themselves so nurses can
dress them,'' Bob Misiaszek said. ``It's a big help for nurses
aides.''
   Other speciality items include terry-cloth bibs with Velcro
snaps, flannel and corduroy lap wraps that tie around a wheelchair
patient's waist and cushy non-skid slippers for patients with foot
disorders.
   ``We try to have clothes that allow people to retain their
self-esteem,'' Bob Misiaszek said while straightening a bin filled
with dainty women's underwear and frilly nightgowns.
   Prices are range from $24 for cotton dresses with front zippers
to $16 for a two-piece jumpsuit.
   ``The prices are reasonable. We've been looking around and the
prices here are better than a department store,'' said Jerry
Schultz of Pine Beach, N.J.
   He and his wife, Jean, were shopping for new clothes for his
91-year-old mother, Amelia Schultz.
   ``This is ideal,'' he said. ``We can't take mother out to the
store and she should like what she's wearing.''
   Silverthreads also will put on fashion shows at the request of
nursing homes. The shows are a boost for patients and staff alike,
said Betty Maxwell, the recreation director at Bartley Manor.
   ``It's great. They can try them on right afterwards,'' she said
as some residents and their families clustered around racks of
dresses, slacks and other items.
   The Misiaszeks say annual sales are a family secret. They also
say Silverthreads provides more than a shopping service.
   ``It's really rewarding to see I'm making a difference. It
really has a lot of painful moments,'' Martin Misiaszek said. ``But
I love it. I wouldn't do anything else except win the lottery.''
   Mrs. Molloy never found her lilac sneakers, although there were
plenty in other colors.
   ``Nooooo,'' she said. ``Gotta be lilac.''
   She settled for a pair of pale yellow slacks, then decided to
browse a bit longer because ``I might find something else that
strikes my fancy. They have things here that we can really use.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions March 26-27</NOTE>
