<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BellResources     03-21 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bell Resources,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bell Resources Ends Bid for Holmes a Court's Bell Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERTH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bell Resources Ltd. on Monday withdrew its takeover
offer for Bell Group Ltd. following a bid for Bell Resources by two
investors.
   The investors, Sir Ronald Brierley's Industrial Equity Ltd. and
Kerry Packer's Consolidated Press Holdings Ltd., are jointly
offering 900 million Australian dollars, the equivalent of $665
million, for Bell Resources.
   Their offer, made last Thursday, was conditioned on Bell
Resources ending its offer for Bell Group. The companies are the
main listed concerns operated by Australian financier Robert Holmes
a Court.
   Bell Resources said the takeover offer was ``a material change
in circumstances'' that should be considered by the company and its
shareholders although Bell Resources considered the price
inadequate.
   Brierley and Packer were offering 1.50 Australian dollars a
share for Bell Resources. The company's stock closed at 1.57
Australian dollars in trading in Sydney Monday, indicating the
market expects the bid to be raised.
   On Feb. 29, Bell Resources offered one of its own shares plus 1
Australian dollar cash for each Bell Group share.
   The bid was seen by many analysts as a move to simplify Holmes a
Court's corporate structure after the October stock market crash,
to put togther Bell Resource's cash and investments with Bell
Group's industrial operations, and therefore to reduce Bell Group's
heavy borrowings.
   The move would give Holmes a Court cash. He owns 45 percent of
Bell Group, which in owns about 40 percent of Bell Resources.
   The takeover bid was criticized as too generous for Bell Group
shares and so to the disadvantage of Bell Resources shareholders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
