<DOCNO> AP880321-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1327EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BusinessInvestment     03-21 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Business Investment,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Investment To Rise 8.8 Percent, Survey Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investment in plant and equipment by U.S.
business is likely to increase about 8.8 percent this year but only
0.5 percent in 1989, according to a survey released Monday.
   Manufacturers are likely to lead the way this year with a 12.5
percent increase in investment, but trail in 1989 with a 2.9
percent decrease, Data Resources Inc. of Lexington, Mass., said.
   The larger non-manufacturing sector is expected to be more
stable, with a 6.6 percent increase this year and a 2.7 percent
increase in 1989, the survey said, based on answers from 457
companies.
   Companies were more optimistic about 1988 than in a previous
survey conducted just before the October stock market crash, when
they predicted overall investment in plant and equipment would rise
6.2 percent, according to Data Resources, a unit of McGraw-Hill Inc.
   Many economists say the stock market crash cooled off the
economy at a time when it was in danger of overheating and falling
into recession. Some are now pushing back the date of an expected
recession to 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880321-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1443EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     03-21 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,0707</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Monday by the Supreme Court in some business-related cases:
   
   DALKON SHIELD
   
   The court refused to let the Dalkon Shield's maker set up a $15
million emergency fund to help women who say the contraceptive
device left them infertile.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that blocks
creation of the fund pending the outcome of bankruptcy proceedings
for A.H. Robins, which manufactures the device.
   In a related case, the court refused to review a ruling that at
least temporarily barred some Dalkon Shield users from suing Aetna
Casualty & Surety Co., which insures A.H. Robins for liability
claims.
   The cases are Mabey vs. Official Committee of Equity Security
Holders, 87-1267, and Oberg vs. Aetna, 87-1208.
   
   EQUAL TIME
   
   The court rejected a constitutional attack on a federal law
requiring broadcasters to give equal time to opposing candidates
for public office.
   The justices, without comment, turned down the appeal of a
Sacramento, Calif., television reporter kept off the air while he
ran for a non-salaried town council seat.
   The case is Branch vs. FCC, 87-628.
   
   AGE BIAS
   
   The court, agreeing to decide an important issue for all
lawsuits alleging age bias in employment, said it will study the
case of a laid-off Pennsylvania man.
   The justices agreed to decide whether Eugene F. Brieck's lawsuit
against his former employer, Harbison-Walker Refractories, should
proceed to a jury trial.
   The case is Harbison-Walker vs. Brieck, 87-271.
   
   GOVERNMENT CONTRACTS
   
   The court agreed to consider killing a key provision of a law
designed to promote competitive bidding on government contracts,
setting the stage for a new ruling on the boundaries between
congressional and presidential powers.
   The court said it will hear Reagan administration arguments
challenging the comptroller general's role in administering the
1984 Competition in Contracting Act.
   The case is Army Corps of Engineers vs. Ameron, 87-163.
   
   SALES TAX
   
   The court agreed to decide whether states may impose sales taxes
on most books, newspapers and magazines while exempting religious
publications.
   The justices said they will review a Texas court ruling that
said such a tax neither violates equal-protection rights nor
breeches the constitutionally required separation of church and
state.
   The case is Texas Monthly vs. Bullock, 87-1245.
   
   CABLE RATES
   
   The court refused to let states and local governments regulate
the prices most of the nation's cable television operators charge
for basic service.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that the
deregulation effected in 1986 by Congress and the Federal
Communications Commission left subscribers vulnerable to illegal
monopoly pricing.
   
   The case is Connecticut vs. FCC, 87-671.
   
   The court agreed to examine the power of labor unions to fire
elected officials for disagreeing with union policies.
   The court said it will consider killing a lawsuit by a Los
Angeles area union business representative who said he was fired
illegally by the Sheet Metal Workers' International Association.
   The case is Sheet Metal Workers vs. Lynn, 86-1940.
   
   SUPERFUND
   
   The court agreed to consider shielding states from having to
help pay for cleaning up hazardous waste sites when the federal
government sues businesses under the so-called Superfund law.
   The court said it will hear arguments by Pennsylvania officials
that exposing states to such liability could saddle them with $100
billion in clean-up costs.
   The case is Pennsylvania vs. Union Gas, 87-1241.
   
   RICO
   
   The court agreed to consider making it easier for people to use
a federal anti-racketeering law to sue businesses.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by phone customers in
Minnesota who have accused Northwestern Bell Telephone Co. of
trying to bribe state public utility officials.
   The phone subscribers sued the company under a law known as the
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO).
   The case is H.J. Inc. vs. Northwestern Bell, 87-1252.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880321-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1521EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AmericanStandard     03-21 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American Standard,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kelso Prepared To Raise Bid For American Standard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kelso & Co. expects to decide by the end of this
month whether to sweeten its $2.5 billion tender offer for American
Standard Inc. to fend off rival bidder Black & Decker Corp.,
according to a report published Monday.
   American Standard, a New York-based plumbing and air
conditioning company, on Thursday accepted Kelso's $78-a-share
offer. But the following day, Black & Decker raised its bid for
American Standard to $77 a share from $73.
   The Kelso offer began Monday and was scheduled to expire at
12:01 a.m. EST April 1. Black & Decker extended its offer to expire
on the same day.
   Despite the fact that Kelso's bid is about $30 million higher,
Black & Decker has maintained that its proposal is better ``in
light of the timing and probability of payment.''
   Black & Decker, a Towson, Md.-based tool and appliance maker, is
hoping to benefit from nervous arbitrageurs who hold a majority of
American Standard's stock and worry that Kelso might not be able to
come up with the financing to complete the transaction.
   Tendering their shares to Black & Decker still would ensure a
premium price for American Standard's stock, which by late
afternoon Monday traded at $76.50 a share, up 87.5 cents, on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Kelso, however, said it was willing to raise its bid to win over
shareholders, according to Monday's editions of the Wall Street
Journal.
   ``We didn't come this far to be deterred by this kind of
response,'' Joseph Schuchert, Kelso's managing partner, told the
newspaper. ``We'll tender at $78 and see what they do. If it's
necessary to bump our tender offer, that's what we'll do.''
   He said Kelso was unlikely to act until March 31.
   Kelso officials did not return numerous telephone calls from The
Associated Press on Monday.
   Kelso specializes in leveraged buyouts involving employee stock
ownership plans, or ESOPs, a concept it pioneered about 30 years
ago.
   In a leveraged buyout, a company is acquired largely through
borrowed money repaid from the target company's profits or sale of
assets. ESOPs also are financed mostly with borrowed funds, but
equity is divided among all of the company's workers, not just a
few investors.
   Kelso said it planned to finance the American Standard
acquisition through a $250 million investment and several bank
loans.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
