<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks fell today in a spate of selling that
reflected another dose of post-crash anxiety and falling prices in
the bond market, a warning signal of higher interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which hit the highest
level since the Oct. 19 collapse twice last week and flirted with
the 2,100-point barrier, fell 21.89 points to 2,065.48 by 3 p.m. on
Wall Street.
   ``There are very nervous people out there,'' said Hank
Striefler, vice president on the trading floor at Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. ``Everybody is concerned. By reaching 2,100, that's
sort of a top for the Dow at the moment.''
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues fell 1.39 to 151.26. On the
American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 1.61 to 297.50.
   Losing issues outnumbered gainers by more than 2-to-1 on the
NYSE, with 1,106 down, 427 up and 419 unchanged. Volume totaled
107.07 million shares with an hour left, a considerably slower pace
than in the two previous sessions.
   Brokers said some of the selling pressure came from slumping
prices in the bond market, a sensitive barometer of inflation and
interest rates.
   Evidence of economic strength that emerged from government
reports last week suggested that inflation could intensify, eroding
the value of fixed-income investments and dampening hope of an
easier monetary policy by the Federal Reserve.
   Among the most prominent losing blue-chips, IBM fell } to 113{,
DuPont fell 1 to 87}, Philip Morris fell 1] to 92} and Merck fell
1| to 158{.
   Takeover action buoyed some notable issues. Koppers rose 3} to
57{ following another offer of $56 a share from Beazer PLC.
Pillsbury rose | to 43| on persistent speculation about unannounced
offers for the company. Federated Department stores, target of
rival takeover offers from R.H. Macy and Campeau, rose | to 66~.
