<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Steel,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Output Rose 1.2 Percent in Week Ended March 19</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel production rose to 1.991 million tons in
the week ended March 19, an increase of 1.2 percent from the
previous week's 1.967 million tons, the American Iron and Steel
Institute reported Monday.
   The industry's production amounted to 92.7 percent of capacity
during the week, compared with 91.6 percent in the previous week.
   Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at
21.726 million net tons, an increase of 34.8 percent from the
16.115 million net tons in the previous year. The steel operations
of USX Corp., the nation's largest steel producer, were shut down
by a strike during the first month of 1987.
   Production so far this year used 89.7 percent of capacity,
compared with 67.0 percent a year earlier.
   Net tonnage by district for the week ended March 19: Northeast
Coast, 277,000; Pittsburgh, 203,000; Youngstown, 131,000; Lake
Erie, 164,000; Detroit, 159,000; Chicago, 553,000; Midwest,
176,000; Southern, 225,000; and Western, 103,000.
