<HEAD>Soybean, Corn Futures Close Higher; Wheat Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices closed higher
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade, while wheat prices fell.
   Soybean futures gained as much as 7\ cents a bushel. Prices rose
early on rumors of new Soviet buying and got a boost later in the
day when the South American agricultural newsletter Safras y
Mercado dropped its Brazilian soybean crop estimate by 400,000
metric tons due to dry weather in an important soybean region.
   Wheat futures retreated on profit-taking by traders who had
purchased contracts after the Agriculture Department's announcement
late Friday that it had targeted the Soviet Union for 1 million
metric tons of wheat under the Export Enhancement Program.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents lower to { cent higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $2.97\ a bushel; corn was 2\
cents to 3{ cents higher with March at $2.01\ a bushel; oats were 5
cents lower to { cent higher with March at $1.91 a bushel; soybeans
were 5 cents to 7\ cents higher with March at $6.27 a bushel.
