<DOCNO> AP880321-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1942EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Franco-GermanCouncil     03-21 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Franco-German Council,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Both Sides Praise First Meeting of Franco-German Economic Council</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German and French finance
ministers praised the first meeting of their bilateral economic
council Monday and pledged to boost cooperation on monetary issues.
   The ministers said they did not talk about proposals for a
European central bank during their landmark meeting, but agreed to
meet again before the summer, in Paris.
   Gerhard Stoltenberg, the West German finance minister, said
Monday's meeting reviewed economic developments in the two nations,
analyzed budget and tax plans and began examining ways of boosting
cooperation in monetary policy.
   French Finance Minister Edouard Balladur also praised the
session, and said he was pleased with Franco-German economic
cooperation, particularly the close contact between the two
nations' central banks.
   ``I am especially happy about the excellent cooperation that has
existed between the Bundesbank and the Banque de France,'' he told
reporters after the three-hour session.
   The Franco-German Economic Council was established in January as
a way of better coordinating policy between the two neighboring
nations.
   The council is to meet four times a year, and comprise the
nations' finance and economics ministers and the heads of the two
central banks.
   West Germany's central bank president, Karl Otto Poehl, is known
to have been skeptical about the council because of fears that it
may infringe upon his Bundesbank's independence.
   But Poehl praised Monday's session, and said the council would
help Europe achieve its goal of a barrier-free internal market by
1992.
   Both Stoltenberg and Balladur said the council would work to
better coordinate 1988 budgets in both nations, and concentrate on
seeking ways of achieving economic growth.
</TEXT>
