<2ND_LINE>AM-Roper, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0166,0807</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GE Boosts Bid For Roper; Challenges Roper-Whirlpool Merger
Agreement In Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf with 2 grafs to UPDATE with Roper studying GE
bid and closing stock price; picks up 5th graf pvs: GE's two ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. launched a double-pronged
attack Monday in its bid for Roper Corp. by boosting its tender
offer to $507 million and filing lawsuits challenging Roper's
agreement to merge with Whirlpool Corp.
   GE's latest bid, up $9 a share to $54 for Roper's outstanding
stock, surpasses the $50-a-share sweetened bid Whirlpool made last
week for the appliance and lawn equipment maker.
   In the second wave of lawsuits filed in the hotly contested bid
for Augusta, Ga.-based Roper, GE charged that Roper's board failed
to act in the best interest of shareholders and, together with
Whirlpool, violated federal disclosure laws.
   In a statement issued after the stock market closed, Roper said
it is reviewing GE's new tender offer and plans to hold a board
meeting later in the week to determine the company's position on
the sweetened bid.
   Roper rose $2.50 a share in composite New York Stock Exchange
trading to close at $55.50 a share. Roper jumped $5.75 a share on
Friday.
   GE's two lawsuits, filed in separate courts in Delaware, counter
a suit filed Friday in which Whirlpool accused GE of trying to
``sabotage'' the definitive merger agreement Whirlpool reached with
Roper's board of directors on Feb. 29.
   GE said in court papers it contacted Robert Cook, Roper's
president and chief executive officer, about a possible acquisition
in November but was turned down.
   Three months later, Roper's board authorized a $37.50-a-share
merger with Whirlpool after Whirlpool threatened to mount a hostile
takeover bid, papers filed in Delaware State Court showed.
   GE, which entered into the fray March 6 with a $45-a-share
offer, charged that Roper failed to ``test the price'' before
agreeing to merge with Whirlpool. GE also charged that Roper
concealed GE's interest in the company when it advised shareholders
to tender to Whirlpool.
   In an attempt to ``lock up'' its agreement with Whirlpool, Roper
gave the Benton Harbor, Mich.-based company an option to purchase
1.6 million newly issued shares for $37.50 if the deal fell
through, a move GE charged would make any subsequent Roper
acquisition more expensive. GE is seeking to block the issue and
transfer of those shares.
   In a separate suit filed in U.S. District Court in Delaware, GE
charged that both Whirlpool and Roper failed to adequately disclose
terms of their merger agreement under Securities and Exchange
Commission laws and neglected to mention GE's interest in Roper.
   Whirlpool, which threw the battle into the courtroom on Friday,
alleged in its suit that a GE executive personally tried to
persuade Roper to break its contract with Whirlpool. The suit said
GE ``intentionally, maliciously and unjustifiedly engaged in a
continuing course of conduct to sabotage'' the deal.
   Part of Whirlpool's lawsuit seeks $117 million in damages, or
the difference between its $50-a-share offer and original offer.
   GE vowed to ``vigorously defend itself'' against the charges and
seeks to transfer the suit from U.S. District Court in Grand
Rapids, Mich., to federal court in Delaware.
   Whirlpool said its suit is ``similar in theory'' to Pennzoil
Co.'s legal battle with Texaco Inc. over Texaco's acquisition of
Getty Oil Co.
   Texaco agreed to settle the suit for $3 billion after Pennzoil
won a $10.3 billion judgment against the oil giant on charges that
Texaco prompted Getty to back out of an agreement with Pennzoil.
   Roper has been supportive of Whirlpool's efforts. In endorsing
Whirlpool's sweetened bid last week, Roper's Cook said the company
``has a strong desire to see this combination successfully
completed.'' He had no further comment when contacted Monday.
   Analysts say a Roper-Whirlpool merger would move Whirlpool ahead
of GE as the nation's leading appliance maker. Whirlpool has said
it would expand Roper from a maker of cooking ranges into a
producer and marketer of a full line of appliances.
   But the acquisition of Roper would help GE secure its position
in the gas stove market and enhance its supplier relationship with
Sears, Roebuck & Co.
   Long limited to electric ranges, GE decided a year ago to widen
its market share by selling gas stoves. Since then GE has purchased
gas stoves from four companies, including Roper, said GE spokesman
Jack Batty from the company's headquarters in Fairfield, Conn.
   In addition, analysts estimate that roughly two-thirds of
Roper's sales come from its agreement to supply Sears with its
kitchen appliance and lawn equipment products.
   Roper reported net income of $24 million on sales of $703
million in fiscal 1987.
</TEXT>
