<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bid,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Of New York Gets SEC Approval, Begins Irving Tender Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of New York Co. said Monday it was
beginning a $1.08 billion tender offer for Irving Bank Corp. after
having received approval to make the bid from the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
   The SEC approved the registration statement on Friday, allowing
Bank of New York to issue its prospectus, Bank of New York
spokesman Owen Brady said.
   Irving spokesman David Santos dismissed the development as
``pretty much a non-event.''
   Bank of New York began its hostile attempt to acquire Irving
last September, a struggle that has been widely followed by bankers
because unfriendly takeovers are unusual in the banking industry.
Its tender offer expires at midnight on April 15.
   Irving's board last week amended its anti-takeover plan to make
it harder for a slate of new Irving directors to scuttle rights if
they win a proxy fight at Irving's annual meeting April 21.
   Bank of New York already has nominated a 16-director slate to
compete with Irving's slate at the meeting. The bank said it would
fight Irving's amended anti-takeover plan in the courts.
</TEXT>
