<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1803EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-21 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0798</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platinum Futures Crack $500 Barrier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures prices surged above $500 a troy ounce Monday,
helped by early gains in oil prices and a generally positive
economic outlook.
   Oil prices settled mixed, however. On other markets, gold and
silver futures advanced; soybean futures were sharply higher while
the grains were mixed; livestock and meat futures were mixed; and
stock-index futures retreated.
   The contract for April delivery of platinum settled $6.90 higher
at $504.20 on the New York Mercantile Exchange. The move marked
only the second time since Jan. 20 that the April platinum contract
has finished above the psychologically important $500 barrier.
   Analysts said gains Monday in all the precious metals _
platinum, gold, silver and palladium _ were driven primarily by a
sharp increase in crude oil futures prices early in the day.
   But when oil prices later fell steeply, the metals gave up only
some of their gains, indicating other supportive factors were at
work.
   The weak dollar, increased U.S. auto sales and the generally
positive tone of recent economic data are all bullish for metals
prices, said Jacques Luben, executive director of investments for
the Platinum Guild International.
   ``It seems as though the consensus is that interest rates will
remain relatively low for the remainder of the year, we may see
higher inflation and we probably won't see a recession this year,''
Luben said.
   Monday's performance was ``a reassuring vote of confidence for
the metals'' but the next few sessions will show just how deep that
confidence runs, said Jack Barbanel, director of futures trading
for Gruntal & Co. in New York.
   ``We're either at the early stage of some new buying momentum or
we're seeing an upside correction in a downside metals market,'' he
said.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled $4.90 to $7.20
higher with April at $449.20 a troy ounce; silver was 8 cents to
10.3 cents higher with March at $6.447 a troy ounce.
   Crude oil's early jump above $17 a barrel on the New York
Mercantile Exchange was triggered partly by speculation that OPEC
President Rilwanu Lukman would announce a meeting of OPEC's pricing
committee at a Tuesday news conference, said Nauman Barakat, an
analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   But prices came tumbling down later in the session when Saudi
Arabia's King Fahd confirmed the country was ``offering discounts,
quite indiscriminately, to almost everybody,'' Barakat said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 9 cents lower to 8
cents higher with April at $16.49 a barrel; heating oil was .12
cent lower to .35 cent higher with April at 45.40 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was unchanged to .12 cent higher with April at
46.11 cents a gallon.
   Soybean and corn futures settled sharply higher on the Chicago
Board of Trade while wheat prices fell.
   Soybean futures rose early in the session on rumors of new
Soviet buying and got a boost later in the day when the
agricultural newsletter Safras y Mercado dropped its Brazilian
soybean crop estimate by 400,000 metric tons due to dry weather,
said Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Wheat settled 2} cents lower to { cent higher with March at
$2.96\ a bushel; corn was 2{ cents to 4} cents higher with March at
$2.01{ a bushel; oats were 5{ cents lower to { cent higher with
March at $1.90{ a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents to 10 cents higher
with March at $6.30 a bushel.
   Frozen pork belly futures settled sharply lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange while livestock futures were mixed.
   The drop in pork belly futures was largely due to expectations,
later confirmed, of a sharp increase in bellies in cold storage.
The USDA announced after the close that nearly 67 million pounds of
pork bellies were stored in the nation's freezers on Feb. 29,
compared to 34.7 million pounds a year ago.
   Sharply lower cash hog prices weighed on the livestock futures,
said Walter Kowalski, an analyst in Chicago with Lind-Waldock & Co.
   Live cattle settled .12 cent lower to .50 cent higher with April
at 73.65 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .10
cent higher with March at 82.70 cents a pound; hogs were .65 cent
lower to .10 cent higher with April at 45.55 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were unchanged to 1.70 cents lower with March at 54.10
cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for June delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settled 1.7 points lower at 270.60.
</TEXT>
