<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 1851EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-EconomyRdp     03-21 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy Rdp,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Markets Mixed to Lower as Government Reports Budget Deficit for
February</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government chalked up a $23.9 billion deficit in its
February spending after posting a rare budget surplus in January,
the Treasury Department reported Monday.
   Meanwhile, stock prices fell in the slowest trading of the year,
while the dollar followed suit and oil prices were mixed.
   The Treasury's latest monthly report on the government's
spending and revenues followed a $16.1 billion surplus in January
which had occurred because Social Security checks that month were
mailed early and counted in the December spending figures.
   So far this fiscal year, the government has run up a five-month
deficit of $89.7 billion, 4.9 percent lower than the red ink
incurred in the same period a year earlier.
   The Reagan administration is projecting a deficit of $146.7
billion for the fiscal year ending Sept. 30, down 2.4 percent from
the $150.4 billion deficit in 1987.
   But many forecasters believe the small improvement will not be
realized because they think the administration has used overly
optimistic projections about the economy.
   On Wall Street, inflation fears and lingering post-crash anxiety
sent stocks tumbling across the board, with the Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials dropping sharply at the opening and remaining
down throughout the trading session.
   The closely watched indicator closed at 2,067.14, down 20.23
points. Broader market indices also fell.
   Trading was also quiet on world currency markets. The dollar
fell against all major currencies except the Canadian dollar,
mirroring the stock market selloff and a decline in bond prices.
   Gold prices jumped as much as $5 a troy ounce in active trading,
spurred by a rally in oil prices. Republic National Bank of New
York quoted a bid price for gold of $449.45 a troy ounce as of 4
p.m. EST, up from $444 an ounce late Friday.
   Gold prices moved in concert with crude oil futures prices,
which pierced the $17-a-barrel level before sliding back in late
trading, following a statement by Saudi King Fahd on prices and
production.
   In remarks carried by the official Saudi press agency, Fahd
suggested that cheating on production quotas and prices by some
members of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries encouraged further weakness in prices.
   That punctured a rally on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
where contracts for April delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark U.S. crude oil, closed at $16.49 per 42-gallon barrel,
down 9 cents from Friday. They had been up as much as 45 cents
during the day.
   Among refined products for April, wholesale heating oil closed
0.35 cent higher at 45.40 cents a gallon, after having touched
46.70 cents a gallon earlier. Unleaded gasoline gave up a 1.41-cent
gain to close 0.12 cent higher at 46.11 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
