<DOCNO> AP880321-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 2128EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CampbellLabels     03-21 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campbell Labels,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campbell To Change Long-Time Label _ But Only On Cooking Soups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campbell Soup Co. is replacing the
red-and-white labels on ``cooking soups'' used primarily as recipe
ingredients, but plans to keep the familiar 90-year-old design on
its eating soups, the company said Monday.
   The new labels will feature color photographs of meals that can
be made from recipes using Campbell's 16 varieties of cooking
soups, according to company spokesman Kevin Lowery.
   The recipe for the pictured meal will be printed on the
underside of the label along with another recipe and a cookbook
offer.
   The traditional red-and-white label was born in 1898, when a
Campbell executive was so inspired by the colors in Cornell
University's new football team uniforms that he ordered the change
from the previous orange-and-black label, Lowery said.
   The red-and-white label went on to win the Gold Medallion for
Excellence at the 1900 Paris Exposition and was immortalized in pop
art by the late Andy Warhol.
   Cooking soups, such as chicken broth, cream of mushroom and
tomato, constitute one-third of Campbell's market.
   Campbell initially will use the new labels on cans produced and
sold in nine western states, where the company will judge consumer
reaction.
   The company indicated the change, the product of one year's
research, could help consumers by saving shopping time and aiding
menu planning.
</TEXT>
