<DOCNO> AP880321-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 2343EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Borg-Warner     03-21 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Borg-Warner,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Borg-Warner Sells Credit-Reporting Subsidiary to TRW</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Borg-Warner Corp. has sold its credit-reporting
subsidiary, Chilton Corp., to TRW Inc. for about $360 million in
cash, the companies announced Monday.
   Borg-Warner said it sold Dallas-based Chilton, which it acquired
in March 1986 for $252 million, to help pay off debt incurred in
its 1987 leveraged buyout.
   Borg-Warner went private last year in the buyout led by a
Merrill Lynch & Co. unit and must pay off $1.7 billion in debts by
the end of 1988. The buyout, which was engineered to avert a
hostile takeover by GAF Corp., left Borg-Warner with total debt of
more than $4 billion.
   TRW Chairman Ruben F. Mettler said in a statement issued in
Cleveland that the acquisition fits into TRW's previously announced
strategy of increasing its presence in the commercial information
systems business.
   The sale of Chilton leaves Borg-Warner with interests in
chemicals and plastics, automotive parts and security and armored
guard services. Borg-Warner already has divested itself of other
assets, including its BWAC Inc. finance unit and its industrial
products group, to pay off debt incurred in the buyout.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
